INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which of the following best describes Oracle Cloud Infrastructure (OCI) as a cloud platform?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"A purely on-premises infrastructure solution managed by Oracle on the customer's behalf"},{"id":"b","text":"A second-generation cloud platform that offers Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS) capabilities"},{"id":"c","text":"A cloud platform that exclusively provides managed database services"},{"id":"d","text":"A private cloud solution that can only be deployed within Oracle's headquarters data centers"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$OCI is Oracle's second-generation cloud platform providing IaaS, PaaS, and SaaS offerings across globally distributed data centers. It is not limited to on-premises deployments, databases, or a single location. The 'second-generation' design emphasizes isolation of compute resources through dedicated bare-metal servers and improved security architecture compared to first-generation cloud designs. Options a, c, and d are all overly restrictive and do not accurately characterize OCI's broad service portfolio.$patch$, $patch$OCI Introduction$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/GSG/Concepts/baremetalintro.htm","label":"Oracle Cloud Infrastructure Documentation – Overview"},{"url":"https://education.oracle.com/oracle-cloud-infrastructure-2025-foundations-associate/pexam_1Z0-1085-25","label":"OCI Foundations Associate Exam Topics (1Z0-1085-25)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '1Z0-1085-25'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which of the following best describes Oracle Cloud Infrastructure (OCI) as a cloud platform?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An OCI Region is composed of one or more Availability Domains (ADs). What is the primary purpose of having multiple Availability Domains within a single OCI Region?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"To provide separate billing accounts for different departments within the same organization"},{"id":"b","text":"To allow customers to deploy resources in different countries simultaneously"},{"id":"c","text":"To provide physical isolation between data centers, enabling high availability and fault tolerance within the same geographic region"},{"id":"d","text":"To divide compute and storage resources so that they cannot communicate with each other"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Availability Domains are one or more data centers located within a region that are connected to each other by a low-latency, high-bandwidth network. Each AD is isolated from the others to prevent correlated failures. This physical isolation enables customers to design highly available and fault-tolerant architectures within the same region. Option a is incorrect because billing is managed at the tenancy level, not per AD. Option b is incorrect because multiple ADs are within the same geographic region, not different countries. Option d is incorrect because ADs are connected and resources can communicate across them.$patch$, $patch$OCI Introduction$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/General/Concepts/regions.htm","label":"OCI Docs – Regions and Availability Domains"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '1Z0-1085-25'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An OCI Region is composed of one or more Availability Domains (ADs). What is the primary purpose of having multiple Availability Domains within a single OCI Region?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In OCI, what is a 'Fault Domain' and how does it relate to Availability Domains?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"A Fault Domain is a separate geographic region used for disaster recovery outside the primary region"},{"id":"b","text":"A Fault Domain is a logical grouping of hardware and infrastructure within an Availability Domain that acts as a separate failure boundary"},{"id":"c","text":"A Fault Domain is the same thing as an Availability Domain, just a different name used in older OCI documentation"},{"id":"d","text":"A Fault Domain is an OCI service that automatically backs up data across multiple regions"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Each Availability Domain contains three Fault Domains. A Fault Domain is a grouping of hardware and infrastructure within an AD designed to provide an additional layer of failure isolation. Resources placed in different Fault Domains do not share physical hardware such as power supplies or network switches, reducing the risk of simultaneous failures. Option a is incorrect because Fault Domains are within a single AD, not separate regions. Option c is incorrect because Fault Domains and Availability Domains are distinct concepts at different scopes. Option d is incorrect because Fault Domains are not a backup service.$patch$, $patch$OCI Introduction$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/General/Concepts/regions.htm#fault","label":"OCI Docs – Fault Domains"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '1Z0-1085-25'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$In OCI, what is a 'Fault Domain' and how does it relate to Availability Domains?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which OCI service category would you use if you wanted to run your own custom application code without managing the underlying virtual machine operating system patching or server hardware?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) – Bare Metal Compute"},{"id":"b","text":"Platform as a Service (PaaS) – such as Oracle Container Engine for Kubernetes or Oracle Functions"},{"id":"c","text":"Software as a Service (SaaS) – such as Oracle Fusion Applications"},{"id":"d","text":"On-premises deployment using Oracle Exadata hardware"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Platform as a Service (PaaS) abstracts away the underlying infrastructure and operating system management, allowing developers to focus solely on deploying and managing their application code. Oracle Functions (serverless) and Oracle Container Engine for Kubernetes are PaaS offerings on OCI. Option a (IaaS Bare Metal) still requires the customer to manage the OS and runtime environment. Option c (SaaS) provides fully managed applications with no custom code deployment at the OS or runtime level. Option d refers to on-premises hardware which is not OCI cloud and requires full infrastructure management.$patch$, $patch$OCI Introduction$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/Functions/Concepts/functionsoverview.htm","label":"OCI Docs – Oracle Functions (Serverless PaaS)"},{"url":"https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/GSG/Concepts/baremetalintro.htm","label":"OCI Docs – Cloud Service Models Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '1Z0-1085-25'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which OCI service category would you use if you wanted to run your own custom application code without managing the underlying virtual machine operating system patching or server hardware?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company wants to benefit from OCI's cloud services while keeping their workloads physically located in their own data center due to data residency regulations. Which OCI offering is specifically designed for this scenario?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"OCI Free Tier"},{"id":"b","text":"OCI Dedicated Region Cloud@Customer"},{"id":"c","text":"OCI Multi-Cloud with Microsoft Azure"},{"id":"d","text":"OCI Compartments"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$OCI Dedicated Region Cloud@Customer brings a full OCI region, including the same hardware, software, and services available in Oracle's public cloud regions, directly into a customer's own data center. This is purpose-built for organizations that have strict data residency, latency, or regulatory requirements preventing them from using public cloud regions. Option a (Free Tier) is a cost model for public cloud usage, not an on-premises deployment model. Option c (Multi-Cloud with Azure) connects OCI to Azure but does not place infrastructure in the customer's own data center. Option d (Compartments) is an IAM and resource organization construct, not a deployment model.$patch$, $patch$OCI Introduction$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/dedicated-region/overview.htm","label":"OCI Docs – Dedicated Region Cloud@Customer"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '1Z0-1085-25'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company wants to benefit from OCI's cloud services while keeping their workloads physically located in their own data center due to data residency regulations. Which OCI offering is specifically designed for this scenario?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which OCI IAM component is used to logically group users who share the same type of access to resources?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Compartment"},{"id":"b","text":"Group"},{"id":"c","text":"Policy"},{"id":"d","text":"Dynamic Group"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$In OCI IAM, a Group is a collection of users who all need the same type of access to a particular set of resources. Policies are then written to grant permissions to groups, not to individual users. A Compartment is a logical container for organizing resources. A Policy is the document that grants permissions. A Dynamic Group is used to group OCI resource principals (like compute instances), not human users.$patch$, $patch$OCI Identity and Access Management$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/Identity/groups/managinggroups.htm","label":"OCI Documentation – Managing Groups"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '1Z0-1085-25'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which OCI IAM component is used to logically group users who share the same type of access to resources?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In Oracle Cloud Infrastructure, what is the primary purpose of a Compartment?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"To store encryption keys for OCI resources"},{"id":"b","text":"To define network boundaries within a VCN"},{"id":"c","text":"To logically isolate and organize cloud resources within a tenancy"},{"id":"d","text":"To group users who require the same level of access"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Compartments are the fundamental building blocks in OCI for organizing and isolating resources within a tenancy. They allow administrators to control access by writing policies that grant groups specific permissions within a compartment. Encryption keys are managed by the Vault service. Network boundaries are defined by VCN constructs like subnets. Grouping users for access is the role of a Group, not a Compartment.$patch$, $patch$OCI Identity and Access Management$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/Identity/compartments/managingcompartments.htm","label":"OCI Documentation – Managing Compartments"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '1Z0-1085-25'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$In Oracle Cloud Infrastructure, what is the primary purpose of a Compartment?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which statement correctly describes the structure of an OCI IAM Policy?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Allow <group_name> to <verb> <resource-type> in <location>"},{"id":"b","text":"Grant <user_name> <permission> on <resource-type> where <condition>"},{"id":"c","text":"Permit <group_name> access to <resource-type> within <compartment>"},{"id":"d","text":"Authorize <user_name> to <verb> <resource-type> in <tenancy>"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$OCI IAM policy statements follow the syntax: Allow <subject> to <verb> <resource-type> in <location> [where <conditions>]. The subject must be a group (not an individual user). Options B, C, and D use incorrect keywords such as 'Grant', 'Permit', and 'Authorize', which are not valid OCI policy verbs, and some reference individual users rather than groups.$patch$, $patch$OCI Identity and Access Management$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/Identity/policieshow/how-policies-work.htm","label":"OCI Documentation – How Policies Work"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '1Z0-1085-25'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which statement correctly describes the structure of an OCI IAM Policy?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company wants a set of Compute instances to automatically call OCI APIs without storing credentials in configuration files. Which OCI IAM feature should they use?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"User Group"},{"id":"b","text":"Auth Token"},{"id":"c","text":"Dynamic Group"},{"id":"d","text":"Compartment Policy"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Dynamic Groups allow OCI resource instances (such as Compute instances, Functions, or other resources) to be treated as principals, similar to user groups. A policy can then be written granting the Dynamic Group permissions to call OCI APIs without embedding credentials. User Groups are for human users. Auth Tokens are user-specific credentials used for third-party API authentication. A Compartment Policy is not a standalone feature — policies are attached to compartments but are not the mechanism for granting resource-based identity.$patch$, $patch$OCI Identity and Access Management$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/Identity/dynamicgroups/managingdynamicgroups.htm","label":"OCI Documentation – Managing Dynamic Groups"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '1Z0-1085-25'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company wants a set of Compute instances to automatically call OCI APIs without storing credentials in configuration files. Which OCI IAM feature should they use?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which built-in OCI IAM verb grants the MOST permissive level of access to a resource type?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"read"},{"id":"b","text":"use"},{"id":"c","text":"manage"},{"id":"d","text":"inspect"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$OCI IAM defines four access levels in increasing order of permissions: inspect < read < use < manage. The 'manage' verb grants full control over a resource type, including the ability to create, update, and delete. 'inspect' allows listing resources. 'read' allows listing and getting details. 'use' allows working with existing resources but not creating or deleting them. 'manage' is the most permissive.$patch$, $patch$OCI Identity and Access Management$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/Identity/policyreference/policyreference_topic-Verbs.htm","label":"OCI Documentation – Verbs"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '1Z0-1085-25'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which built-in OCI IAM verb grants the MOST permissive level of access to a resource type?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In OCI IAM, which special compartment serves as the root of the compartment hierarchy and contains all other compartments within a tenancy?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The Admin Compartment"},{"id":"b","text":"The Root Compartment (tenancy)"},{"id":"c","text":"The Default Compartment"},{"id":"d","text":"The Security Compartment"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$In OCI, the tenancy itself acts as the root compartment. When a policy statement uses 'in tenancy', it applies to all resources across the entire tenancy. All other compartments are nested under this root. There is no built-in 'Admin Compartment', 'Default Compartment', or 'Security Compartment' in OCI IAM by default.$patch$, $patch$OCI Identity and Access Management$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/Identity/getstarted/identity-domains.htm","label":"OCI Documentation – Overview of IAM"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '1Z0-1085-25'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$In OCI IAM, which special compartment serves as the root of the compartment hierarchy and contains all other compartments within a tenancy?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which OCI IAM entity is automatically created when a new OCI tenancy is provisioned and has full administrative privileges over all resources?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The default service account"},{"id":"b","text":"The tenancy administrator user"},{"id":"c","text":"The root IAM group"},{"id":"d","text":"The OCI managed policy administrator"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$When a new OCI tenancy is created, a tenancy administrator user (often called the 'default administrator') is automatically provisioned. This user is placed in the Administrators group and has full access to all resources in the tenancy. There is no 'default service account', 'root IAM group', or 'OCI managed policy administrator' created by default during tenancy provisioning.$patch$, $patch$OCI Identity and Access Management$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/GSG/Tasks/signingin.htm","label":"OCI Documentation – Managing the Tenancy"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '1Z0-1085-25'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which OCI IAM entity is automatically created when a new OCI tenancy is provisioned and has full administrative privileges over all resources?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which Oracle Cloud Infrastructure resource serves as the fundamental building block for private networking and provides an isolated, customizable network environment within a single OCI region?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Dynamic Routing Gateway (DRG)"},{"id":"b","text":"Virtual Cloud Network (VCN)"},{"id":"c","text":"Network Security Group (NSG)"},{"id":"d","text":"Internet Gateway"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A Virtual Cloud Network (VCN) is the core private networking resource in OCI. It provides a logically isolated, software-defined network within an OCI region where you launch your cloud resources. A DRG is used to connect a VCN to on-premises networks or other VCNs. NSGs and Internet Gateways are components used within or attached to a VCN, not the foundational building block itself.$patch$, $patch$Networking$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/Network/Tasks/VCNs.htm","label":"OCI Documentation – Virtual Cloud Networks Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '1Z0-1085-25'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which Oracle Cloud Infrastructure resource serves as the fundamental building block for private networking and provides an isolated, customizable network environment within a single OCI region?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer wants instances in a private subnet of an OCI Virtual Cloud Network to download software updates from the internet without being directly reachable from the internet. Which OCI networking component should be used to enable this outbound-only internet access?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Internet Gateway"},{"id":"b","text":"Service Gateway"},{"id":"c","text":"NAT Gateway"},{"id":"d","text":"Local Peering Gateway (LPG)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A NAT (Network Address Translation) Gateway allows instances in a private subnet to initiate outbound connections to the internet without exposing those instances to inbound internet traffic. An Internet Gateway supports two-way internet connectivity and is suited for public subnets. A Service Gateway provides access to Oracle services (like Object Storage) without traversing the internet. An LPG is used to peer two VCNs within the same region.$patch$, $patch$Networking$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/Network/Tasks/NATgateway.htm","label":"OCI Documentation – NAT Gateway"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '1Z0-1085-25'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A developer wants instances in a private subnet of an OCI Virtual Cloud Network to download software updates from the internet without being directly reachable from the internet. Which OCI networking component should be used to enable this outbound-only internet access?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In Oracle Cloud Infrastructure, what is the maximum number of DNS labels (i.e., the depth) that can form a valid subnet DNS label within a VCN?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"A subnet is identified by its CIDR block only; subnets do not have DNS labels"},{"id":"b","text":"Each subnet can be assigned a DNS label, and the fully qualified domain name of an instance combines the instance hostname, subnet DNS label, VCN DNS label, and the domain oraclevcn.com"},{"id":"c","text":"Subnets share the same DNS label as their parent VCN"},{"id":"d","text":"Each subnet uses a public IP address as its DNS identifier instead of a label"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$In OCI, when you assign a DNS label to a VCN and a DNS label to a subnet, each instance in that subnet gets a fully qualified domain name (FQDN) in the format: <hostname>.<subnet-dns-label>.<vcn-dns-label>.oraclevcn.com. This allows instances to resolve each other by hostname within the VCN. Subnets do not inherit the VCN's DNS label—they each have their own. CIDR blocks and public IPs are not used as DNS identifiers.$patch$, $patch$Networking$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/Network/Concepts/dns.htm","label":"OCI Documentation – DNS in Your Virtual Cloud Network"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '1Z0-1085-25'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$In Oracle Cloud Infrastructure, what is the maximum number of DNS labels (i.e., the depth) that can form a valid subnet DNS label within a VCN?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which OCI networking gateway allows resources inside a Virtual Cloud Network to access Oracle Cloud services such as Oracle Object Storage without sending traffic over the public internet?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Internet Gateway"},{"id":"b","text":"NAT Gateway"},{"id":"c","text":"Service Gateway"},{"id":"d","text":"Dynamic Routing Gateway (DRG)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A Service Gateway enables private access to supported Oracle Cloud services (such as Object Storage and Autonomous Database) from within a VCN, keeping traffic on Oracle's internal network and never exposing it to the public internet. An Internet Gateway provides general public internet access. A NAT Gateway gives private instances outbound internet access. A DRG is used for connectivity to on-premises networks or remote VCNs.$patch$, $patch$Networking$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/Network/Tasks/servicegateway.htm","label":"OCI Documentation – Service Gateway"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '1Z0-1085-25'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which OCI networking gateway allows resources inside a Virtual Cloud Network to access Oracle Cloud services such as Oracle Object Storage without sending traffic over the public internet?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An OCI administrator needs to allow HTTP (port 80) traffic from the internet to a set of web server instances. The administrator wants to apply the rule at the individual instance level rather than at the subnet level. Which OCI feature should be used?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Security List"},{"id":"b","text":"Network Security Group (NSG)"},{"id":"c","text":"Route Table"},{"id":"d","text":"DHCP Options"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Network Security Groups (NSGs) allow you to define security rules that apply to specific individual resources (such as compute instances, load balancers, or database systems) that are added as members of the NSG. This provides more granular, resource-level control compared to Security Lists, which apply rules at the subnet level and affect all resources in that subnet. Route Tables control traffic routing, and DHCP Options configure DNS and hostname settings.$patch$, $patch$Networking$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/Network/Concepts/networksecuritygroups.htm","label":"OCI Documentation – Network Security Groups"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '1Z0-1085-25'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An OCI administrator needs to allow HTTP (port 80) traffic from the internet to a set of web server instances. The administrator wants to apply the rule at the individual instance level rather than at the subnet level. Which OCI feature should be used?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In Oracle Cloud Infrastructure, what is the purpose of a Route Table associated with a subnet?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"It defines firewall rules that allow or deny traffic to and from resources in the subnet"},{"id":"b","text":"It specifies the rules that determine where network traffic originating from the subnet is directed"},{"id":"c","text":"It assigns private IP addresses to instances within the subnet using DHCP"},{"id":"d","text":"It encrypts traffic leaving the subnet to ensure data-in-transit security"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A Route Table in OCI contains rules (routes) that specify the next-hop destination for traffic leaving the subnet based on the destination IP range. For example, a route rule might direct all internet-bound traffic (0.0.0.0/0) to an Internet Gateway. Firewall-type rules are handled by Security Lists or NSGs, not Route Tables. DHCP Options handle IP addressing, and OCI does not use Route Tables for encryption.$patch$, $patch$Networking$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/Network/Tasks/managingroutetables.htm","label":"OCI Documentation – Route Tables"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '1Z0-1085-25'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$In Oracle Cloud Infrastructure, what is the purpose of a Route Table associated with a subnet?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company has two Virtual Cloud Networks (VCNs) in the same OCI region and wants resources in each VCN to communicate with each other using private IP addresses without traffic traversing the public internet. Which OCI feature enables this connectivity?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"FastConnect"},{"id":"b","text":"Site-to-Site VPN"},{"id":"c","text":"Local Peering Gateway (LPG)"},{"id":"d","text":"Internet Gateway"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A Local Peering Gateway (LPG) enables VCN peering between two VCNs in the same OCI region, allowing private IP communication between them without the traffic leaving Oracle's network or going over the internet. FastConnect and Site-to-Site VPN are used to connect OCI VCNs to on-premises data centers. An Internet Gateway provides access to the public internet and does not facilitate private VCN-to-VCN connectivity.$patch$, $patch$Networking$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/Network/Tasks/localVCNpeering.htm","label":"OCI Documentation – Local VCN Peering (Within Region)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
