INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer sends an HTTP POST request to the Cisco DNA Center northbound REST API to create a new network site. The server responds with status code 201. What does this status code indicate?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The request was received but is still being processed."},{"id":"b","text":"The resource was successfully created."},{"id":"c","text":"The request was unauthorized and authentication is required."},{"id":"d","text":"The server encountered an internal error."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material lists HTTP status codes: '2xx (success: 200 OK, 201 Created, 204 No Content).' A 201 Created response confirms the server successfully created the requested resource. A 401 would indicate authentication is required. A 500 would indicate a server-side error. There is no standard 'still processing' semantic for 201.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://developer.cisco.com/docs/dna-center/","label":"Cisco DNA Center API Documentation"},{"url":"https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc9110#section-15.3.2","label":"RFC 9110 – HTTP Semantics: Status Codes"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A developer sends an HTTP POST request to the Cisco DNA Center northbound REST API to create a new network site. The server responds with status code 201. What does this status code indicate?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which of the following best describes the architectural difference between a traditional network and a Software-Defined Network (SDN)?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Traditional networks use a centralized control plane, while SDN distributes the control plane to each device."},{"id":"b","text":"Traditional networks have a distributed control plane on each device, while SDN centralizes the control plane in a controller."},{"id":"c","text":"SDN eliminates the data plane entirely and processes all traffic in the controller."},{"id":"d","text":"Traditional networks rely on REST APIs, while SDN uses CLI-only management."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Traditional: distributed control plane (each device runs routing). SDN: centralized control plane (controller programs data plane).' In SDN, the controller makes forwarding decisions and programs the data plane of individual devices; the data plane itself is not eliminated. Traditional networks use distributed routing protocols, not REST APIs, as their primary management paradigm.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/solutions/software-defined-networking/overview.html","label":"Cisco Software-Defined Networking Overview"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9781587147142","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide – SDN Chapter"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which of the following best describes the architectural difference between a traditional network and a Software-Defined Network (SDN)?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network programmer needs a Python library to connect to multiple vendor devices over SSH and execute show commands without using a vendor-specific SDK. Which Python library, cited in the CCNA automation domain, is specifically designed as an SSH client abstraction for network devices?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"requests"},{"id":"b","text":"Netmiko"},{"id":"c","text":"Nornir"},{"id":"d","text":"Terraform"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material identifies: 'Netmiko: SSH library for network devices.' Netmiko is purpose-built to simplify SSH connections to network devices. 'requests' is an HTTP client library for REST API calls. Nornir is an orchestration framework (not just an SSH library). Terraform is an infrastructure-as-code tool, not a Python SSH library.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://github.com/ktbyers/netmiko","label":"Netmiko GitHub Repository"},{"url":"https://developer.cisco.com/learning/tracks/netprog-eng/","label":"Cisco DevNet – Network Programmability Basics"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network programmer needs a Python library to connect to multiple vendor devices over SSH and execute show commands without using a vendor-specific SDK. Which Python library, cited in the CCNA automation domain, is specifically designed as an SSH client abstraction for network devices?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An engineer needs to modify a single attribute on an existing REST API resource without replacing the entire object. Which HTTP method should be used?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"GET"},{"id":"b","text":"POST"},{"id":"c","text":"PUT"},{"id":"d","text":"PATCH"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["d"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material defines HTTP methods as: 'GET (read), POST (create), PUT (replace), PATCH (modify), DELETE (remove).' PATCH is used to partially modify an existing resource, making it the correct choice when only one attribute needs to change. PUT replaces the entire resource. POST creates a new resource. GET only retrieves data.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc5789","label":"RFC 5789 – PATCH Method for HTTP"},{"url":"https://developer.cisco.com/learning/modules/rest-api-fundamentals/","label":"Cisco DevNet – REST API Fundamentals"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An engineer needs to modify a single attribute on an existing REST API resource without replacing the entire object. Which HTTP method should be used?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which Cisco on-device automation feature allows a network engineer to trigger a configuration change or script automatically when a specific syslog event is detected on an IOS device, without any external controller?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Cisco DNA Center Assurance"},{"id":"b","text":"Cisco Embedded Event Manager (EEM)"},{"id":"c","text":"Ansible ios_config module"},{"id":"d","text":"RESTCONF with YANG models"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Cisco EEM (Embedded Event Manager): on-device automation via applets and Tcl scripts.' EEM runs directly on the IOS device and can react to events such as syslog messages, CLI input, or interface state changes without any external controller. DNA Center Assurance is a monitoring feature. Ansible ios_config requires an external control node. RESTCONF is a programmability interface, not an event-driven on-device automation tool.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/eem/configuration/xe-16/eem-xe-16-book.html","label":"Cisco IOS Embedded Event Manager (EEM) Configuration Guide"},{"url":"https://developer.cisco.com/docs/ios-xe/#!embedded-event-manager","label":"Cisco DevNet – EEM Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which Cisco on-device automation feature allows a network engineer to trigger a configuration change or script automatically when a specific syslog event is detected on an IOS device, without any external controller?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network architect is designing a solution where business intent is automatically translated into network device configurations across the entire enterprise fabric. Which Cisco platform and concept best represents this capability?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Cisco IOS EEM applets performing Tcl-based scripting"},{"id":"b","text":"Cisco DNA Center / Catalyst Center implementing Intent-Based Networking (IBN)"},{"id":"c","text":"Ansible playbooks using YAML to configure individual routers over SSH"},{"id":"d","text":"NAPALM providing multi-vendor abstraction for CLI commands"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material describes Cisco DNA Center / Catalyst Center as providing 'Intent-based networking (IBN) - business intent translated to network config,' along with 'Assurance, automation, and analytics' via a northbound REST API and southbound NETCONF/YANG to devices. This centralized, intent-driven approach is the defining feature of DNA Center. EEM is on-device and reactive. Ansible operates at a per-device configuration level without holistic intent abstraction. NAPALM is a Python abstraction library, not an intent-based platform.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/cloud-systems-management/dna-center/index.html","label":"Cisco DNA Center – Intent-Based Networking"},{"url":"https://developer.cisco.com/docs/dna-center/","label":"Cisco Catalyst Center Documentation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network architect is designing a solution where business intent is automatically translated into network device configurations across the entire enterprise fabric. Which Cisco platform and concept best represents this capability?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer is examining a frame captured on a LAN segment. The destination MAC address in the frame is FF:FF:FF:FF:FF:FF. Which statement best describes this frame?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The frame is destined for a specific host whose MAC address has been resolved via ARP."},{"id":"b","text":"The frame will be forwarded by all switches and processed by all hosts in the same broadcast domain."},{"id":"c","text":"The frame is a multicast frame and will only be processed by hosts that have joined a specific multicast group."},{"id":"d","text":"The frame will be dropped by all Layer 2 switches because the destination is not in the MAC address table."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A destination MAC address of FF:FF:FF:FF:FF:FF is the Layer 2 broadcast address. Switches flood frames with this destination out all ports in the same VLAN/broadcast domain, and every host in that broadcast domain receives and processes the frame. Option A describes a known unicast frame. Option C describes a multicast frame, which uses a different MAC address range (e.g., 01:00:5E:xx:xx:xx for IPv4 multicast). Option D is incorrect because switches do not drop broadcast frames; they flood them.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/tech/lan-switching/lan-switching-fundamentals/index.html","label":"Cisco – LAN Switching Overview (Catalyst Switching)"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9781587147142","label":"Cisco Press – CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Chapter on Ethernet LANs"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer is examining a frame captured on a LAN segment. The destination MAC address in the frame is FF:FF:FF:FF:FF:FF. Which statement best describes this frame?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which OSI layer is responsible for end-to-end error recovery, flow control, and reliable data transfer between two hosts across a network?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Layer 2 – Data Link"},{"id":"b","text":"Layer 3 – Network"},{"id":"c","text":"Layer 4 – Transport"},{"id":"d","text":"Layer 5 – Session"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Layer 4, the Transport layer, is responsible for end-to-end (host-to-host) reliable delivery, error recovery, and flow control. TCP operates at this layer and uses mechanisms such as acknowledgments, sequence numbers, and windowing to ensure reliable data transfer. Layer 2 (Data Link) provides node-to-node error detection on a single link segment, not end-to-end across a network. Layer 3 (Network) handles logical addressing and routing of packets between networks. Layer 5 (Session) manages dialog control and session establishment between applications, not reliable data transfer.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/routers/10000-series-routers/50421-23.html","label":"Cisco – OSI Model Reference"},{"url":"https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc793","label":"RFC 793 – Transmission Control Protocol (TCP)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which OSI layer is responsible for end-to-end error recovery, flow control, and reliable data transfer between two hosts across a network?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A host is configured with an IPv4 address of 172.16.45.200 and a subnet mask of 255.255.252.0. What is the network address of the subnet to which this host belongs?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"172.16.44.0"},{"id":"b","text":"172.16.45.0"},{"id":"c","text":"172.16.40.0"},{"id":"d","text":"172.16.48.0"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The subnet mask 255.255.252.0 equals /22 in CIDR notation. The third octet mask value of 252 (11111100 in binary) means the block size in the third octet is 4 (256 - 252 = 4). Starting from 0, the /22 subnet blocks in the third octet are: 0, 4, 8, 12, 16, 20, 24, 28, 32, 36, 40, 44, 48 … The host's third octet is 45, which falls in the range 44–47 (network 172.16.44.0, broadcast 172.16.47.255). Therefore the network address is 172.16.44.0. Option B (172.16.45.0) is the host address with the last octet zeroed, which is not how subnetting works. Option C (172.16.40.0) is the previous /22 block. Option D (172.16.48.0) is the next /22 block.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html","label":"Cisco – IP Addressing and Subnetting for New Users"},{"url":"https://learningnetwork.cisco.com/s/ccna-exam-topics","label":"Cisco Learning Network – CCNA Exam Topics"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A host is configured with an IPv4 address of 172.16.45.200 and a subnet mask of 255.255.252.0. What is the network address of the subnet to which this host belongs?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator is configuring a Cisco Catalyst switch and wants to ensure that any device connecting to access ports is automatically placed into the correct VLAN based on its MAC address. Which feature should the administrator configure to achieve this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Dynamic Trunking Protocol (DTP)"},{"id":"b","text":"VLAN Trunking Protocol (VTP)"},{"id":"c","text":"Dynamic VLAN assignment using VMPS or 802.1X with RADIUS"},{"id":"d","text":"Port Address Translation (PAT)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Dynamic VLAN assignment allows a switch to place a device into the correct VLAN based on its MAC address (via VMPS) or identity (via 802.1X with a RADIUS server that returns a VLAN attribute). DTP (option A) is used to negotiate trunking between switches, not to assign VLANs based on device identity. VTP (option B) is a protocol used to synchronize VLAN databases across switches, not to assign VLANs dynamically to end devices. PAT (option D) is a Layer 3/4 NAT mechanism and has no role in VLAN assignment.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/sec/b_179_sec_9300_cg/configuring_ieee_802_1x_port_based_authentication.html","label":"Cisco - Configuring VLAN-Based Authentication (802.1X with Dynamic VLAN Assignment)"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/vlan/6606-dynamic-vlan.html","label":"Cisco - Dynamic VLAN Membership Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator is configuring a Cisco Catalyst switch and wants to ensure that any device connecting to access ports is automatically placed into the correct VLAN based on its MAC address. Which feature should the administrator configure to achieve this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A switch port is configured as a trunk and is carrying traffic for VLANs 10, 20, and 30. An administrator notices that frames belonging to VLAN 10 are being sent across the trunk link without an 802.1Q tag. What is the most likely explanation for this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"VLAN 10 has been pruned from the trunk by VTP."},{"id":"b","text":"VLAN 10 is configured as the native VLAN on that trunk port."},{"id":"c","text":"The trunk port is using ISL encapsulation, which does not support tagging."},{"id":"d","text":"Spanning Tree Protocol has placed VLAN 10 in a blocking state."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$In 802.1Q trunking, the native VLAN is the one VLAN whose frames are transmitted across a trunk link without an 802.1Q tag. By default, VLAN 1 is the native VLAN, but it can be changed with the 'switchport trunk native vlan <vlan-id>' command. If VLAN 10 is untagged, it has been designated as the native VLAN. VTP pruning (option A) would stop a VLAN's traffic from traversing the trunk entirely, not just remove its tag. ISL (option C) is a Cisco proprietary trunking protocol that encapsulates the entire original frame, tagging all VLANs including a native equivalent — it does not leave any VLAN untagged. STP blocking (option D) would prevent the port from forwarding any traffic for that VLAN, not cause untagged frames.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/8021q/17056-741-4.html","label":"Cisco - IEEE 802.1Q and Native VLAN Configuration"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/vlan/b_179_vlan_9300_cg/configuring_vlan_trunks.html","label":"Cisco - Configuring VLAN Trunks (Catalyst Switches)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A switch port is configured as a trunk and is carrying traffic for VLANs 10, 20, and 30. An administrator notices that frames belonging to VLAN 10 are being sent across the trunk link without an 802.1Q tag. What is the most likely explanation for this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator is deploying Rapid Per-VLAN Spanning Tree Plus (Rapid PVST+) on a distribution-layer Cisco switch. The switch should become the root bridge for VLAN 50. Which command accomplishes this most reliably by setting an explicit bridge priority?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"spanning-tree vlan 50 priority 61440"},{"id":"b","text":"spanning-tree vlan 50 root primary"},{"id":"c","text":"spanning-tree vlan 50 priority 4096"},{"id":"d","text":"spanning-tree vlan 50 forward-time 4"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$STP bridge priority values must be multiples of 4096. The lower the priority, the more likely the switch is to become root bridge. Setting 'spanning-tree vlan 50 priority 4096' assigns the second-lowest possible priority (after 0), making this switch almost certainly the root bridge. Option A uses a priority of 61440, which is near the maximum and would make the switch the least preferred root candidate. Option B ('spanning-tree vlan 50 root primary') is a macro command that is convenient but works by dynamically lowering the priority to beat the current root — it is less deterministic and predictable in production environments compared to setting an explicit priority value. Option D modifies the forward delay timer and has no effect on root bridge election.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/stp/b_179_stp_9300_cg/configuring_spanning_tree_protocol.html","label":"Cisco - Configuring Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) Bridge Priority"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/spanning-tree-protocol/24062-146.html","label":"Cisco - Understanding Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol (802.1w)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator is deploying Rapid Per-VLAN Spanning Tree Plus (Rapid PVST+) on a distribution-layer Cisco switch. The switch should become the root bridge for VLAN 50. Which command accomplishes this most reliably by setting an explicit bridge priority?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A router has the following routes in its routing table:

  192.168.10.0/24 via 10.0.0.1
  192.168.10.0/26 via 10.0.0.2
  0.0.0.0/0 via 10.0.0.3

A packet arrives destined for 192.168.10.50. Which next-hop address will the router use to forward this packet?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"10.0.0.1, because it matches the /24 route first"},{"id":"b","text":"10.0.0.2, because the /26 prefix is the longest match for 192.168.10.50"},{"id":"c","text":"10.0.0.3, because the default route always takes precedence"},{"id":"d","text":"The packet is dropped because 192.168.10.50 matches two routes and creates a conflict"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Cisco IOS uses the longest prefix match (most specific route) principle when making forwarding decisions. 192.168.10.50 falls within both 192.168.10.0/24 (covers .0–.255) and 192.168.10.0/26 (covers .0–.63). The /26 is more specific (longer prefix), so it wins and the packet is forwarded via 10.0.0.2. The default route (0.0.0.0/0) is only used when no more-specific match exists. There is no conflict—longest match is a deterministic tie-breaker.$patch$, $patch$IP Connectivity$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/routers/12000-series-routers/47321-ciscoef.html","label":"Cisco – IP Routing: Process Switching, Fast Switching, and CEF"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9781587147142","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide – Longest Prefix Match"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A router has the following routes in its routing table:

  192.168.10.0/24 via 10.0.0.1
  192.168.10.0/26 via 10.0.0.2
  0.0.0.0/0 via 10.0.0.3

A packet arrives destined for 192.168.10.50. Which next-hop address will the router use to forward this packet?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator configures a static default route on a branch router using the command:

  ip route 0.0.0.0 0.0.0.0 Serial0/0/0

After the configuration, the branch router cannot reach any internet destinations, although the Serial0/0/0 interface shows as up/up. The ISP router on the other end of the serial link is also reachable via ping. What is the MOST likely cause of the problem?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The subnet mask 0.0.0.0 is invalid for a static route and the command was rejected"},{"id":"b","text":"A static route using an exit interface on a point-to-multipoint link may cause recursive routing issues, but on a true point-to-point serial link this command is valid—the issue is likely a missing or incorrect ip address on Serial0/0/0"},{"id":"c","text":"The default route requires an administrative distance of 254 to be installed in the routing table"},{"id":"d","text":"Static default routes are only supported on FastEthernet interfaces in Cisco IOS"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The command 'ip route 0.0.0.0 0.0.0.0 Serial0/0/0' is a valid static default route specifying an exit interface rather than a next-hop IP address. On a true point-to-point serial link, this is fully supported and the route will be installed. The most plausible remaining cause of failure when the interface is up/up and the directly-connected ISP router is pingable is a misconfigured or missing IP address on Serial0/0/0 that prevents traffic beyond the directly-connected segment from being routed correctly. Option A is wrong—0.0.0.0 0.0.0.0 is the valid wildcard used to define the default route. Option C is wrong—the default administrative distance for a static route is 1, not 254 (254 is used for floating static routes). Option D is incorrect; static routes are supported on any routed interface.$patch$, $patch$IP Connectivity$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/iproute_static/configuration/xe-16/irs-xe-16-book/irs-cfg-static-routes.html","label":"Cisco – Configuring Static Routing"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/iproute_static/command/irs-cr-book/irs-cr-i1.html#wp3532606090","label":"Cisco – ip route Command Reference"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator configures a static default route on a branch router using the command:

  ip route 0.0.0.0 0.0.0.0 Serial0/0/0

After the configuration, the branch router cannot reach any internet destinations, although the Serial0/0/0 interface shows as up/up. The ISP router on the other end of the serial link is also reachable via ping. What is the MOST likely cause of the problem?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An OSPFv2 neighbor relationship between two routers is stuck in the EXSTART state. Both routers are connected via an Ethernet segment and OSPF has been verified as enabled on both interfaces. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The two routers have different OSPF process IDs configured"},{"id":"b","text":"The MTU values configured on the two connected interfaces do not match"},{"id":"c","text":"The routers are in different OSPF areas, so they can never form an adjacency"},{"id":"d","text":"One of the routers has OSPF authentication enabled while the other does not, causing the hello packets to be rejected before EXSTART"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The EXSTART state is where two OSPF routers negotiate the master/slave relationship and initial Database Description (DBD) sequence numbers. If the interface MTU values differ, the DBD packets from one router may exceed the MTU of the other, causing the receiving router to silently discard them. This prevents the exchange from progressing and leaves the adjacency stuck in EXSTART. Option A is incorrect—OSPF process IDs are locally significant and do not affect adjacency formation. Option C is incorrect—routers in different areas can still form adjacencies on a shared link as long as one area is area 0 or they are connected via a virtual link; moreover, a mismatch in area ID would cause the neighbor to be stuck in INIT/2-WAY, not EXSTART. Option D is incorrect—an authentication mismatch would prevent hello packets from being accepted, so the adjacency would not even reach the EXSTART state.$patch$, $patch$IP Connectivity$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/open-shortest-path-first-ospf/13685-13.html","label":"Cisco – OSPF Neighbor States Explained"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/open-shortest-path-first-ospf/7107-so-mtu.html","label":"Cisco – Troubleshooting OSPF Stuck in EXSTART/EXCHANGE State"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An OSPFv2 neighbor relationship between two routers is stuck in the EXSTART state. Both routers are connected via an Ethernet segment and OSPF has been verified as enabled on both interfaces. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator needs to configure a Cisco router so that internal hosts using private IPv4 addresses can access the internet through a single public IP address assigned to the router's outside interface. Which IP Services feature should be configured to accomplish this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Static NAT, mapping each internal private IP address to a unique public IP address on a one-to-one basis"},{"id":"b","text":"PAT (Port Address Translation), also known as NAT overload, allowing multiple internal hosts to share a single public IP address using unique source port numbers"},{"id":"c","text":"Dynamic NAT, using a pool of multiple public IP addresses assigned randomly to internal hosts as they initiate connections"},{"id":"d","text":"NAT64, translating IPv6 addresses from internal hosts to a single IPv4 public address on the outside interface"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$PAT (Port Address Translation), commonly referred to as NAT overload, is the correct solution when multiple internal hosts must share a single public IP address to reach the internet. PAT distinguishes sessions from different internal hosts by assigning unique source port numbers to each translation entry, allowing thousands of simultaneous connections through one public IP. Static NAT (option a) requires a unique public IP per internal host, so it cannot work with only one public address. Dynamic NAT (option c) also draws from a pool of multiple public IPs and would exhaust the pool if only one IP is available. NAT64 (option d) is used for IPv6-to-IPv4 translation, which is not the scenario described here.$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/network-address-translation-nat/26704-nat-faq-00.html","label":"Cisco - Configuring Network Address Translation: Getting Started"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/network-address-translation-nat/6209-5.html","label":"Cisco - NAT Order of Operations"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9781587147142","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide - IP Services"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator needs to configure a Cisco router so that internal hosts using private IPv4 addresses can access the internet through a single public IP address assigned to the router's outside interface. Which IP Services feature should be configured to accomplish this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator wants to prevent unauthorized devices from gaining network access by ensuring that only devices with valid credentials can connect to a switch port using 802.1X authentication. Which component acts as the intermediary between the supplicant and the authentication server in this process?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"RADIUS server"},{"id":"b","text":"Authenticator (the switch)"},{"id":"c","text":"Supplicant (the end device)"},{"id":"d","text":"TACACS+ server"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$In the 802.1X authentication framework, there are three key roles: the supplicant (the end device requesting access), the authenticator (typically the switch or wireless access point), and the authentication server (typically a RADIUS server). The authenticator acts as the intermediary — it intercepts the supplicant's credentials, forwards them to the authentication server using RADIUS, and then enforces the access decision (permit or deny) returned by the server. The RADIUS server (option A) is the authentication server itself, not the intermediary. The supplicant (option C) is the client device initiating the request. TACACS+ (option D) is an alternative AAA protocol primarily used for device administration (e.g., CLI access), not typically for 802.1X port-based network access control.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/sec_usr_8021x/configuration/xe-16/sec-user-8021x-xe-16-book/config-ieee-802x-pba.html","label":"Cisco - IEEE 802.1X Port-Based Authentication"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9781587147142","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide - Security Fundamentals"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator wants to prevent unauthorized devices from gaining network access by ensuring that only devices with valid credentials can connect to a switch port using 802.1X authentication. Which component acts as the intermediary between the supplicant and the authentication server in this process?$patch$);

-- 200-301-P4: 50 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer is troubleshooting a connectivity issue and needs to identify which OSI layer is responsible for logical addressing and routing packets between networks. Which OSI layer should the engineer focus on?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Layer 1 – Physical"},{"id":"b","text":"Layer 2 – Data Link"},{"id":"c","text":"Layer 3 – Network"},{"id":"d","text":"Layer 4 – Transport"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that routers operate at Layer 3 and 'route packets based on dst IP.' Layer 3 (Network) is responsible for logical (IP) addressing and inter-network routing. Layer 2 (Data Link) uses MAC addresses for local delivery, Layer 4 (Transport) handles end-to-end communication (TCP/UDP), and Layer 1 (Physical) deals with signal transmission. A router—the primary Layer 3 device—makes forwarding decisions based on destination IP addresses found in the Layer 3 header.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/routers/12400-series-internet-routers/8499-osi-transport-layers.html","label":"Cisco – OSI Model Explained"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9781587147142","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide – Network Layer"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer is troubleshooting a connectivity issue and needs to identify which OSI layer is responsible for logical addressing and routing packets between networks. Which OSI layer should the engineer focus on?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which IPv4 address range is defined by RFC 1918 as a private address space with a /8 prefix length, allowing for the largest number of assignable host addresses in a single network?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"192.168.0.0/16"},{"id":"b","text":"172.16.0.0/12"},{"id":"c","text":"10.0.0.0/8"},{"id":"d","text":"169.254.0.0/16"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material lists the RFC 1918 private ranges as '10/8, 172.16-31/12, 192.168/16.' The 10.0.0.0/8 block provides a 24-bit host space, yielding over 16 million usable host addresses—by far the largest of the three private ranges. 192.168.0.0/16 and 172.16.0.0/12 are also RFC 1918 private ranges but are smaller. 169.254.0.0/16 is the APIPA (Automatic Private IP Addressing) range, not an RFC 1918 private range intended for general enterprise use.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc1918","label":"RFC 1918 – Address Allocation for Private Internets"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html","label":"Cisco – Understanding IP Addressing"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which IPv4 address range is defined by RFC 1918 as a private address space with a /8 prefix length, allowing for the largest number of assignable host addresses in a single network?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A switch receives a frame destined for a MAC address that does not exist in its MAC address table. What action does the switch take?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Drops the frame silently."},{"id":"b","text":"Sends an ARP request out all ports to resolve the MAC address."},{"id":"c","text":"Forwards the frame out all ports except the port on which it was received (floods)."},{"id":"d","text":"Forwards the frame only out the port connected to the default gateway."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states that a switch performs 'Flooding (unknown unicast/multicast/broadcast)' when the destination MAC is not in the CAM table. This means the frame is sent out every port except the ingress port so that the destination device—wherever it may be—can receive it and respond, allowing the switch to subsequently learn its MAC address. Dropping the frame would break connectivity; switches do not perform ARP (that is a host/router function); and forwarding only to the default gateway port is incorrect switch behavior.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/switches/how-does-a-switch-work.html","label":"Cisco – How Does a Switch Work?"},{"url":"https://www.netacad.com/courses/ccna-introduction-networks","label":"Cisco Networking Academy – Switching Concepts"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A switch receives a frame destined for a MAC address that does not exist in its MAC address table. What action does the switch take?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator needs to connect two routers back-to-back using the minimum number of IPv4 addresses while still supporting standard broadcast-based addressing. Which subnet mask should be used for the point-to-point link?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"/32"},{"id":"b","text":"/31"},{"id":"c","text":"/30"},{"id":"d","text":"/28"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states '/30 = 4 addrs (2 usable, point-to-point)' and separately notes that '/31 (RFC 3021) for p2p without broadcast.' The question specifically asks for a configuration that still supports standard broadcast-based addressing, which rules out /31 (RFC 3021 eliminates network/broadcast addresses). A /30 provides exactly 4 addresses (1 network, 2 host, 1 broadcast), making it the minimum subnet that supports broadcast semantics on a point-to-point link. /32 is a host route, and /28 provides 16 addresses—more than necessary.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc3021","label":"RFC 3021 – Using 31-Bit Prefixes on IPv4 Point-to-Point Links"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html","label":"Cisco – IP Addressing and Subnetting for New Users"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator needs to connect two routers back-to-back using the minimum number of IPv4 addresses while still supporting standard broadcast-based addressing. Which subnet mask should be used for the point-to-point link?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A technician types a command at the router prompt and sees 'Router>' displayed. Which Cisco IOS mode is the router currently in, and what is a key limitation of this mode?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Global Configuration mode – configuration changes are temporary."},{"id":"b","text":"Privileged EXEC mode – limited show commands are available."},{"id":"c","text":"User EXEC mode – access to most show and debug commands is restricted."},{"id":"d","text":"Interface Configuration mode – only interface-level commands are available."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material identifies Cisco IOS modes by their prompts: 'User EXEC (>)'. The '>' symbol confirms the technician is in User EXEC mode. This mode provides only a limited subset of monitoring commands and restricts access to privileged commands such as 'show running-config,' 'debug,' and configuration mode entry—those require Privileged EXEC mode (indicated by '#'). Global Configuration and Interface Configuration modes have different prompt formats and are reached only after entering Privileged EXEC mode.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/fundamentals/configuration/xe-16/fundamentals-xe-16-book/cf-cli-basics.html","label":"Cisco – Understanding the User Interface"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9781587147142","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide – IOS CLI"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A technician types a command at the router prompt and sees 'Router>' displayed. Which Cisco IOS mode is the router currently in, and what is a key limitation of this mode?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which IPv6 address type is automatically assigned to every IPv6-enabled interface, is confined to the local network segment, and is derived using the FE80::/10 prefix?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Global Unicast address"},{"id":"b","text":"Unique Local address"},{"id":"c","text":"Link-Local address"},{"id":"d","text":"Multicast address"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states 'Link-Local (FE80::/10)' as one of the key IPv6 address types. Link-Local addresses are mandatory on all IPv6-enabled interfaces, are not routable beyond the local link, and always begin with FE80::/10. Global Unicast addresses (2000::/3) are routable on the public internet. Unique Local addresses (FC00::/7) are the IPv6 equivalent of RFC 1918 private addresses and are routable within an organization but not on the internet. Multicast addresses (FF00::/8) are used for one-to-many communication.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/ipv6_basic/configuration/xe-16/ip6b-xe-16-book/ip6-add-basic-conn.html","label":"Cisco – IPv6 Addressing Overview"},{"url":"https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc4291","label":"RFC 4291 – IP Version 6 Addressing Architecture"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which IPv6 address type is automatically assigned to every IPv6-enabled interface, is confined to the local network segment, and is derived using the FE80::/10 prefix?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator needs to run a 10 Gbps Ethernet link over copper cabling across the full 100-meter maximum distance. Which cable category meets both the speed and distance requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Cat5e"},{"id":"b","text":"Cat6 (unshielded standard installation)"},{"id":"c","text":"Cat6a"},{"id":"d","text":"Single-mode fiber"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material specifies: 'Cat5e (1 Gbps, 100m), Cat6 (1-10 Gbps), Cat6a (10 Gbps, 100m).' Cat6a is the only copper twisted-pair category listed that supports 10 Gbps at the full 100-meter distance. Cat5e supports only 1 Gbps. Standard Cat6 can reach 10 Gbps but only up to approximately 55 meters, not the full 100-meter run. Single-mode fiber is not a copper cable and is used for long-distance runs rather than in-building copper cabling, making it an incorrect answer in this copper-specific context.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/ethernet/12006-chapter4.html","label":"Cisco – Cabling Specifications and Standards"},{"url":"https://standards.ieee.org/ieee/802.3an/3485/","label":"IEEE 802.3an – 10GBASE-T Standard"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator needs to run a 10 Gbps Ethernet link over copper cabling across the full 100-meter maximum distance. Which cable category meets both the speed and distance requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In IPv6, which protocol replaces both ARP and ICMP Redirect functionality used in IPv4, and what message types does it use to perform neighbor discovery?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"DHCPv6 – uses Solicit and Advertise messages."},{"id":"b","text":"NDP – uses Neighbor Solicitation (NS) and Neighbor Advertisement (NA) messages."},{"id":"c","text":"ICMPv6 Echo – uses Echo Request and Echo Reply messages."},{"id":"d","text":"SLAAC – uses Router Solicitation (RS) and Router Advertisement (RA) messages only."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'NDP (replaces ARP+ICMP redirect): NS/NA, RS/RA.' Neighbor Discovery Protocol (NDP) subsumes the role of ARP for MAC-to-IP resolution and also handles ICMP Redirect functions, using Neighbor Solicitation (NS) and Neighbor Advertisement (NA) messages for these purposes. DHCPv6 provides stateful address configuration but does not replace ARP. ICMPv6 Echo messages are for ping-like testing, not neighbor resolution. While SLAAC uses RS/RA messages for address autoconfiguration (also part of NDP), those messages alone do not replace ARP—NS/NA messages serve that specific function.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc4861","label":"RFC 4861 – Neighbor Discovery for IP version 6 (IPv6)"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/ipv6_basic/configuration/xe-16/ip6b-xe-16-book/ip6-neighb-disc.html","label":"Cisco – IPv6 Neighbor Discovery"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$In IPv6, which protocol replaces both ARP and ICMP Redirect functionality used in IPv4, and what message types does it use to perform neighbor discovery?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator is configuring a trunk link between two Cisco switches. Which 802.1Q tag field provides the 12-bit VLAN identifier?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"TPID (Tag Protocol Identifier)"},{"id":"b","text":"PCP (Priority Code Point)"},{"id":"c","text":"DEI (Drop Eligible Indicator)"},{"id":"d","text":"VID (VLAN Identifier)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["d"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The 802.1Q tag is 4 bytes total, composed of the TPID (0x8100) and the TCI (Tag Control Information). The TCI contains three subfields: PCP (3 bits for QoS priority), DEI (1 bit for drop eligibility), and the VID (12 bits) which carries the actual VLAN identifier. With 12 bits, VID can represent VLAN IDs 0–4095. TPID identifies the frame as 802.1Q-tagged but does not carry VLAN information. PCP and DEI serve QoS and congestion purposes respectively.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/8021q/17056-741-4.html","label":"Cisco – 802.1Q VLAN Tagging"},{"url":"https://standards.ieee.org/ieee/802.1Q/6844/","label":"IEEE 802.1Q-2018 Standard Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator is configuring a trunk link between two Cisco switches. Which 802.1Q tag field provides the 12-bit VLAN identifier?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A switch port connected to an end-user workstation is inadvertently negotiating a trunk link with the workstation due to DTP. Which command best mitigates this security risk?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"switchport mode dynamic desirable"},{"id":"b","text":"switchport mode dynamic auto"},{"id":"c","text":"switchport mode access"},{"id":"d","text":"switchport nonegotiate"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'for security use switchport mode access or trunk' to prevent DTP from negotiating unintended trunk links. Configuring 'switchport mode access' hard-sets the port as an access port and disables DTP negotiation on that port, ensuring a workstation cannot spoof DTP frames to become a trunk. 'dynamic desirable' and 'dynamic auto' both allow DTP negotiation, which is the vulnerability being addressed. While 'switchport nonegotiate' also disables DTP, 'switchport mode access' is the recommended command for end-user ports as it both sets the correct port type and prevents negotiation.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/vlans/10023-3.html","label":"Cisco – Secure Switch Deployment Guide (DTP)"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9781587147142","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide – VLANs and Trunking"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A switch port connected to an end-user workstation is inadvertently negotiating a trunk link with the workstation due to DTP. Which command best mitigates this security risk?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An IP phone is connected to a Cisco switch access port. The switch must separate voice traffic from data traffic at Layer 2. Which feature accomplishes this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Native VLAN"},{"id":"b","text":"Voice VLAN"},{"id":"c","text":"VTP transparent mode"},{"id":"d","text":"VLAN 1 default assignment"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Voice VLAN: separate L2 for IP phones via CDP/LLDP-MED.' The voice VLAN feature allows a single switch port to carry both a data VLAN (for a PC behind the phone) and a separate voice VLAN (for the IP phone's traffic), providing Layer 2 segmentation. CDP or LLDP-MED is used to signal the voice VLAN ID to the phone. Native VLAN carries untagged traffic but is not specifically designed for phone segmentation. VTP transparent mode relates to VLAN database propagation. VLAN 1 is the default VLAN but has no special voice capability.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/vlan/b_179_vlan_9300_cg/configuring_voice_vlan.html","label":"Cisco – Configuring Voice VLAN"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/ip-multicast/212707-lldp-med-and-voice-vlan.html","label":"Cisco – LLDP-MED and Voice VLAN"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An IP phone is connected to a Cisco switch access port. The switch must separate voice traffic from data traffic at Layer 2. Which feature accomplishes this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer is designing inter-VLAN routing for a small office with 10 VLANs on a single Layer 2 switch and one router. The router has only one physical interface available. Which solution should the engineer implement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Configure a separate physical router interface for each VLAN"},{"id":"b","text":"Use a Switch Virtual Interface (SVI) on the Layer 2 switch"},{"id":"c","text":"Configure router subinterfaces with 802.1Q encapsulation (router-on-a-stick)"},{"id":"d","text":"Enable IP routing on the Layer 2 switch"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Router-on-a-stick: subinterfaces with encapsulation dot1q.' When only one physical router interface is available, the router-on-a-stick method creates logical subinterfaces (e.g., G0/0.10, G0/0.20) each configured with 'encapsulation dot1q <vlan-id>' to route between VLANs over a single trunk link to the switch. Option A is impractical with only one physical interface. Option B (SVIs) requires a Layer 3 switch, not a Layer 2 switch. Option D also requires a Layer 3 capable switch.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/inter-vlan-routing/41860-howto-L3-intervlanrouting.html","label":"Cisco – Inter-VLAN Routing Configuration Guide"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/vlans/14976-50.html","label":"Cisco – Router on a Stick Configuration Example"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer is designing inter-VLAN routing for a small office with 10 VLANs on a single Layer 2 switch and one router. The router has only one physical interface available. Which solution should the engineer implement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which Spanning Tree Protocol standard is Cisco's per-VLAN implementation of the Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol (802.1w)?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"802.1D PVST+"},{"id":"b","text":"802.1s MST"},{"id":"c","text":"Rapid PVST+"},{"id":"d","text":"Common Spanning Tree (CST)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly lists: '802.1w RSTP (per VLAN PVST+/Rapid-PVST+ in Cisco).' Rapid PVST+ is Cisco's per-VLAN implementation of 802.1w, running a separate RSTP instance for each VLAN. 802.1D PVST+ is Cisco's per-VLAN implementation of the original (slower) 802.1D STP. 802.1s MST (Multiple Spanning Tree) maps multiple VLANs to fewer STP instances to reduce overhead. Common Spanning Tree runs a single instance for all VLANs and is not per-VLAN.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/spanning-tree-protocol/24062-146.html","label":"Cisco – Understanding Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol (802.1w)"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/tech/lan-switching/spanning-tree-protocol/index.html","label":"Cisco – Spanning Tree Protocol Features"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which Spanning Tree Protocol standard is Cisco's per-VLAN implementation of the Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol (802.1w)?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A switch port connected to a downstream access switch is configured with PortFast. What is the primary behavior change introduced by enabling PortFast on this port?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The port immediately transitions to forwarding state, bypassing the listening and learning states"},{"id":"b","text":"The port is prevented from ever becoming a root port"},{"id":"c","text":"The port drops all BPDUs received from neighboring switches"},{"id":"d","text":"The port automatically bundles with other ports to form an EtherChannel"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'PortFast (skips listening/learning) on access ports.' PortFast causes a port to immediately transition from blocking directly to forwarding, skipping the listening and learning states of 802.1D STP. This reduces convergence time for end devices. However, it should only be used on ports connected to end hosts, not switches, because if a switch is connected to a PortFast port and sends BPDUs, it could create a topology loop. Option B describes Root Guard behavior. Option C describes BPDU Filter. Option D is unrelated to PortFast.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/spanning-tree-protocol/10588-74.html","label":"Cisco – PortFast, BPDU Guard, and Root Guard Configuration"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9200/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/stp/b-179-9200-stp-cg/configuring_portfast.html","label":"Cisco – Spanning Tree PortFast BPDU Guard Enhancement"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A switch port connected to a downstream access switch is configured with PortFast. What is the primary behavior change introduced by enabling PortFast on this port?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator wants to form an EtherChannel between two Cisco switches using an open, vendor-neutral protocol. Which protocol and mode combination should be used on both switches to ensure negotiation occurs?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"PAgP in desirable mode on both switches"},{"id":"b","text":"LACP in active mode on both switches"},{"id":"c","text":"LACP in passive mode on both switches"},{"id":"d","text":"PAgP in auto mode on both switches"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'LACP (open standard, 802.3ad)' and 'Modes: LACP active/passive.' LACP is the IEEE 802.3ad open standard, making it vendor-neutral. When both switches are set to 'active,' each side actively sends LACP negotiation PDUs, ensuring the EtherChannel forms. PAgP is Cisco proprietary (not vendor-neutral). LACP passive mode means the port will only respond to LACP PDUs but will not initiate — if both ends are passive, no negotiation occurs and the channel will not form. Similarly, PAgP auto on both ends will not form a channel (both wait for the other to initiate).$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/lyr2/b_179_lyr2_9300_cg/configuring_etherchannel.html","label":"Cisco – EtherChannel Configuration Guide (LACP/PAgP)"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/etherchannel/12023-4.html","label":"Cisco – Understanding EtherChannel"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator wants to form an EtherChannel between two Cisco switches using an open, vendor-neutral protocol. Which protocol and mode combination should be used on both switches to ensure negotiation occurs?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A wireless engineer is deploying lightweight access points in a large enterprise campus. Which protocol do these APs use to communicate with the Wireless LAN Controller (WLC)?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"LWAPP (Lightweight Access Point Protocol) over raw IP"},{"id":"b","text":"CAPWAP (Control and Provisioning of Wireless Access Points)"},{"id":"c","text":"STP (Spanning Tree Protocol) tunnels"},{"id":"d","text":"VTP (VLAN Trunking Protocol)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Lightweight APs use CAPWAP tunnel to WLC (control + data).' CAPWAP (defined in RFC 5415) is the standard protocol used by lightweight APs to establish tunnels to the WLC for both control traffic (management, configuration) and data traffic (client data forwarding). LWAPP was the predecessor Cisco proprietary protocol replaced by CAPWAP. STP and VTP are Layer 2 switch protocols unrelated to wireless AP-to-controller communication. Autonomous APs, by contrast, run IOS independently and do not require a WLC.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/wireless/4400-series-wireless-lan-controllers/99427-capwap-overview.html","label":"Cisco – CAPWAP Wireless Controller Overview"},{"url":"https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc5415","label":"RFC 5415 – CAPWAP Protocol Specification"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A wireless engineer is deploying lightweight access points in a large enterprise campus. Which protocol do these APs use to communicate with the Wireless LAN Controller (WLC)?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In the 2.4 GHz Wi-Fi band used in the United States, which set of channels is considered non-overlapping and should be used to minimize co-channel interference in a multi-AP deployment?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Channels 1, 5, and 10"},{"id":"b","text":"Channels 1, 6, and 11"},{"id":"c","text":"Channels 2, 7, and 12"},{"id":"d","text":"Channels 3, 6, and 9"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'non-overlapping 1, 6, 11 in 2.4 GHz US.' In the 2.4 GHz band, each channel is 22 MHz wide but spaced only 5 MHz apart, causing significant overlap between adjacent channels. Channels 1, 6, and 11 are spaced 25 MHz apart from each other, making them the only three channels that do not overlap in the US regulatory domain. Using these three channels across neighboring APs minimizes co-channel and adjacent-channel interference in a dense wireless deployment.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/wireless-mobility/wireless-lan-wlan/212574-802-11-channel-management-best-practice.html","label":"Cisco – 802.11 Channel Planning Best Practices"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/solutions/Enterprise/Mobility/WiFiDeployGuide/WiFiDeployGuide/WiFiDG_ch5.html","label":"Cisco – Wireless LAN Design Guide – Channel Allocation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$In the 2.4 GHz Wi-Fi band used in the United States, which set of channels is considered non-overlapping and should be used to minimize co-channel interference in a multi-AP deployment?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A switch is running VTP in transparent mode. An administrator makes VLAN changes on this switch. What is the expected behavior regarding VTP advertisement propagation?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The switch generates VTP advertisements and updates all VTP clients in the domain"},{"id":"b","text":"The switch forwards VTP advertisements it receives but does not synchronize its own VLAN database from them, and its local VLAN changes are not advertised to the domain"},{"id":"c","text":"The switch accepts VTP advertisements and overwrites its VLAN database with received updates"},{"id":"d","text":"The switch discards all VTP advertisements received from neighboring switches"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material lists VTP modes as 'server, client, transparent.' A switch in VTP transparent mode operates independently of the VTP domain: it does not synchronize its VLAN database based on received VTP advertisements (so incoming advertisements do not modify its local VLAN config), and it does not originate or propagate its own VLAN changes as VTP updates to the rest of the domain. However, it does forward VTP advertisements it receives out other trunk ports, acting as a relay. This is distinct from VTP server mode (which generates and syncs updates) and VTP client mode (which syncs but cannot make local changes).$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/vtp/10558-21.html","label":"Cisco – VTP Configuration Guide"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/vtp/98154-conf-vlan.html","label":"Cisco – Understanding VLAN Trunk Protocol (VTP)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A switch is running VTP in transparent mode. An administrator makes VLAN changes on this switch. What is the expected behavior regarding VTP advertisement propagation?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator configures a Cisco router with the command 'ip helper-address 10.1.1.10' on an interface. What is the primary purpose of this command?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"To assign a static IP address to the interface"},{"id":"b","text":"To forward DHCP broadcast messages to a DHCP server on a different subnet"},{"id":"c","text":"To configure the router as the authoritative DHCP server for the local subnet"},{"id":"d","text":"To enable DNS resolution by pointing to a DNS server at 10.1.1.10"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The 'ip helper-address' command is used on a router interface to relay DHCP broadcast packets (as well as other UDP broadcasts) to a unicast destination — in this case, the DHCP server at 10.1.1.10 on a remote subnet. As noted in the source material, 'ip helper-address' is used for 'relaying DHCP across subnets,' because DHCP Discover messages are broadcasts that cannot natively cross router boundaries. Option A is incorrect because 'ip helper-address' does not assign an IP to the interface. Option C is incorrect because this command does not make the router a DHCP server. Option D is incorrect because DNS server assignment uses 'ip name-server', not 'ip helper-address'.$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/ipaddr_dhcp/configuration/xe-16/dhcp-xe-16-book/config-dhcp-server.html#GUID-7B1B3F76-4E08-4B4C-B2CB-A8B3C65C4F2B","label":"Cisco - Configuring DHCP (ip helper-address)"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9781587147142","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide - DHCP Relay"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator configures a Cisco router with the command 'ip helper-address 10.1.1.10' on an interface. What is the primary purpose of this command?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer is troubleshooting NTP on a Cisco router that has no access to an external time source. Which command allows the router to act as an NTP server for other devices on the network using its own internal clock?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"ntp server 127.127.1.0"},{"id":"b","text":"ntp authenticate"},{"id":"c","text":"ntp master 5"},{"id":"d","text":"ntp peer 0.0.0.0"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The 'ntp master' command configures a Cisco router to act as an authoritative NTP server using its own hardware clock, even without synchronization to an external reference clock. The optional stratum number (e.g., 5) sets the stratum level the router will advertise to clients. The source material states: 'NTP master to act as server without external sync.' Option A is incorrect — while 127.127.x.x is a loopback clock reference used in some NTP configurations, 'ntp server 127.127.1.0' alone does not configure the router as an NTP server for others. Option B ('ntp authenticate') enables NTP authentication but does not configure the router as a server. Option D is not a valid NTP IOS command for this purpose.$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/bsm/configuration/xe-16/bsm-xe-16-book/bsm-time-calendar-set.html","label":"Cisco - Configuring NTP (ntp master command)"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/iproute_pi/command/iproute-pi-cr-book/ntp-commands.html","label":"Cisco IOS Network Management Command Reference - ntp master"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer is troubleshooting NTP on a Cisco router that has no access to an external time source. Which command allows the router to act as an NTP server for other devices on the network using its own internal clock?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A VoIP administrator needs to ensure that voice traffic receives the highest priority treatment as it traverses the WAN. According to DSCP Per-Hop Behavior standards, which DSCP value should be applied to voice bearer (RTP) traffic?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"DSCP AF41 (decimal 34)"},{"id":"b","text":"DSCP CS3 (decimal 24)"},{"id":"c","text":"DSCP EF (decimal 46)"},{"id":"d","text":"DSCP BE (decimal 0)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Expedited Forwarding (EF), with a DSCP value of 46, is the standard Per-Hop Behavior (PHB) designation for latency-sensitive traffic such as voice bearer (RTP) streams. The source material explicitly states: 'EF (Expedited Forwarding, DSCP 46) for voice.' EF provides a low-loss, low-latency, low-jitter service. AF41 (DSCP 34) is used for high-priority video or data but does not guarantee the strict latency bounds EF provides. CS3 (DSCP 24) maps to call-signaling traffic, not voice bearer. DSCP BE (0) is best-effort and receives no priority treatment.$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/qos_dfsv/configuration/xe-16/qos-dfsv-xe-16-book/qos-dfsv-dif-svc.html","label":"Cisco - QoS DSCP and Per-Hop Behaviors"},{"url":"https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc3246","label":"RFC 3246 - An Expedited Forwarding PHB"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A VoIP administrator needs to ensure that voice traffic receives the highest priority treatment as it traverses the WAN. According to DSCP Per-Hop Behavior standards, which DSCP value should be applied to voice bearer (RTP) traffic?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A router is configured with NAT overload (PAT). A host with the inside local address 192.168.10.5 sends a packet to the internet. After translation, the packet appears on the internet sourced from 203.0.113.1:51200. In NAT terminology, what is 203.0.113.1 referred to as?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Inside local address"},{"id":"b","text":"Outside local address"},{"id":"c","text":"Outside global address"},{"id":"d","text":"Inside global address"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["d"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$In Cisco NAT terminology, the 'inside global' address is the public (routable) IP address that represents an inside host as seen from the outside (internet). The source material defines it as: 'inside global (public inside).' In this scenario, 192.168.10.5 is the inside local address (private address of the host as seen inside), and 203.0.113.1 is the inside global address (the public-facing translation of that inside host). The outside local address is how an outside host appears to inside devices, and the outside global address is the actual public IP of the destination server — neither applies to the translated source address here.$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/network-address-translation-nat/4606-8.html","label":"Cisco - NAT: Local and Global Definitions"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/ipaddr_nat/configuration/xe-16/nat-xe-16-book/iadnat-addr-xlat.html","label":"Cisco - How NAT Works"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A router is configured with NAT overload (PAT). A host with the inside local address 192.168.10.5 sends a packet to the internet. After translation, the packet appears on the internet sourced from 203.0.113.1:51200. In NAT terminology, what is 203.0.113.1 referred to as?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator wants to receive SNMP notifications from a Cisco router. Unlike traps, which notification mechanism requires the receiving management system to acknowledge each message, providing guaranteed delivery?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"SNMP GET"},{"id":"b","text":"SNMP SET"},{"id":"c","text":"SNMP Trap"},{"id":"d","text":"SNMP Inform"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["d"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$SNMP Inform messages are acknowledged notifications — the receiving NMS (Network Management Station) must send back an acknowledgment. If no acknowledgment is received, the sender retransmits the Inform. This is in direct contrast to SNMP Traps, which are fire-and-forget with no acknowledgment or retransmission. The source material states: 'trap (notification), inform (acked notification).' SNMP GET is a polling operation used to retrieve MIB values, not a notification. SNMP SET is used to modify MIB values on the managed device. Neither GET nor SET are notification mechanisms.$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/snmp/configuration/xe-16/snmp-xe-16-book/nm-snmp-cfg-snmp-support.html","label":"Cisco - Configuring SNMP Support (Traps vs Informs)"},{"url":"https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc3416","label":"RFC 3416 - Version 2 of the Protocol Operations for SNMP (InformRequest-PDU)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator wants to receive SNMP notifications from a Cisco router. Unlike traps, which notification mechanism requires the receiving management system to acknowledge each message, providing guaranteed delivery?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator applies an extended ACL to a router interface. According to Cisco best practices, where should an extended ACL be placed relative to traffic flow?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Closest to the destination to minimize unnecessary traffic filtering"},{"id":"b","text":"Closest to the source to prevent unwanted traffic from traversing the network"},{"id":"c","text":"On the loopback interface of the router for centralized enforcement"},{"id":"d","text":"On the core switch rather than the router for faster processing"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Extended ACLs (100-199 or 2000-2699): match src/dst IP, protocol, ports; apply closest to source.' Because extended ACLs can match specific source and destination combinations, placing them close to the source prevents unwanted traffic from consuming bandwidth across the network before being dropped. Standard ACLs, by contrast, should be placed closest to the destination because they only filter on source IP, and placing them near the source could inadvertently block legitimate traffic to other destinations. The other options — loopback interfaces and core switches — are not recommended placement strategies for traffic filtering ACLs.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/access-lists/26448-ACLsamples.html","label":"Cisco – ACL Placement Best Practices"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9781587147142","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide – ACLs"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator applies an extended ACL to a router interface. According to Cisco best practices, where should an extended ACL be placed relative to traffic flow?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which command correctly applies a named extended ACL called BLOCK_WEB to an interface in the inbound direction on a Cisco IOS router?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"ip access-group BLOCK_WEB in"},{"id":"b","text":"ip access-list extended BLOCK_WEB in"},{"id":"c","text":"access-group BLOCK_WEB inbound"},{"id":"d","text":"ip access-class BLOCK_WEB in"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Apply with "ip access-group <num> in/out" on interface.' This same syntax applies whether the ACL is numbered or named — the command is always 'ip access-group <ACL-name-or-number> in|out' at the interface configuration level. Option B ('ip access-list extended') is the command used to create or enter the named ACL configuration, not to apply it to an interface. Option C ('access-group') is not a valid IOS command. Option D ('ip access-class') is used specifically for VTY (Telnet/SSH) lines, not physical interfaces.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/ipaddr/command/ipaddr-cr-book/ipaddr-i1.html","label":"Cisco IOS IP Addressing Services Command Reference – ip access-group"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/access-lists/13608-21.html","label":"Cisco – Configuring IP Access Lists"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which command correctly applies a named extended ACL called BLOCK_WEB to an interface in the inbound direction on a Cisco IOS router?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A switch port is configured with port security. When a violation occurs, the port continues to forward frames from known secure MAC addresses but drops frames from unknown MAC addresses and does not send a syslog message or SNMP trap. Which violation mode is configured?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Shutdown"},{"id":"b","text":"Restrict"},{"id":"c","text":"Protect"},{"id":"d","text":"Err-disable"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material identifies three port security violation modes: shutdown, restrict, and protect. The 'protect' mode drops frames from unknown MAC addresses silently — it does not increment violation counters, generate syslog messages, or send SNMP traps — and keeps the port active for allowed MACs. 'Restrict' mode similarly drops unauthorized frames but does generate syslog messages and increment violation counters. 'Shutdown' (and its resulting err-disable state) disables the port entirely upon violation. Since the scenario describes silent dropping with no notification, 'protect' is the correct answer.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst2960/software/release/12-2_55_se/configuration/guide/scg_2960/swtrafc.html","label":"Cisco – Configuring Port Security"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9781587147142","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide – Port Security"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A switch port is configured with port security. When a violation occurs, the port continues to forward frames from known secure MAC addresses but drops frames from unknown MAC addresses and does not send a syslog message or SNMP trap. Which violation mode is configured?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Cisco switch has DHCP snooping enabled on a VLAN. Which type of message will the switch drop if received on an untrusted port?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"DHCP Discover messages from client hosts"},{"id":"b","text":"DHCP Request messages sent by clients broadcasting for an IP address"},{"id":"c","text":"DHCP Offer and DHCP Acknowledgment messages originating from a DHCP server"},{"id":"d","text":"DHCP Release messages sent by clients returning their IP addresses"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'DHCP snooping: Drops bogus DHCP server responses (offer/ack) on untrusted ports.' DHCP Offer and Acknowledgment (ACK) messages are server-originated responses. On untrusted ports, the switch expects only client-originated traffic (Discover, Request, Release), so any server response arriving on an untrusted port is considered a rogue DHCP server response and is dropped. DHCP Discover, Request, and Release messages are client messages and are permitted on untrusted ports so legitimate client communication can proceed normally.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst6500/ios/12-2SXF/native/configuration/guide/swCG/snoodhcp.html","label":"Cisco – DHCP Snooping and Dynamic ARP Inspection"},{"url":"https://developer.cisco.com/certification/exam-topic-associated-content/?examTopicId=1z0-1085-22","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Study Guide – DHCP Snooping"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Cisco switch has DHCP snooping enabled on a VLAN. Which type of message will the switch drop if received on an untrusted port?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security engineer wants to use a protocol that encrypts the entire AAA payload — including the username, password, and all command authorization data — when communicating between a network device and the AAA server. Which protocol should be selected?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"RADIUS using UDP port 1812"},{"id":"b","text":"TACACS+ using TCP port 49"},{"id":"c","text":"RADIUS using UDP port 1813"},{"id":"d","text":"LDAP using TCP port 389"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'TACACS+ (port 49, TCP, encrypts entire payload, supports command authorization).' TACACS+ encrypts the full body of every AAA packet, providing stronger confidentiality than RADIUS, which 'encrypts password only.' TACACS+ also supports granular per-command authorization, making it preferred for device administration scenarios. RADIUS on port 1812 handles authentication/authorization, port 1813 is used for accounting, but both only encrypt the password field — not the entire payload. LDAP (port 389) is a directory protocol and is not a native AAA protocol for Cisco device management.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security-vpn/remote-authentication-dial-user-service-radius/13838-10.html","label":"Cisco – Comparing TACACS+ and RADIUS"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/security/ise/3-0/admin_guide/b_ISE_admin_3_0/b_ISE_admin_30_overview.html","label":"Cisco Identity Services Engine AAA Protocol Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security engineer wants to use a protocol that encrypts the entire AAA payload — including the username, password, and all command authorization data — when communicating between a network device and the AAA server. Which protocol should be selected?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In an 802.1X deployment, a corporate laptop attempts to authenticate before being granted access to the network. Which 802.1X role does the laptop fulfill?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Authenticator"},{"id":"b","text":"Authentication Server"},{"id":"c","text":"Supplicant"},{"id":"d","text":"RADIUS Proxy"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material defines the 802.1X roles as: 'Supplicant (host) <-> Authenticator (switch/AP) <-> Authentication Server (ISE/RADIUS).' The end-user device — in this case the corporate laptop — is the supplicant. It initiates the EAP exchange by presenting credentials to the authenticator. The authenticator (the switch or wireless access point) relays those credentials to the authentication server (such as Cisco ISE running RADIUS). The authentication server validates the credentials and instructs the authenticator to permit or deny access. A 'RADIUS Proxy' is not an 802.1X role defined in the source material.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/sec_usr_8021x/configuration/15-mt/sec-usr-8021x-15-mt-book/config-ieee-802x-pba.html","label":"Cisco – 802.1X Port-Based Authentication Overview"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/security/identity-services-engine/index.html","label":"Cisco Identity Services Engine – 802.1X Authentication"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$In an 802.1X deployment, a corporate laptop attempts to authenticate before being granted access to the network. Which 802.1X role does the laptop fulfill?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator types 'service password-encryption' on a Cisco router. Which statement accurately describes the effect of this command?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"All passwords in the running configuration are encrypted using a strong, irreversible MD5 hash."},{"id":"b","text":"Passwords are obfuscated using a weak, reversible Type 7 cipher visible in the configuration."},{"id":"c","text":"The enable secret password is upgraded from Type 5 to Type 9 scrypt encryption automatically."},{"id":"d","text":"SSH is enabled on all VTY lines and Telnet is disabled globally."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material clearly states: '"service password-encryption" (weak Type 7 reversible cipher).' This command applies a simple Vigenère-based obfuscation (Type 7) to plaintext passwords stored in the running and startup configurations — such as VTY passwords and username passwords — preventing casual shoulder-surfing but not providing real cryptographic protection since Type 7 can be trivially reversed with freely available tools. It does not use MD5 (that is Type 5, used by 'enable secret') or scrypt (Type 9), and it has no effect on SSH configuration.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security-vpn/secure-shell-ssh/110416-preserved-pwd-type-6.html","label":"Cisco – Password Encryption on Cisco IOS Routers"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/security/authentication/configuration/15-mt/sec-usr-auth-15-mt-book/sec-encrypt-passwords.html","label":"Cisco IOS Security Configuration Guide – Service Password Encryption"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator types 'service password-encryption' on a Cisco router. Which statement accurately describes the effect of this command?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company is deploying a site-to-site IPsec VPN between two branch offices. The network architect wants the original IP headers of packets to be completely encrypted and hidden within a new outer IP packet as the data traverses the public internet. Which IPsec mode should be configured?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Transport mode, because it encrypts the original IP header and payload between the two gateways"},{"id":"b","text":"Tunnel mode, because it encapsulates the entire original IP packet — including the original header — inside a new IP packet"},{"id":"c","text":"Transport mode, because it is used exclusively for gateway-to-gateway communications"},{"id":"d","text":"Tunnel mode, but the original IP header remains visible to intermediate routers for routing purposes"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Modes: transport (host-host, original IP exposed) vs tunnel (gateway-gateway, original IP encrypted).' Tunnel mode wraps the entire original IP packet — both the original header and payload — inside a new IP packet with a new outer header, so the original source and destination IP addresses are hidden from intermediate devices. This is the standard mode for site-to-site VPNs between gateways (routers or firewalls). Transport mode only encrypts the payload and leaves the original IP header intact, making it suitable for host-to-host communications but exposing endpoint addressing information. Option D is incorrect because in tunnel mode the original header is encrypted, not visible.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/about/security-center/fun-ipsec.html","label":"Cisco – IPsec Modes of Operation"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/sec_conn_ikevpn/configuration/xe-16/sec-conn-ikevpn-xe-16-book/sec-conn-ikevpn-vpn.html","label":"Cisco – Site-to-Site IPsec VPN Configuration Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company is deploying a site-to-site IPsec VPN between two branch offices. The network architect wants the original IP headers of packets to be completely encrypted and hidden within a new outer IP packet as the data traverses the public internet. Which IPsec mode should be configured?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A wireless network engineer is upgrading a corporate WLAN from WPA2-Personal to the latest security standard. The new standard should eliminate offline dictionary attacks against the pre-shared key by using a modern key exchange mechanism. Which wireless security standard and authentication method should be implemented?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"WPA2-Enterprise with RADIUS and EAP-TLS certificates"},{"id":"b","text":"WPA3-Personal with Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE)"},{"id":"c","text":"WPA with TKIP for backward compatibility and improved key mixing"},{"id":"d","text":"WEP with a 256-bit key for enhanced encryption strength"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'WPA3 (SAE - Simultaneous Authentication of Equals, replaces PSK).' WPA3-Personal replaces the Pre-Shared Key (PSK) handshake used in WPA2-Personal with SAE, a password-authenticated key agreement protocol derived from Dragonfly. SAE provides forward secrecy and is resistant to offline dictionary attacks because it does not expose a verifiable handshake to passive eavesdroppers. WPA2-Enterprise with EAP-TLS (option A) would also be highly secure but uses certificate-based 802.1X rather than a shared password — it does not replace PSK with SAE, and the question specifies the desire for the latest PSK-replacement standard. WPA with TKIP and WEP are explicitly identified in the source material as 'obsolete/insecure.'$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/wireless/what-is-wpa3.html","label":"Cisco – WPA3 Overview and Deployment Guide"},{"url":"https://www.wi-fi.org/discover-wi-fi/security","label":"Wi-Fi Alliance – WPA3 Specification"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A wireless network engineer is upgrading a corporate WLAN from WPA2-Personal to the latest security standard. The new standard should eliminate offline dictionary attacks against the pre-shared key by using a modern key exchange mechanism. Which wireless security standard and authentication method should be implemented?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer wants to retrieve the current running configuration from a Cisco IOS-XE device using NETCONF. Which TCP port and transport protocol does NETCONF use by default?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Port 443 over TLS"},{"id":"b","text":"Port 830 over SSH"},{"id":"c","text":"Port 80 over HTTP"},{"id":"d","text":"Port 8443 over HTTPS"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$According to the source material, NETCONF (RFC 6241) uses XML over SSH on port 830. This distinguishes it from RESTCONF, which uses HTTPS (port 443), and from standard web traffic on port 80. Port 8443 is not associated with NETCONF. When initiating a NETCONF session to a Cisco IOS-XE device, an SSH session must be established specifically on port 830.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc6241","label":"RFC 6241 – Network Configuration Protocol (NETCONF)"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/prog/configuration/1612/b_1612_programmability_cg/configuring_yang_datamodel.html","label":"Cisco IOS XE NETCONF/YANG Configuration Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer wants to retrieve the current running configuration from a Cisco IOS-XE device using NETCONF. Which TCP port and transport protocol does NETCONF use by default?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An automation script needs to update a single field in a device's configuration via a REST API without replacing the entire resource. Which HTTP method is most appropriate for this operation?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"GET"},{"id":"b","text":"POST"},{"id":"c","text":"PUT"},{"id":"d","text":"PATCH"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["d"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states that PATCH is used to modify (partially update) an existing resource. GET is used to read data, POST to create new resources, and PUT to fully replace an existing resource. Because the engineer wants to update only a single field rather than replace the entire configuration object, PATCH is the correct and most precise HTTP method to use.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://developer.cisco.com/learning/tracks/devnet-associate/network-programmability-basics/04-rest-api-fundamentals/step/1","label":"Cisco DevNet – REST API Fundamentals"},{"url":"https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc5789","label":"RFC 5789 – PATCH Method for HTTP"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
