         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"JSON"},{"id":"b","text":"XML"},{"id":"c","text":"YAML"},{"id":"d","text":"CSV"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'YAML: indentation-sensitive, used in Ansible playbooks.' YAML (YAML Ain't Markup Language) uses whitespace/indentation to define structure, making it human-readable but sensitive to incorrect spacing. JSON uses curly braces and key-value pairs and is primarily used in REST APIs (per the source). XML uses tag-based syntax and is used in NETCONF (per the source). CSV is a tabular format unrelated to network automation playbooks.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.ansible.com/ansible/latest/reference_appendices/YAMLSyntax.html","label":"Ansible Documentation – YAML Syntax"},{"url":"https://yaml.org/spec/1.2.2/","label":"YAML Official Specification"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
