         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Cisco DNA Center Intent API"},{"id":"b","text":"Embedded Event Manager (EEM)"},{"id":"c","text":"NETCONF edit-config operation"},{"id":"d","text":"NAPALM multi-vendor abstraction library"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Cisco EEM (Embedded Event Manager): on-device automation via applets and Tcl scripts.' EEM allows Cisco IOS devices to detect events (such as interface state changes) locally and execute automated responses without any external controller. DNA Center Intent API requires an external controller. NETCONF edit-config is a protocol operation for configuration, not event-driven automation. NAPALM is an external Python library and requires a management host, not on-device execution.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/eem/configuration/xe-17/eem-xe-17-book/eem-overview.html","label":"Cisco IOS Embedded Event Manager (EEM) Configuration Guide"},{"url":"https://developer.cisco.com/docs/ios-xe/embedded-event-manager/","label":"Cisco DevNet – EEM Introduction"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
