INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer is reviewing the OSI model layers. Which layer is responsible for routing packets based on the destination IP address?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Layer 1 – Physical"},{"id":"b","text":"Layer 2 – Data Link"},{"id":"c","text":"Layer 3 – Network"},{"id":"d","text":"Layer 4 – Transport"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Layer 3: router (routes packets based on dst IP).' The Network layer (Layer 3) of the OSI model is where IP addressing and routing decisions are made. Layer 1 deals with physical signals, Layer 2 with MAC addressing, and Layer 4 with end-to-end transport (TCP/UDP). Routers are the archetypal Layer 3 device because they examine the destination IP address to determine the best path for forwarding packets.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/routers/12400-series-internet-routers/8069-osi.html","label":"Cisco – OSI Model Overview"},{"url":"https://learningnetwork.cisco.com/s/ccna-exam-topics","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Exam Topics"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer is reviewing the OSI model layers. Which layer is responsible for routing packets based on the destination IP address?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A technician installs a hub to connect eight workstations. How does this affect collision domains compared to using a Layer 2 switch with eight ports?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"A hub creates eight separate collision domains; a switch creates one shared collision domain."},{"id":"b","text":"Both a hub and a switch create one shared collision domain for all devices."},{"id":"c","text":"A hub creates one shared collision domain; a switch creates eight separate collision domains."},{"id":"d","text":"A hub eliminates collisions because it regenerates signals on all ports simultaneously."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material notes: 'Collision domain (per switch port; eliminated by full duplex).' A switch places each port in its own collision domain, meaning eight switch ports yield eight isolated collision domains. A hub, by contrast, is a Layer 1 device with no MAC awareness ('hub, repeater (broadcast, no MAC awareness)'), so all devices share a single collision domain. Full-duplex operation on switch ports further eliminates collisions entirely.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/tech/lan-switching/lan-switching-technology/tech-brief-listing.html","label":"Cisco – LAN Switching Overview"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9780135792735","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide – Collision Domains"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A technician installs a hub to connect eight workstations. How does this affect collision domains compared to using a Layer 2 switch with eight ports?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which IPv4 address range is defined by RFC 1918 as a private address space with a /12 prefix?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"10.0.0.0/8"},{"id":"b","text":"172.16.0.0/12"},{"id":"c","text":"192.168.0.0/16"},{"id":"d","text":"169.254.0.0/16"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material lists the RFC 1918 private ranges as: '10/8, 172.16-31/12, 192.168/16.' The 172.16.0.0/12 block covers 172.16.0.0 through 172.31.255.255. Option A (10.0.0.0/8) is private but uses a /8 prefix. Option C (192.168.0.0/16) is private with a /16 prefix. Option D (169.254.0.0/16) is the APIPA range, not an RFC 1918 private range.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc1918","label":"RFC 1918 – Address Allocation for Private Internets"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html","label":"Cisco – Understanding IP Addressing"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which IPv4 address range is defined by RFC 1918 as a private address space with a /12 prefix?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An engineer needs to connect two routers using a point-to-point serial link and wants to conserve IP address space. Which subnet mask provides exactly two usable host addresses while following the most common traditional approach for point-to-point links?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"/28 – provides 14 usable addresses"},{"id":"b","text":"/29 – provides 6 usable addresses"},{"id":"c","text":"/30 – provides 2 usable addresses"},{"id":"d","text":"/31 – provides 0 usable addresses due to no host bits remaining"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: '/30 = 4 addrs (2 usable, point-to-point).' A /30 subnet has 4 total addresses: a network address, two host addresses, and a broadcast address — making it the traditional choice for point-to-point links. Option D (/31) is noted as 'RFC 3021 for p2p without broadcast,' which is valid but less traditional and uses 0 broadcast. Options A and B waste more addresses than necessary for a two-endpoint link.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc3021","label":"RFC 3021 – Using 31-Bit Prefixes on IPv4 Point-to-Point Links"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html","label":"Cisco – IP Addressing and Subnetting for New Users"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An engineer needs to connect two routers using a point-to-point serial link and wants to conserve IP address space. Which subnet mask provides exactly two usable host addresses while following the most common traditional approach for point-to-point links?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator examines a switch's MAC address table and notices that the destination MAC address in an incoming frame is not listed. What action will the switch take?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Drop the frame immediately to prevent loops."},{"id":"b","text":"Forward the frame out all ports except the ingress port (flooding)."},{"id":"c","text":"Send the frame to the default gateway for resolution."},{"id":"d","text":"Buffer the frame until the destination MAC is learned."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly describes switching behavior: 'Flooding (unknown unicast/multicast/broadcast), filtering (drop), forwarding.' When a switch receives a frame with an unknown destination MAC, it floods the frame out every port except the one it arrived on. This allows the intended recipient to receive and respond, after which the switch can learn the MAC-to-port mapping and forward future frames directly.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-man-switching/8021q/24062-vlans.html","label":"Cisco – How Switches Work: Understanding MAC Flooding and Switching"},{"url":"https://learningnetwork.cisco.com/s/ccna-exam-topics","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Exam Topics – Network Fundamentals"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator examines a switch's MAC address table and notices that the destination MAC address in an incoming frame is not listed. What action will the switch take?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which IPv6 address type is automatically assigned to every IPv6-enabled interface and is only valid for communication on the local link?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Global Unicast – prefix 2000::/3"},{"id":"b","text":"Unique Local – prefix FC00::/7"},{"id":"c","text":"Link-Local – prefix FE80::/10"},{"id":"d","text":"Multicast – prefix FF00::/8"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material lists IPv6 address types: 'Link-Local (FE80::/10).' A link-local address (FE80::/10) is automatically configured on every IPv6 interface during initialization and is only routable on the local network segment — routers will never forward packets with a link-local source or destination. Global Unicast (2000::/3) is routable on the Internet, Unique Local (FC00::/7) is the IPv6 analog of RFC 1918 private space, and Multicast (FF00::/8) is used for one-to-many communication.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/ipv6_basic/configuration/xe-16/ip6b-xe-16-book/ip6-add-basic-conn-xe.html","label":"Cisco – IPv6 Addressing Overview"},{"url":"https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc4291","label":"RFC 4291 – IP Version 6 Addressing Architecture"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which IPv6 address type is automatically assigned to every IPv6-enabled interface and is only valid for communication on the local link?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Cisco IOS engineer types a command and sees the prompt change to 'Router(config)#'. Which configuration mode has the engineer entered, and what is the correct way to reach this mode from Privileged EXEC mode?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Interface configuration mode; reached by typing 'interface <type><number>'."},{"id":"b","text":"Global configuration mode; reached by typing 'configure terminal'."},{"id":"c","text":"Privileged EXEC mode; reached by typing 'enable'."},{"id":"d","text":"User EXEC mode; reached by typing 'disable'."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material describes Cisco IOS modes: 'User EXEC (>), Privileged EXEC (#), Global config, Interface config modes.' The prompt 'Router(config)#' indicates Global configuration mode, which is entered from Privileged EXEC mode (#) by issuing the 'configure terminal' command. Interface configuration mode would display 'Router(config-if)#'. Privileged EXEC is reached with 'enable' from User EXEC mode, and 'disable' returns to User EXEC.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/fundamentals/configuration/xe-3s/fundamentals-xe-3s-book/cf-cli-basics.html","label":"Cisco – Using the Command-Line Interface (CLI)"},{"url":"https://learningnetwork.cisco.com/s/ccna-exam-topics","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Exam Topics – Network Fundamentals"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Cisco IOS engineer types a command and sees the prompt change to 'Router(config)#'. Which configuration mode has the engineer entered, and what is the correct way to reach this mode from Privileged EXEC mode?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A technician needs to run a copper Ethernet cable at 10 Gbps for a full 100-meter distance inside a building. Which cable category is the minimum requirement to reliably support this specification?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Cat5e – rated for 1 Gbps at 100 m"},{"id":"b","text":"Cat6 – rated for 10 Gbps but only up to 55 m"},{"id":"c","text":"Cat6a – rated for 10 Gbps at 100 m"},{"id":"d","text":"Multi-mode fiber – required for any speed above 1 Gbps over copper"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material specifies: 'Cat5e (1 Gbps, 100m), Cat6 (1-10 Gbps), Cat6a (10 Gbps, 100m).' Cat6a (Augmented Category 6) is the minimum copper standard that supports 10 Gbps for the full 100-meter distance. Cat5e caps at 1 Gbps. Cat6 can support 10 Gbps but only for shorter runs (up to approximately 55 m in practice). Multi-mode fiber can carry high speeds but is a fiber medium, not a copper option.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/collateral/switches/catalyst-9200-series-switches/nb-09-cat9200-ser-data-sheet-cte-en.html","label":"Cisco – Ethernet Cabling Guide"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/articles/article.asp?p=2738354","label":"TIA-568 Cabling Standard Overview – Cisco Press"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A technician needs to run a copper Ethernet cable at 10 Gbps for a full 100-meter distance inside a building. Which cable category is the minimum requirement to reliably support this specification?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator configures a switch port connected to an end-user workstation. Which command correctly sets the port as an access port assigned to VLAN 30?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"switchport mode trunk\nswitchport trunk allowed vlan 30"},{"id":"b","text":"switchport mode access\nswitchport access vlan 30"},{"id":"c","text":"switchport mode dynamic\nswitchport access vlan 30"},{"id":"d","text":"switchport encapsulation dot1q 30\nswitchport mode access"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Access ports carry traffic for a single VLAN and send/receive frames untagged. The correct IOS sequence is 'switchport mode access' followed by 'switchport access vlan 30'. Option A configures a trunk, which is used for multiple VLANs. Option C uses 'dynamic' which relies on DTP negotiation and is not a definitive access-port configuration. Option D incorrectly applies 'encapsulation dot1q', which is used on router subinterfaces for router-on-a-stick, not directly on a switch access port. Source: 'Access ports (single VLAN, untagged).'$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/vlan/b_179_vlan_9300_cg/configuring_vlans.html","label":"Cisco – Configuring VLANs"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator configures a switch port connected to an end-user workstation. Which command correctly sets the port as an access port assigned to VLAN 30?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which 802.1Q frame field carries the 12-bit VLAN identifier, and how large is the complete 802.1Q tag inserted into an Ethernet frame?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The TPID field carries the VLAN ID; the tag is 2 bytes total."},{"id":"b","text":"The TCI field carries the VLAN ID within its 12-bit VID sub-field; the tag is 4 bytes total."},{"id":"c","text":"The PCP field carries the VLAN ID; the tag is 4 bytes total."},{"id":"d","text":"The DEI field carries the VLAN ID; the tag is 8 bytes total."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The 802.1Q tag is exactly 4 bytes. It consists of a 2-byte TPID (set to 0x8100 to indicate an 802.1Q frame) and a 2-byte TCI (Tag Control Information). Within the TCI, the 12-bit VID (VLAN Identifier) sub-field carries the VLAN ID, allowing up to 4,094 usable VLANs. The PCP (3 bits) and DEI (1 bit) are the other TCI sub-fields used for QoS and drop eligibility, not for VLAN identification. Source: '802.1Q tag is 4 bytes (TPID 0x8100 + TCI with PCP/DEI/VID 12-bit).'$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/lanswitch/configuration/xe-17/lanswitch-xe-17-book/vlan-encapsulation.html","label":"IEEE 802.1Q Overview – Cisco"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which 802.1Q frame field carries the 12-bit VLAN identifier, and how large is the complete 802.1Q tag inserted into an Ethernet frame?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Cisco switch port is configured with 'switchport mode dynamic auto'. A neighboring switch port is configured with 'switchport mode dynamic desirable'. What will be the resulting port mode?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Both ports will remain in access mode because neither actively initiates trunking."},{"id":"b","text":"The ports will form a trunk because 'desirable' actively initiates DTP negotiation and 'auto' will respond."},{"id":"c","text":"The ports will form a trunk only if the native VLANs match on both sides."},{"id":"d","text":"The link will enter an err-disabled state due to a DTP mode mismatch."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$DTP (Dynamic Trunking Protocol) governs automatic trunk negotiation. A port in 'dynamic desirable' mode actively sends DTP frames to negotiate a trunk. A port in 'dynamic auto' mode does not initiate but will accept a trunk if the neighbor requests it. Therefore, desirable + auto results in a trunk link. Two 'auto' ports would not form a trunk because neither initiates. Native VLAN mismatch produces a warning but does not prevent the trunk from forming. Source: 'DTP: Dynamic Trunking Protocol (auto/desirable).'$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/vlan/b_179_vlan_9300_cg/configuring_layer_2_protocols.html","label":"Cisco – DTP Configuration Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Cisco switch port is configured with 'switchport mode dynamic auto'. A neighboring switch port is configured with 'switchport mode dynamic desirable'. What will be the resulting port mode?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which Spanning Tree Protocol feature should be enabled on access ports connected to end-user devices to allow them to transition directly to the forwarding state without passing through the listening and learning states?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"BPDU Guard"},{"id":"b","text":"Root Guard"},{"id":"c","text":"PortFast"},{"id":"d","text":"Loop Guard"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$PortFast is designed for access ports connected to end hosts. It allows a port to skip the STP listening and learning states and move immediately to the forwarding state, dramatically reducing the time a host waits to reach the network after a link comes up. BPDU Guard is typically used alongside PortFast to err-disable the port if a BPDU is received (protecting against accidental switch connections). Root Guard prevents an unauthorized switch from becoming the root bridge. Loop Guard protects against unidirectional link failures. Source: 'PortFast (skips listening/learning) on access ports.'$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/spanning-tree-protocol/10588-74.html","label":"Cisco – PortFast and BPDU Guard"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which Spanning Tree Protocol feature should be enabled on access ports connected to end-user devices to allow them to transition directly to the forwarding state without passing through the listening and learning states?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator wants to provide inter-VLAN routing on a single router using subinterfaces. Which command correctly configures subinterface Gi0/0.10 for VLAN 10?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"interface GigabitEthernet0/0.10\n ip address 192.168.10.1 255.255.255.0\n switchport access vlan 10"},{"id":"b","text":"interface GigabitEthernet0/0.10\n encapsulation dot1q 10\n ip address 192.168.10.1 255.255.255.0"},{"id":"c","text":"interface GigabitEthernet0/0.10\n encapsulation isl 10\n ip address 192.168.10.1 255.255.255.0"},{"id":"d","text":"interface GigabitEthernet0/0\n switchport trunk encapsulation dot1q\n switchport mode trunk vlan 10"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Router-on-a-stick inter-VLAN routing requires creating a logical subinterface for each VLAN, configuring 'encapsulation dot1q <vlan-id>' to associate the subinterface with the correct VLAN tag, and assigning an IP address as the default gateway for that VLAN. Option A incorrectly uses 'switchport access vlan', which is a Layer 2 switch command, not valid on a router subinterface. Option C references ISL, which is a legacy Cisco-proprietary trunking protocol not used on modern Cisco routers. Option D configures the physical interface with switch commands, which is invalid on a router. Source: 'Router-on-a-stick: subinterfaces with encapsulation dot1q.'$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/inter-vlan-routing/14976-50.html","label":"Cisco – Router-on-a-Stick Inter-VLAN Routing"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator wants to provide inter-VLAN routing on a single router using subinterfaces. Which command correctly configures subinterface Gi0/0.10 for VLAN 10?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer is configuring EtherChannel between two Cisco switches using an open-standard protocol. The engineer configures one side with 'channel-group 1 mode active'. Which mode must be configured on the other side for the EtherChannel to successfully form?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"mode desirable"},{"id":"b","text":"mode on"},{"id":"c","text":"mode passive"},{"id":"d","text":"mode auto"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The 'active' mode is an LACP (Link Aggregation Control Protocol, IEEE 802.3ad) mode — LACP is the open-standard EtherChannel protocol. In LACP, a port in 'active' mode unconditionally sends LACP PDUs. A port in 'passive' mode will respond to LACP PDUs but does not initiate them. The combination of active + passive (or active + active) forms an LACP EtherChannel. Mode 'on' forces the channel without any negotiation protocol and will not work with 'active' because 'active' sends LACP frames that the 'on' side ignores. Modes 'desirable' and 'auto' belong to PAgP (Cisco proprietary), not LACP. Source: 'LACP (open standard, 802.3ad) … Modes: LACP active/passive.'$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/ha/b_179_ha_9300_cg/configuring_etherchannel.html","label":"Cisco – EtherChannel Configuration Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer is configuring EtherChannel between two Cisco switches using an open-standard protocol. The engineer configures one side with 'channel-group 1 mode active'. Which mode must be configured on the other side for the EtherChannel to successfully form?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A wireless network uses 2.4 GHz 802.11n access points. An administrator wants to deploy three APs in an open office to provide full coverage with minimal co-channel interference. Which combination of channels should be assigned?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Channels 1, 2, and 3"},{"id":"b","text":"Channels 1, 6, and 11"},{"id":"c","text":"Channels 1, 5, and 10"},{"id":"d","text":"Channels 3, 7, and 11"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$In the 2.4 GHz band used in the United States, channels 1, 6, and 11 are the only three non-overlapping channels. Each channel occupies 22 MHz of spectrum, and only channels 1, 6, and 11 are spaced far enough apart (5 channels = 25 MHz) to avoid overlap. Using any other combination (e.g., 1, 5, 10 or 3, 7, 11) results in partial overlap and co-channel or adjacent-channel interference, degrading performance. Source: 'Channels: non-overlapping 1, 6, 11 in 2.4 GHz US.'$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/wireless-mobility/wireless-lan/intro-to-channels.html","label":"Cisco – Wireless LAN Channel Deployment"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A wireless network uses 2.4 GHz 802.11n access points. An administrator wants to deploy three APs in an open office to provide full coverage with minimal co-channel interference. Which combination of channels should be assigned?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$What is the primary function of CAPWAP in a Cisco enterprise wireless deployment using lightweight access points?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"CAPWAP encrypts 802.1X EAP authentication messages between the RADIUS server and wireless clients."},{"id":"b","text":"CAPWAP provides a tunnel between lightweight APs and a Wireless LAN Controller (WLC) to carry both control and data traffic."},{"id":"c","text":"CAPWAP is a channel-bonding protocol that combines multiple 2.4 GHz channels to increase throughput."},{"id":"d","text":"CAPWAP is used exclusively on autonomous APs to provide centralized management via a web interface."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$In a split-MAC (lightweight) architecture, access points offload most intelligence to a centralized Wireless LAN Controller. CAPWAP (Control and Provisioning of Wireless Access Points) is the standard tunnel protocol that carries two planes: a control channel (management, configuration, firmware) and a data channel (client traffic forwarded to the WLC). Autonomous APs run full IOS locally and do not use CAPWAP. CAPWAP is not a channel-bonding protocol, nor is it specifically for RADIUS communication. Source: 'Lightweight APs use CAPWAP tunnel to WLC (control + data). Autonomous APs run IOS independently.'$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/wireless-mobility/wireless-lan/213927-capwap-protocol-overview.html","label":"Cisco – CAPWAP Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$What is the primary function of CAPWAP in a Cisco enterprise wireless deployment using lightweight access points?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator notices a switch port transitions to err-disabled state shortly after a PC is replaced with a small unmanaged switch. Which STP feature is most likely responsible for this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Root Guard — it detected a superior BPDU and blocked the port."},{"id":"b","text":"BPDU Guard — it detected a BPDU on a PortFast-enabled port and err-disabled it."},{"id":"c","text":"Loop Guard — it detected a unidirectional link failure and err-disabled the port."},{"id":"d","text":"UDLD — it detected a mismatched duplex setting and err-disabled the port."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$BPDU Guard is typically enabled on access ports that also have PortFast configured. Its purpose is to protect the network by err-disabling any port that receives a BPDU — an event that indicates an unauthorized switch has been connected. When the PC was replaced with an unmanaged switch, the switch began sending BPDUs, triggering BPDU Guard to shut down the port. Root Guard also responds to BPDUs but places the port in a root-inconsistent state (not err-disabled) when a superior BPDU is received on a non-root port. Loop Guard responds to missing BPDUs, not received ones. UDLD addresses unidirectional links, not BPDU reception. Source: 'BPDU Guard, Root Guard, Loop Guard, BPDU Filter, UDLD.'$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/spanning-tree-protocol/10588-74.html","label":"Cisco – BPDU Guard and PortFast"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator notices a switch port transitions to err-disabled state shortly after a PC is replaced with a small unmanaged switch. Which STP feature is most likely responsible for this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which VTP mode allows a Cisco switch to create, modify, and delete VLANs locally and forward VTP advertisements, but does NOT synchronize its VLAN database from the VTP server?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"VTP Server mode"},{"id":"b","text":"VTP Client mode"},{"id":"c","text":"VTP Transparent mode"},{"id":"d","text":"VTP Off mode"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$VTP Transparent mode allows local VLAN management (create, modify, delete) independent of the VTP domain. Transparent-mode switches forward VTP advertisements received on trunk ports to other switches, but they do not apply those updates to their own VLAN database nor do they send their own VLAN information as VTP updates. VTP Server mode manages VLANs and synchronizes clients. VTP Client mode cannot create or delete VLANs and synchronizes its database from the server. VTP Off mode (available in VTPv3) does not participate in VTP at all and does not forward advertisements. Source: 'VTP modes: server, client, transparent; VTP pruning.'$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/vlan/b_179_vlan_9300_cg/configuring_vtp.html","label":"Cisco – VTP Configuration Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which VTP mode allows a Cisco switch to create, modify, and delete VLANs locally and forward VTP advertisements, but does NOT synchronize its VLAN database from the VTP server?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator needs to forward DHCP client broadcasts from the 192.168.10.0/24 subnet to a DHCP server located at 10.0.0.5 on a different subnet. Which IOS command, applied to the router interface facing the client subnet, accomplishes this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"ip dhcp pool CLIENTS"},{"id":"b","text":"ip helper-address 10.0.0.5"},{"id":"c","text":"ip dhcp relay 10.0.0.5"},{"id":"d","text":"service dhcp 10.0.0.5"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'ip helper-address for relaying DHCP across subnets.' The command 'ip helper-address 10.0.0.5' is configured on the router interface in the client subnet (the one that receives the broadcast). It converts the DHCP broadcast into a unicast packet directed to the DHCP server. Option A creates a local DHCP pool, not a relay. Option C is not a valid IOS command. Option D is not a valid IOS relay command.$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/ipaddr_dhcp/configuration/xe-16/dhcp-xe-16-book/config-dhcp-server.html","label":"Cisco IOS IP Addressing Services Configuration Guide – Configuring DHCP"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator needs to forward DHCP client broadcasts from the 192.168.10.0/24 subnet to a DHCP server located at 10.0.0.5 on a different subnet. Which IOS command, applied to the router interface facing the client subnet, accomplishes this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer is analyzing SNMP traffic captures and notices that management notifications from a Cisco router do NOT require acknowledgment from the NMS. Which SNMP message type is being used?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"inform"},{"id":"b","text":"get-bulk"},{"id":"c","text":"trap"},{"id":"d","text":"set"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'trap (notification), inform (acked notification).' A trap is a one-way, unacknowledged notification sent from the agent (router) to the NMS. An inform is similar but requires an acknowledgment — making it reliable. get-bulk is used for polling large amounts of data, and set is used to modify MIB objects. Because no acknowledgment is required in the scenario, the answer is trap.$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/snmp/configuration/xe-16/snmp-xe-16-book/nm-snmp-cfg-snmp-support.html","label":"Cisco IOS Network Management Configuration Guide – Configuring SNMP"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer is analyzing SNMP traffic captures and notices that management notifications from a Cisco router do NOT require acknowledgment from the NMS. Which SNMP message type is being used?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A VoIP engineer wants to ensure that real-time voice packets experience the absolute minimum queuing delay on a WAN interface. Which QoS queuing mechanism is specifically designed to meet this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"FIFO (First-In, First-Out)"},{"id":"b","text":"WFQ (Weighted Fair Queueing)"},{"id":"c","text":"LLQ (Low Latency Queueing)"},{"id":"d","text":"Shaping"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Queueing: LLQ (Low Latency Queueing) for voice.' LLQ combines Priority Queueing with CBWFQ, creating a strict priority queue that services voice packets first before any other traffic class, thereby minimizing latency and jitter. FIFO processes packets in arrival order with no priority distinction. WFQ provides weighted fairness but lacks a strict priority queue. Shaping buffers excess traffic to smooth output rate, which actually introduces delay — the opposite of what voice needs.$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/qos_conmgt/configuration/xe-16/qos-conmgt-xe-16-book/qos-conmgt-oview.html","label":"Cisco QoS: Low Latency Queueing (LLQ) Configuration Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A VoIP engineer wants to ensure that real-time voice packets experience the absolute minimum queuing delay on a WAN interface. Which QoS queuing mechanism is specifically designed to meet this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Cisco router is configured with NAT overload (PAT). An inside host with the private address 10.1.1.10 sends a packet that is translated so it appears to originate from the public IP 203.0.113.1 as seen by internet hosts. In Cisco NAT terminology, what is 10.1.1.10 called?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Inside global address"},{"id":"b","text":"Outside local address"},{"id":"c","text":"Outside global address"},{"id":"d","text":"Inside local address"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["d"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material defines: 'Inside local (private inside).' The inside local address is the private IP address assigned to the host on the inside network — in this case, 10.1.1.10. The inside global address (203.0.113.1) is the public-facing address of that same host after translation, as seen by outside devices. Outside local and outside global refer to addresses of hosts on the outside/internet network, not to the inside host.$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/network-address-translation-nat/4606-8.html","label":"Cisco NAT: Inside and Outside Addresses – IP Addressing Services Configuration Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Cisco router is configured with NAT overload (PAT). An inside host with the private address 10.1.1.10 sends a packet that is translated so it appears to originate from the public IP 203.0.113.1 as seen by internet hosts. In Cisco NAT terminology, what is 10.1.1.10 called?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A syslog message with severity level 3 is generated on a Cisco router. An engineer needs to understand how critical this event is relative to the full severity scale. Which statement correctly describes severity level 3?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"It is the least severe level, used only for routine debugging output."},{"id":"b","text":"It represents an Error condition, less critical than Emergency (0), Alert (1), and Critical (2) but more critical than Warning (4) through Debug (7)."},{"id":"c","text":"It represents a Warning condition and is the midpoint of the eight severity levels."},{"id":"d","text":"It is equivalent to severity 0 because all levels above 3 are informational only."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Severity 0 (emergency) to 7 (debug).' The eight standard syslog severity levels in order from most to least critical are: 0-Emergency, 1-Alert, 2-Critical, 3-Error, 4-Warning, 5-Notice, 6-Informational, 7-Debug. Severity 3 (Error) is indeed more critical than levels 4–7 and less critical than 0–2. Option A incorrectly describes level 7 (Debug). Option C incorrectly names level 3 as Warning (that is level 4). Option D is factually incorrect.$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/sysmgt_logsys/configuration/xe-16/sysmgt-logsys-xe-16-book/sysmgt-cfg-logging.html","label":"Cisco IOS System Management Configuration Guide – Configuring Syslog"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A syslog message with severity level 3 is generated on a Cisco router. An engineer needs to understand how critical this event is relative to the full severity scale. Which statement correctly describes severity level 3?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator needs to filter traffic based on both source IP address and destination TCP port number. Which type of ACL should be used, and where should it be applied relative to the traffic source?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Standard ACL applied closest to the destination"},{"id":"b","text":"Extended ACL applied closest to the source"},{"id":"c","text":"Standard ACL applied closest to the source"},{"id":"d","text":"Extended ACL applied closest to the destination"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Extended ACLs (numbered 100-199 or 2000-2699) can match on source/destination IP, protocol, and port numbers, making them capable of filtering on both source IP and destination TCP port. Because extended ACLs are more granular, best practice is to place them closest to the source to discard unwanted traffic early and avoid unnecessary traversal of the network. Standard ACLs match only on source IP and are placed closest to the destination. Placing an extended ACL at the destination (option d) would work functionally but wastes bandwidth by allowing traffic to traverse the network before being dropped.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html","label":"Cisco - ACL Configuration Guide"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9781587147142","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide - ACLs"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator needs to filter traffic based on both source IP address and destination TCP port number. Which type of ACL should be used, and where should it be applied relative to the traffic source?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator configures the following on a switch interface: 'switchport port-security violation restrict'. What happens when a frame from an unknown MAC address arrives on that port?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The port is immediately placed into an err-disabled state"},{"id":"b","text":"The frame is dropped, a syslog message is generated, and the violation counter is incremented, but the port remains up"},{"id":"c","text":"The frame is forwarded and the MAC address is added to the secure MAC table"},{"id":"d","text":"The frame is silently dropped with no logging or counter increment"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states port security supports three violation modes: shutdown, restrict, and protect. The 'restrict' mode drops frames from unknown MAC addresses, increments the security violation counter, and generates a syslog alert — but does NOT disable the port. This differs from 'shutdown' mode, which places the port into err-disabled state (option a), and 'protect' mode, which silently drops frames without logging or incrementing a counter (option d). Option c would describe normal forwarding behavior when no violation has occurred.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-x/configuration_guide/sec/b_173_sec_9300_cg/configuring_port_security.html","label":"Cisco - Port Security Configuration Guide"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9781587147142","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide - Switch Security"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator configures the following on a switch interface: 'switchport port-security violation restrict'. What happens when a frame from an unknown MAC address arrives on that port?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$DHCP snooping is enabled on a Cisco switch. Which type of DHCP message will be dropped if it arrives on an untrusted port?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"DHCP Discover"},{"id":"b","text":"DHCP Request"},{"id":"c","text":"DHCP Offer"},{"id":"d","text":"DHCP Release"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states that DHCP snooping drops 'bogus DHCP server responses (offer/ack) on untrusted ports.' A DHCP Offer is a server-to-client response message; if it arrives on an untrusted port, the switch assumes a rogue DHCP server is present and discards the packet. DHCP Discover (option a) and DHCP Request (option b) are client-originated messages and are permitted on untrusted ports. DHCP Release (option d) is also a client-originated message. Only server-side responses (Offer and Ack) are blocked on untrusted ports.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-x/configuration_guide/sec/b_173_sec_9300_cg/configuring_dhcp_features.html","label":"Cisco - DHCP Snooping Configuration Guide"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9781587147142","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide - DHCP Snooping"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$DHCP snooping is enabled on a Cisco switch. Which type of DHCP message will be dropped if it arrives on an untrusted port?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security engineer is selecting a AAA protocol that encrypts the entire payload of every packet exchanged between the network device and the AAA server, and also supports per-command authorization. Which protocol meets BOTH requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"RADIUS using UDP port 1812"},{"id":"b","text":"TACACS+ using TCP port 49"},{"id":"c","text":"RADIUS using TCP port 1813"},{"id":"d","text":"LDAP using TCP port 389"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$According to the source material, TACACS+ runs on TCP port 49, encrypts the entire payload (not just the password), and supports command-level authorization — satisfying both requirements. RADIUS (options a and c) uses UDP ports 1812 (authentication) and 1813 (accounting) and encrypts only the password field, making it insufficient for full-payload confidentiality. LDAP (option d) is a directory protocol, not a AAA protocol for network device access, and does not provide the same feature set.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security-vpn/remote-authentication-dial-user-service-radius/13838-10.html","label":"Cisco - TACACS+ and RADIUS Comparison"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9781587147142","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide - AAA"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security engineer is selecting a AAA protocol that encrypts the entire payload of every packet exchanged between the network device and the AAA server, and also supports per-command authorization. Which protocol meets BOTH requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In an 802.1X deployment, which device is responsible for relaying EAP messages between the end-user host and the authentication server?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Supplicant"},{"id":"b","text":"Authentication Server (ISE/RADIUS)"},{"id":"c","text":"Authenticator (switch or wireless AP)"},{"id":"d","text":"DHCP server"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material defines the three 802.1X roles as: Supplicant (the end-host requesting access), Authenticator (the switch or AP that relays EAP messages between supplicant and authentication server), and Authentication Server (ISE or RADIUS, which validates credentials). The Authenticator sits in the middle and proxies EAP frames — it does not validate credentials itself. The supplicant (option a) is the client device, not the relay. The authentication server (option b) performs validation but does not relay to the supplicant directly. The DHCP server (option d) is unrelated to 802.1X authentication.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/8021x/116681-config-aaa-8021x-00.html","label":"Cisco - Understanding 802.1X Authentication"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9781587147142","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide - 802.1X"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$In an 802.1X deployment, which device is responsible for relaying EAP messages between the end-user host and the authentication server?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator uses the 'service password-encryption' command on a Cisco IOS device. Which statement BEST describes the protection this provides for passwords stored in the running configuration?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Passwords are hashed with MD5 and are irreversible"},{"id":"b","text":"Passwords are encrypted with a strong scrypt algorithm, providing modern protection"},{"id":"c","text":"Passwords are obfuscated with a weak, reversible Type 7 cipher that can be decoded with freely available tools"},{"id":"d","text":"Passwords are encrypted using AES-256, providing strong confidentiality"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states that 'service password-encryption' applies a weak Type 7 reversible cipher. This means that while passwords will not appear in plain text in the configuration, they can be trivially decoded using widely available Cisco Type 7 decoders. It does NOT use MD5 (option a — that is 'enable secret' Type 5), scrypt (option b — that is Type 9 enable secret), or AES-256 (option d). Administrators should rely on 'enable secret' with Type 9 for stronger password protection.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security-vpn/remote-authentication-dial-user-service-radius/107614-64.html","label":"Cisco - Protecting Passwords in Cisco IOS Devices"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9781587147142","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide - Device Security"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator uses the 'service password-encryption' command on a Cisco IOS device. Which statement BEST describes the protection this provides for passwords stored in the running configuration?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company needs to establish a VPN between two branch office routers so that all traffic — including the original IP headers — is encrypted and encapsulated inside a new IP packet. Which IPsec mode satisfies this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Transport mode, because it encrypts only the payload, leaving the original IP header intact"},{"id":"b","text":"Tunnel mode, because it encrypts the entire original packet (including IP header) and wraps it in a new IP header"},{"id":"c","text":"Transport mode, because it is used for gateway-to-gateway connections"},{"id":"d","text":"Tunnel mode, because it leaves the original IP header exposed for routing purposes"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that IPsec tunnel mode is used for gateway-to-gateway (site-to-site) connections and encrypts the original IP packet — including the IP header — then wraps it in a new outer IP header. This hides the original source and destination addresses. Transport mode (options a and c) is used for host-to-host communication and encrypts only the payload, leaving the original IP header exposed. Option d incorrectly describes tunnel mode as exposing the original header, which is the defining characteristic of transport mode, not tunnel mode.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security-vpn/ipsec-negotiation-ike-protocols/115265-understanding-ipsec-main-aggressive.html","label":"Cisco - IPsec Tunnel and Transport Mode"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9781587147142","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide - VPN and IPsec"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company needs to establish a VPN between two branch office routers so that all traffic — including the original IP headers — is encrypted and encapsulated inside a new IP packet. Which IPsec mode satisfies this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization wants to deploy wireless security that uses Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE) to eliminate vulnerabilities associated with pre-shared key handshakes. Which wireless security standard implements SAE?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"WEP"},{"id":"b","text":"WPA using TKIP"},{"id":"c","text":"WPA2-Personal using AES-CCMP"},{"id":"d","text":"WPA3"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["d"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material directly states that 'WPA3 uses SAE (Simultaneous Authentication of Equals), which replaces PSK.' SAE provides forward secrecy and resistance to offline dictionary attacks, addressing weaknesses in the WPA2 4-way handshake. WEP (option a) is obsolete and uses static RC4 keys with no SAE. WPA (option b) uses TKIP, which is also considered insecure. WPA2-Personal (option c) uses AES-CCMP with PSK (the 4-way handshake), which SAE was specifically designed to replace.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/wireless/what-is-wi-fi-security.html","label":"Cisco - Wi-Fi Security Overview and WPA3"},{"url":"https://www.wi-fi.org/discover-wi-fi/security","label":"Wi-Fi Alliance - WPA3 Security"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization wants to deploy wireless security that uses Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE) to eliminate vulnerabilities associated with pre-shared key handshakes. Which wireless security standard implements SAE?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Dynamic ARP Inspection (DAI) is enabled on a VLAN. Which table does DAI use to validate ARP packets and determine whether a sender's IP-to-MAC binding is legitimate?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The MAC address table (CAM table)"},{"id":"b","text":"The DHCP snooping binding table"},{"id":"c","text":"The ARP cache of the default gateway"},{"id":"d","text":"The spanning tree port state table"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that DAI 'validates ARP packets against the DHCP snooping binding table' to mitigate ARP poisoning attacks. The DHCP snooping binding table maps IP addresses to MAC addresses and switch ports, providing the ground truth for legitimate IP-to-MAC bindings. The CAM table (option a) maps MAC addresses to switch ports but does not track IP addresses, so it cannot validate ARP bindings. The default gateway's ARP cache (option c) is on a different device and is not consulted by the switch. The spanning tree port state table (option d) is related to loop prevention, not ARP validation.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-x/configuration_guide/sec/b_173_sec_9300_cg/configuring_dynamic_arp_inspection.html","label":"Cisco - Dynamic ARP Inspection Configuration Guide"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9781587147142","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide - DAI and IP Source Guard"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Dynamic ARP Inspection (DAI) is enabled on a VLAN. Which table does DAI use to validate ARP packets and determine whether a sender's IP-to-MAC binding is legitimate?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer wants to retrieve the current running configuration from a Cisco IOS-XE device using NETCONF. Which TCP port and transport protocol does NETCONF use by default?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"TCP port 443 over HTTPS"},{"id":"b","text":"TCP port 830 over SSH"},{"id":"c","text":"TCP port 161 over UDP"},{"id":"d","text":"TCP port 80 over HTTP"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$According to the source material, NETCONF (RFC 6241) uses XML over SSH on port 830. This is the standardized transport for NETCONF sessions on Cisco IOS-XE devices. Port 443 is used by HTTPS/RESTCONF, port 161/UDP is SNMP, and port 80 is plain HTTP — none of these are the default NETCONF transport.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/prog/configuration/169/b_169_programmability_cg/configuring_yang_datamodel.html","label":"Cisco IOS XE NETCONF/YANG"},{"url":"https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc6241","label":"RFC 6241 - Network Configuration Protocol (NETCONF)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
