INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer needs to write a Python script that connects to multiple Cisco IOS devices via SSH to retrieve interface statistics. Which Python library, listed in the CCNA source material, is specifically designed as an SSH client library for network devices?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"requests"},{"id":"b","text":"Netmiko"},{"id":"c","text":"Nornir"},{"id":"d","text":"NAPALM"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material identifies 'Netmiko: SSH library for network devices' as the specific purpose of that library. The 'requests' library is an HTTP client for REST APIs. 'NAPALM' provides multi-vendor abstraction but is higher-level. 'Nornir' is an orchestration framework. Since the task specifically requires SSH connectivity to devices, Netmiko is the most direct and appropriate choice.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://github.com/ktbyers/netmiko","label":"Netmiko GitHub Repository"},{"url":"https://developer.cisco.com/learning/labs/intro-to-coding-for-network-engineers/introduction/","label":"Cisco DevNet - Python for Network Engineers"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer needs to write a Python script that connects to multiple Cisco IOS devices via SSH to retrieve interface statistics. Which Python library, listed in the CCNA source material, is specifically designed as an SSH client library for network devices?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$What is the primary architectural difference between a traditional network and a Software-Defined Networking (SDN) architecture, as described in CCNA study materials?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Traditional networks use a centralized control plane, while SDN uses a distributed control plane on each device."},{"id":"b","text":"Traditional networks use a distributed control plane on each device, while SDN uses a centralized control plane in a controller."},{"id":"c","text":"Traditional networks do not forward packets, while SDN uses dedicated data-plane hardware for all forwarding decisions."},{"id":"d","text":"Both traditional and SDN architectures use a centralized controller, but SDN also allows each device to make independent routing decisions."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material clearly states: 'Traditional: distributed control plane (each device runs routing)' and 'SDN: centralized control plane (controller programs data plane).' In traditional networking, each router or switch independently runs control-plane protocols (e.g., OSPF, STP). In SDN, a central controller holds the control plane logic and programs forwarding rules down to devices in the data plane. The other options reverse or incorrectly conflate these definitions.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/solutions/enterprise-networks/software-defined-access/index.html","label":"Cisco SD-Access Solution Overview"},{"url":"https://developer.cisco.com/learning/labs/sdn-introduction/introduction/","label":"Cisco DevNet - Introduction to SDN"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$What is the primary architectural difference between a traditional network and a Software-Defined Networking (SDN) architecture, as described in CCNA study materials?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Cisco IOS-XE device has Cisco EEM (Embedded Event Manager) configured. An applet is triggered whenever interface GigabitEthernet0/1 goes down, and it automatically sends a syslog alert. Which statement best describes the role of EEM in this scenario?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"EEM acts as an external orchestration controller that pushes configuration changes from a centralized server."},{"id":"b","text":"EEM provides on-device automation by responding to local events with applets or Tcl scripts without requiring an external system."},{"id":"c","text":"EEM is a northbound REST API interface used by DNA Center to monitor device events."},{"id":"d","text":"EEM uses NETCONF sessions on port 830 to receive event triggers from a remote management station."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Cisco EEM (Embedded Event Manager): on-device automation via applets and Tcl scripts.' The key distinction is that EEM runs directly on the device itself — it does not require an external controller, REST API call, or NETCONF session to respond to events. When the interface goes down (a local event), the EEM applet fires and executes the configured action (e.g., syslog) entirely within the device's IOS-XE process.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/eem/configuration/xe-17/eem-xe-17-book/eem-overview.html","label":"Cisco EEM Configuration Guide for IOS-XE"},{"url":"https://developer.cisco.com/docs/ios-xe/#!embedded-event-manager","label":"Cisco DevNet - Embedded Event Manager"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Cisco IOS-XE device has Cisco EEM (Embedded Event Manager) configured. An applet is triggered whenever interface GigabitEthernet0/1 goes down, and it automatically sends a syslog alert. Which statement best describes the role of EEM in this scenario?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer is reviewing the OSI model layers to troubleshoot a connectivity issue. At which OSI layer does a standard Layer 2 switch primarily operate, and what is the primary identifier it uses to forward frames?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Layer 1 (Physical); it uses IP addresses to forward frames"},{"id":"b","text":"Layer 2 (Data Link); it uses MAC addresses to forward frames"},{"id":"c","text":"Layer 3 (Network); it uses MAC addresses to forward frames"},{"id":"d","text":"Layer 2 (Data Link); it uses IP addresses to forward frames"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A standard Layer 2 switch operates at the Data Link layer (Layer 2) of the OSI model. It builds and maintains a MAC address table (also called a CAM table) by inspecting source MAC addresses of incoming frames, and it forwards frames based on destination MAC addresses. Layer 3 devices such as routers use IP addresses (Layer 3) for forwarding decisions. Layer 1 (Physical) devices such as hubs deal only with electrical signals and have no addressing awareness. Option (d) is incorrect because Layer 2 devices do not use IP addresses for forwarding.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/ethernet/10561-3.html","label":"Cisco – Catalyst Switching FAQs: How Switches Learn and Forward Frames"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9780135792735","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide – OSI and TCP/IP Models"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer is reviewing the OSI model layers to troubleshoot a connectivity issue. At which OSI layer does a standard Layer 2 switch primarily operate, and what is the primary identifier it uses to forward frames?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An engineer is subnetting the 192.168.10.0/24 network to create subnets that each support at least 30 hosts. Which subnet mask should be applied to meet this requirement while using the least number of host bits possible?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"/25 (255.255.255.128) — provides 126 usable hosts per subnet"},{"id":"b","text":"/26 (255.255.255.192) — provides 62 usable hosts per subnet"},{"id":"c","text":"/27 (255.255.255.224) — provides 30 usable hosts per subnet"},{"id":"d","text":"/28 (255.255.255.240) — provides 14 usable hosts per subnet"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$To find the smallest subnet that supports at least 30 hosts, use the formula: usable hosts = 2^n – 2, where n is the number of host bits. A /27 mask leaves 5 host bits: 2^5 – 2 = 30 usable host addresses, which exactly meets the requirement. A /28 provides only 14 usable hosts, which is insufficient. A /26 and /25 both satisfy the requirement but waste host bits — /27 is the most efficient (least host bits while still satisfying ≥30 hosts). The two subtracted addresses are the network address and the directed broadcast address, which cannot be assigned to hosts.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html","label":"Cisco – IP Addressing and Subnetting for New Users"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9780135792735","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide Volume 1 – IPv4 Subnetting"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An engineer is subnetting the 192.168.10.0/24 network to create subnets that each support at least 30 hosts. Which subnet mask should be applied to meet this requirement while using the least number of host bits possible?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator is configuring a Cisco Catalyst switch and needs to ensure that only one MAC address is learned on FastEthernet0/5, and that the port is automatically disabled if a violation occurs. Which combination of commands achieves this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"switchport mode access\nswitchport port-security\nswitchport port-security maximum 1\nswitchport port-security violation restrict"},{"id":"b","text":"switchport mode access\nswitchport port-security\nswitchport port-security maximum 1\nswitchport port-security violation shutdown"},{"id":"c","text":"switchport mode trunk\nswitchport port-security\nswitchport port-security maximum 1\nswitchport port-security violation shutdown"},{"id":"d","text":"switchport mode access\nswitchport port-security\nswitchport port-security maximum 2\nswitchport port-security violation shutdown"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option B is correct because port security requires the port to be in access mode (not trunk), a maximum of 1 MAC address enforces the single-device requirement, and the 'violation shutdown' action places the port into an err-disabled state when a violation is detected — which means the port is automatically disabled. Option A uses 'violation restrict', which drops offending frames and logs the violation but does NOT disable the port. Option C incorrectly sets the port to trunk mode, which is incompatible with port security. Option D allows a maximum of 2 MAC addresses, which does not satisfy the 'only one MAC address' requirement.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst7000/software/configuration/guide/swportsecurity.html","label":"Cisco - Configuring Port Security"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9781587147142","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide - Port Security"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator is configuring a Cisco Catalyst switch and needs to ensure that only one MAC address is learned on FastEthernet0/5, and that the port is automatically disabled if a violation occurs. Which combination of commands achieves this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A switch port is configured as an 802.1Q trunk between two Cisco switches. VLAN 10 traffic is expected to traverse the trunk, but hosts in VLAN 10 on Switch B cannot communicate with hosts in VLAN 10 on Switch A. The administrator runs 'show interfaces trunk' on Switch A and sees that VLAN 10 is not listed in the 'VLANs allowed and active in management domain' column. What is the most likely cause of this problem?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"VLAN 10 has not been created in the VLAN database on Switch A."},{"id":"b","text":"The native VLAN is set to VLAN 10 on Switch A."},{"id":"c","text":"The trunk encapsulation on Switch A is set to ISL instead of 802.1Q."},{"id":"d","text":"Spanning Tree Protocol has placed VLAN 10 in a forwarding state on Switch A."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option A is correct. The 'VLANs allowed and active in management domain' column in 'show interfaces trunk' output only lists VLANs that are both permitted on the trunk AND exist (are active) in the local VLAN database. If VLAN 10 has not been created on Switch A with the 'vlan 10' command, it will not appear as active even if it is allowed on the trunk, preventing traffic from being forwarded. Option B is incorrect because setting VLAN 10 as the native VLAN would still allow it to pass traffic (untagged), and it would appear differently in the output rather than being absent entirely. Option C is incorrect because an encapsulation mismatch would typically cause the trunk to not form at all, affecting all VLANs rather than just VLAN 10. Option D is incorrect because STP placing a port in a forwarding state is normal and desired behavior — a blocking state would be a concern, but even then it would not remove the VLAN from the 'allowed and active' list.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9200/software/release/17-1/configuration_guide/vlan/b_171_vlan_9200_cg/configuring_vlans.html","label":"Cisco - Configuring VLANs and Trunking"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/8021q/24067-197.html","label":"Cisco - Understanding the show interfaces trunk Command Output"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A switch port is configured as an 802.1Q trunk between two Cisco switches. VLAN 10 traffic is expected to traverse the trunk, but hosts in VLAN 10 on Switch B cannot communicate with hosts in VLAN 10 on Switch A. The administrator runs 'show interfaces trunk' on Switch A and sees that VLAN 10 is not listed in the 'VLANs allowed and active in management domain' column. What is the most likely cause of this problem?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator has configured NAT overload (PAT) on a Cisco router to allow multiple internal hosts to share a single public IP address. After the configuration, internal hosts can ping external servers by IP address, but DNS resolution is failing. Which UDP port must be permitted outbound on the router's ACL to allow DNS queries to reach external DNS servers?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"UDP port 53"},{"id":"b","text":"UDP port 67"},{"id":"c","text":"UDP port 161"},{"id":"d","text":"UDP port 123"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$DNS (Domain Name System) uses UDP port 53 for standard queries and responses. Since internal hosts can ping external IPs successfully, NAT/PAT is functioning correctly for ICMP traffic; however, DNS queries are being blocked because UDP port 53 is not permitted by the outbound ACL. Option B (UDP 67) is used by DHCP for server-to-client communication. Option C (UDP 161) is used by SNMP for polling. Option D (UDP 123) is used by NTP for time synchronization. Permitting UDP port 53 outbound will allow DNS queries to pass through the router to external resolvers.$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/network-address-translation-nat/26704-nat-faq-00.html","label":"Cisco - Configuring Network Address Translation: Getting Started"},{"url":"https://www.iana.org/assignments/service-names-port-numbers/service-names-port-numbers.xhtml","label":"IANA Service Name and Transport Protocol Port Number Registry - DNS (port 53)"},{"url":"https://learningnetwork.cisco.com/s/ccna-exam-topics","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide - IP Services"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator has configured NAT overload (PAT) on a Cisco router to allow multiple internal hosts to share a single public IP address. After the configuration, internal hosts can ping external servers by IP address, but DNS resolution is failing. Which UDP port must be permitted outbound on the router's ACL to allow DNS queries to reach external DNS servers?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator wants to prevent unauthorized devices from connecting to the corporate LAN by verifying their identity at the port level before granting network access. Which IEEE standard defines the framework used to accomplish this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"IEEE 802.1Q"},{"id":"b","text":"IEEE 802.1X"},{"id":"c","text":"IEEE 802.3af"},{"id":"d","text":"IEEE 802.11i"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$IEEE 802.1X is the standard for Port-Based Network Access Control (PNAC). It defines an authentication mechanism that requires a supplicant (client device) to authenticate to an authenticator (switch port) via an authentication server (typically a RADIUS server) before being granted access to the LAN. IEEE 802.1Q is the standard for VLAN tagging, not authentication. IEEE 802.3af defines Power over Ethernet (PoE). IEEE 802.11i defines security mechanisms for wireless LANs (WPA2), not wired port-based authentication.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/sec/b_179_sec_9300_cg/configuring_ieee_802_1x_port_based_authentication.html","label":"Cisco - Configuring IEEE 802.1X Port-Based Authentication"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9780135792735","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide - Security Fundamentals"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator wants to prevent unauthorized devices from connecting to the corporate LAN by verifying their identity at the port level before granting network access. Which IEEE standard defines the framework used to accomplish this?$patch$);

-- SOA-C03: 5 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A CloudOps engineer needs to deploy a new version of an application to a fleet of Amazon EC2 instances managed by AWS Systems Manager. The deployment must automatically roll back if the error rate reported by Amazon CloudWatch exceeds 5% within 10 minutes of deployment. Which AWS service and feature combination should the engineer use to meet these requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"AWS CodeDeploy with an EC2/On-Premises deployment group, using an automatic rollback configuration triggered by a CloudWatch alarm that monitors the application error rate."},{"id":"b","text":"AWS Systems Manager Run Command with a custom rollback script that polls CloudWatch metrics every minute and reverts the deployment if the threshold is breached."},{"id":"c","text":"AWS Elastic Beanstalk with a rolling deployment policy and a manually configured CloudWatch alarm that sends an SNS notification to trigger a Lambda rollback function."},{"id":"d","text":"AWS CloudFormation with a StackSet deployment and drift detection enabled, configured to revert the stack to its previous state when a CloudWatch alarm enters ALARM state."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$AWS CodeDeploy natively supports automatic rollbacks based on CloudWatch alarms. You define a CloudWatch alarm (e.g., monitoring a 5xx error rate metric) and attach it to the CodeDeploy deployment group's rollback configuration. If the alarm transitions to ALARM state during or after deployment, CodeDeploy automatically re-deploys the last known good application revision — requiring no custom scripts or additional Lambda functions. Option B (Run Command with a polling script) achieves the goal but introduces significant custom code and operational overhead. Option C (Elastic Beanstalk) is not applicable here because the instances are already managed by Systems Manager and not provisioned by Elastic Beanstalk; additionally, it still requires a Lambda intermediary. Option D (CloudFormation StackSets with drift detection) is designed for infrastructure configuration drift, not application-level error-rate-triggered rollbacks, and does not natively integrate with CodeDeploy application revisions.$patch$, $patch$Deployment, Provisioning, and Automation$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codedeploy/latest/userguide/deployments-rollback-and-redeploy.html","label":"AWS CodeDeploy – Automatic Rollbacks"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codedeploy/latest/userguide/deployment-groups-configure-advanced-options.html","label":"AWS CodeDeploy – Configure a Deployment Group with CloudWatch Alarms"},{"url":"https://d1.awsstatic.com/training-and-certification/docs-sysops-associate/AWS-Certified-SysOps-Administrator-Associate_Exam-Guide.pdf","label":"AWS SOA-C03 Exam Guide – Deployment, Provisioning, and Automation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'SOA-C03'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A CloudOps engineer needs to deploy a new version of an application to a fleet of Amazon EC2 instances managed by AWS Systems Manager. The deployment must automatically roll back if the error rate reported by Amazon CloudWatch exceeds 5% within 10 minutes of deployment. Which AWS service and feature combination should the engineer use to meet these requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company hosts a static website using an Amazon S3 bucket and distributes it globally via Amazon CloudFront. Users in a specific geographic region report that they are still reaching the S3 origin directly instead of being served from a CloudFront edge location. The CloudFront distribution is fully deployed and the domain name is correct. Which configuration issue is MOST likely causing this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The S3 bucket policy does not include a condition restricting access to the CloudFront origin access control (OAC) principal."},{"id":"b","text":"The users are resolving the S3 bucket's website endpoint URL directly rather than the CloudFront distribution domain name or a CNAME alias pointing to it."},{"id":"c","text":"The CloudFront distribution does not have a geo-restriction policy configured to allow traffic from that geographic region."},{"id":"d","text":"The CloudFront cache behavior is set to forward all headers to the origin, which disables edge caching and forces requests to the origin."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$CloudFront only serves requests that are directed to the CloudFront distribution domain (e.g., d1234.cloudfront.net) or a CNAME alias. If end users are navigating directly to the S3 bucket website endpoint URL, their requests bypass CloudFront entirely and go straight to S3. Option A describes a permissions hardening practice but would result in 403 errors rather than bypassing CloudFront. Option C (geo-restriction) would block users in a region, not cause them to hit S3 directly. Option D (forwarding all headers) degrades cacheability and increases origin load, but it does not reroute traffic away from CloudFront to S3.$patch$, $patch$Networking and Content Delivery$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudFront/latest/DeveloperGuide/GettingStarted.SimpleDistribution.html","label":"Amazon CloudFront — Getting Started with a Simple CloudFront Distribution"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudFront/latest/DeveloperGuide/private-content-restricting-access-to-s3.html","label":"Restricting access to an Amazon S3 origin with Origin Access Control"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'SOA-C03'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company hosts a static website using an Amazon S3 bucket and distributes it globally via Amazon CloudFront. Users in a specific geographic region report that they are still reaching the S3 origin directly instead of being served from a CloudFront edge location. The CloudFront distribution is fully deployed and the domain name is correct. Which configuration issue is MOST likely causing this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An operations team manages a VPC with both public and private subnets across two Availability Zones. EC2 instances in the private subnets must download OS patches from the internet, but must not be directly reachable from the internet. The team observes that instances in private subnets in us-east-1b cannot reach the internet, while instances in us-east-1a can. What is the MOST likely root cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The NAT gateway is deployed only in the public subnet in us-east-1a, and the route table associated with the us-east-1b private subnet still points to that same NAT gateway, which is in a different AZ."},{"id":"b","text":"A second NAT gateway has not been provisioned in the public subnet in us-east-1b, so the route table for the us-east-1b private subnet has no valid 0.0.0.0/0 route."},{"id":"c","text":"The internet gateway is not attached to the VPC in us-east-1b."},{"id":"d","text":"The security group on the private instances in us-east-1b is missing an outbound rule allowing HTTPS traffic on port 443."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$For high availability and cost-efficiency best practices, a NAT gateway should be deployed in each Availability Zone, with each AZ's private subnet route table pointing to the NAT gateway in the same AZ. If a NAT gateway only exists in us-east-1a and the us-east-1b private route table has no 0.0.0.0/0 route (or a broken one), instances in us-east-1b will fail to reach the internet. Option A describes a partial misconfiguration (cross-AZ NAT routing) that would still work functionally but incurs cross-AZ data transfer costs — it does not cause a total failure. Option C is incorrect because internet gateways are VPC-level resources and are not AZ-specific. Option D is plausible but security groups are stateful and the default outbound rule allows all traffic; a missing outbound rule would not explain why us-east-1a works and us-east-1b does not given identical security groups.$patch$, $patch$Networking and Content Delivery$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/vpc-nat-gateway.html","label":"NAT gateways — AWS Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_Route_Tables.html","label":"Configure route tables — Amazon VPC"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'SOA-C03'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An operations team manages a VPC with both public and private subnets across two Availability Zones. EC2 instances in the private subnets must download OS patches from the internet, but must not be directly reachable from the internet. The team observes that instances in private subnets in us-east-1b cannot reach the internet, while instances in us-east-1a can. What is the MOST likely root cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A CloudOps engineer needs to enforce that all traffic between an on-premises data center and an Amazon VPC travels over a redundant, low-latency private connection. The current AWS Site-to-Site VPN connection occasionally experiences latency spikes due to internet variability. The company already has an AWS Direct Connect connection in place but it is not being used for this traffic. What should the engineer configure to route the VPC-to-on-premises traffic over Direct Connect while keeping the VPN as a failover path?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Attach both the Direct Connect gateway and the VPN to a single Transit Gateway, and use BGP AS_PATH prepending on the VPN to make the Direct Connect path preferred."},{"id":"b","text":"Create a new Site-to-Site VPN connection over the Direct Connect connection using a hosted VIF and configure equal-cost multipath routing (ECMP) across both connections."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable AWS Global Accelerator on the existing VPN endpoints to reduce latency spikes without modifying the routing configuration."},{"id":"d","text":"Replace the Direct Connect connection with an additional VPN connection that terminates at a different internet service provider (ISP) for path diversity."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Attaching both the Direct Connect gateway and the VPN virtual private gateway to an AWS Transit Gateway allows centralized routing management. BGP AS_PATH prepending on the VPN advertisement makes the VPN routes less preferred, so traffic uses Direct Connect by default. If the Direct Connect path becomes unavailable, BGP reconverges and traffic automatically fails over to the VPN. Option B confuses a hosted private VIF with a VPN — you can run a VPN over Direct Connect using a public VIF or transit VIF, but the described scenario is not standard practice and ECMP does not implement primary/failover semantics. Option C is incorrect because AWS Global Accelerator is designed for public-facing application endpoints, not private VPN tunnels. Option D is counterproductive — it removes Direct Connect and replaces it with a second internet-based VPN, which does not satisfy the requirement for a private, low-latency connection.$patch$, $patch$Networking and Content Delivery$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/virtualgateways.html","label":"AWS Direct Connect and VPN failover with Transit Gateway"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/routing-and-bgp.html","label":"BGP routing and Direct Connect — AWS Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/direct-connect-transit-gateways.html","label":"Transit Gateway with Direct Connect gateway"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'SOA-C03'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A CloudOps engineer needs to enforce that all traffic between an on-premises data center and an Amazon VPC travels over a redundant, low-latency private connection. The current AWS Site-to-Site VPN connection occasionally experiences latency spikes due to internet variability. The company already has an AWS Direct Connect connection in place but it is not being used for this traffic. What should the engineer configure to route the VPC-to-on-premises traffic over Direct Connect while keeping the VPN as a failover path?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company's web application is served through Amazon CloudFront. The security team requires that all HTTP requests are automatically redirected to HTTPS and that the CloudFront distribution only accepts TLSv1.2 or later. A CloudOps engineer has updated the distribution's viewer protocol policy to 'Redirect HTTP to HTTPS'. After testing, the engineer notices that the browser still successfully establishes a connection using TLSv1.1. Which additional configuration step is required to enforce TLSv1.2 as the minimum protocol version?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Update the origin protocol policy to require HTTPS only, which will cascade the TLS version requirement to viewers."},{"id":"b","text":"Set the Security Policy on the CloudFront distribution's viewer certificate configuration to 'TLSv1.2_2021' (or a later equivalent profile)."},{"id":"c","text":"Attach an AWS WAF web ACL to the CloudFront distribution and create a rule that blocks requests that arrive over TLSv1.1."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable Field-Level Encryption on the CloudFront distribution to enforce stronger TLS negotiation with viewers."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$CloudFront's Security Policy controls the minimum TLS protocol version and the set of cipher suites that CloudFront uses when negotiating TLS connections with viewers. Selecting a Security Policy such as 'TLSv1.2_2021' ensures that CloudFront will reject connections from clients that can only support TLSv1.1 or older. The viewer protocol policy (Redirect HTTP to HTTPS) only controls whether HTTP is redirected to HTTPS — it does not govern which TLS version is negotiated. Option A (origin protocol policy) governs connections between CloudFront and the origin server, not between viewers and CloudFront edge locations, so it has no effect on viewer-facing TLS versions. Option C (AWS WAF) operates at the HTTP/HTTPS request layer after the TLS handshake has already completed; it cannot block connections based on the TLS version used during the handshake. Option D (Field-Level Encryption) is a data-encryption feature for sensitive form fields and has no bearing on the minimum TLS version.$patch$, $patch$Networking and Content Delivery$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudFront/latest/DeveloperGuide/secure-connections-supported-viewer-protocols-ciphers.html","label":"Supported protocols and ciphers — Amazon CloudFront Security Policies"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudFront/latest/DeveloperGuide/distribution-web-values-specify.html#DownloadDistValuesViewerProtocolPolicy","label":"Viewer protocol policy — Amazon CloudFront"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'SOA-C03'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company's web application is served through Amazon CloudFront. The security team requires that all HTTP requests are automatically redirected to HTTPS and that the CloudFront distribution only accepts TLSv1.2 or later. A CloudOps engineer has updated the distribution's viewer protocol policy to 'Redirect HTTP to HTTPS'. After testing, the engineer notices that the browser still successfully establishes a connection using TLSv1.1. Which additional configuration step is required to enforce TLSv1.2 as the minimum protocol version?$patch$);

-- SCS-C03: 5 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security engineer receives an Amazon GuardDuty finding indicating that an IAM user's access key has been used from an unusual geographic location to call the GetSecretValue API on AWS Secrets Manager. The engineer suspects the access key has been compromised. Which action should the engineer take FIRST to contain the incident?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Delete the IAM user account immediately to prevent further unauthorized access."},{"id":"b","text":"Deactivate the compromised IAM access key by setting its status to Inactive in the IAM console."},{"id":"c","text":"Rotate the secret value stored in AWS Secrets Manager to invalidate any data that may have been retrieved."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable AWS CloudTrail in all regions to ensure future API calls are logged."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The immediate containment priority when an IAM access key is suspected to be compromised is to deactivate (set to Inactive) that specific key. This stops the attacker from making any further API calls using the stolen credentials without permanently deleting the user or their other resources, which preserves forensic evidence and minimizes disruption. Deleting the IAM user (option a) is a more disruptive action and should come after initial containment and investigation. Rotating the Secrets Manager secret (option c) is an important remediation step but is not the first containment action — the attacker can still make additional API calls with the active key until it is disabled. Enabling CloudTrail (option d) is a preventive/detective control and does nothing to stop ongoing unauthorized activity.$patch$, $patch$Incident Response$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/id_credentials_access-keys.html","label":"AWS IAM – Managing Access Keys for IAM Users"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/aws-security-incident-response-guide/containment.html","label":"AWS Security Incident Response Guide – Containment"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/guardduty/latest/ug/guardduty_finding-types-iam.html","label":"Amazon GuardDuty Finding Types – UnauthorizedAccess:IAMUser/AnomalousBehavior"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'SCS-C03'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security engineer receives an Amazon GuardDuty finding indicating that an IAM user's access key has been used from an unusual geographic location to call the GetSecretValue API on AWS Secrets Manager. The engineer suspects the access key has been compromised. Which action should the engineer take FIRST to contain the incident?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security engineer needs to ensure that all objects uploaded to an Amazon S3 bucket are encrypted at rest using AWS Key Management Service (KMS) keys managed by the organization. Which S3 bucket configuration should the engineer apply to enforce this requirement for every object, including uploads that do not specify an encryption method?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable S3 default encryption on the bucket by specifying SSE-KMS with a customer-managed KMS key, and apply a bucket policy that denies any PutObject request where the header 's3:x-amz-server-side-encryption' is not set to 'aws:kms'."},{"id":"b","text":"Enable S3 Versioning on the bucket and configure an S3 Lifecycle policy to transition all objects to SSE-KMS encryption after one day."},{"id":"c","text":"Create an IAM policy that requires all IAM users to include the SSE-KMS header when calling PutObject, and attach it to every IAM user and role in the account."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable Amazon Macie on the bucket to detect unencrypted objects and configure Macie to automatically re-encrypt any object it finds without a KMS key."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option A is correct because S3 default encryption ensures that any object uploaded without an explicit encryption header is automatically encrypted using the specified SSE-KMS key. However, default encryption alone does not prevent a caller from explicitly requesting a different encryption method (e.g., SSE-S3) or no encryption at all. Adding a bucket policy that denies PutObject requests lacking the 'aws:kms' encryption header closes this gap and guarantees all objects are protected with the organization-managed KMS key. Option B is incorrect because S3 Lifecycle policies manage object transitions between storage classes or expiration; they cannot retroactively re-encrypt objects with a different key type. Option C is incorrect because IAM policies govern permissions but cannot force the inclusion of specific request headers, and they would not cover all callers (e.g., anonymous or cross-account) that might reach the bucket. Option D is incorrect because Amazon Macie is a data discovery and classification service; it does not have the capability to automatically re-encrypt S3 objects.$patch$, $patch$Data Protection$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/default-bucket-encryption.html","label":"Amazon S3 Default Encryption for S3 Buckets — AWS Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/serv-side-encryption.html","label":"Protecting Data with Server-Side Encryption — AWS Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/UsingKMSEncryption.html#require-sse-kms","label":"Using Bucket Policies to Require SSE-KMS — AWS Documentation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'SCS-C03'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security engineer needs to ensure that all objects uploaded to an Amazon S3 bucket are encrypted at rest using AWS Key Management Service (KMS) keys managed by the organization. Which S3 bucket configuration should the engineer apply to enforce this requirement for every object, including uploads that do not specify an encryption method?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company is establishing its AWS security baseline and needs to ensure that all new AWS accounts created within its AWS Organization automatically inherit a set of mandatory security controls, such as CloudTrail being enabled and specific AWS Config rules being enforced. Which AWS service or feature is the MOST operationally efficient way to achieve this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Manually apply IAM permission boundaries to every new account after it is created."},{"id":"b","text":"Use AWS Control Tower with pre-configured guardrails applied to Organizational Units (OUs)."},{"id":"c","text":"Create an AWS Lambda function triggered by CloudWatch Events that runs security scripts on new accounts."},{"id":"d","text":"Use AWS Trusted Advisor to scan all accounts and remediate non-compliant resources daily."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$AWS Control Tower provides a landing zone that automates the setup of a well-architected multi-account environment. Its guardrails (both preventive, implemented via Service Control Policies, and detective, implemented via AWS Config rules) are automatically applied to Organizational Units and inherited by any new account enrolled under them — making it the most operationally efficient solution. Option A is manual and error-prone. Option C is a custom, fragile solution that requires ongoing maintenance. Option D is Trusted Advisor, which provides recommendations but does not enforce or automatically remediate security controls.$patch$, $patch$Security Foundations and Governance$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/controltower/latest/userguide/how-control-tower-works.html","label":"AWS Control Tower – How It Works"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/controltower/latest/userguide/guardrails.html","label":"AWS Control Tower Guardrails"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'SCS-C03'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company is establishing its AWS security baseline and needs to ensure that all new AWS accounts created within its AWS Organization automatically inherit a set of mandatory security controls, such as CloudTrail being enabled and specific AWS Config rules being enforced. Which AWS service or feature is the MOST operationally efficient way to achieve this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization wants to enforce a policy that prevents any principal in its AWS Organization from disabling AWS CloudTrail logging across all member accounts, including the management account. Which mechanism should the security team use to implement this control?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Attach a deny-based IAM policy to every IAM user and role in each member account that blocks the cloudtrail:StopLogging action."},{"id":"b","text":"Enable AWS Config with a managed rule that detects when CloudTrail is disabled and sends an SNS notification."},{"id":"c","text":"Create a Service Control Policy (SCP) at the root or applicable OU level of the AWS Organization that explicitly denies the cloudtrail:StopLogging and cloudtrail:DeleteTrail actions."},{"id":"d","text":"Use an AWS IAM permission boundary on all roles to prevent them from calling CloudTrail APIs."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Service Control Policies (SCPs) are a type of AWS Organizations policy that set maximum permission guardrails for all principals (IAM users, roles, and even the root user) in member accounts. An SCP applied at the root or OU level that denies cloudtrail:StopLogging and cloudtrail:DeleteTrail will enforce this restriction across every affected account, regardless of what IAM policies grant. Option A is operationally impractical because it requires updating every principal in every account. Option B is detective, not preventive — it detects the change after it has already occurred. Option D (permission boundaries) controls the maximum permissions of individual roles but cannot be enforced centrally across an entire Organization the way SCPs can.$patch$, $patch$Security Foundations and Governance$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/organizations/latest/userguide/orgs_manage_policies_scps.html","label":"AWS Organizations – Service Control Policies (SCPs)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/organizations/latest/userguide/orgs_manage_policies_scps_examples_cloudtrail.html","label":"SCP Examples – Prevent Users from Disabling CloudTrail"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'SCS-C03'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization wants to enforce a policy that prevents any principal in its AWS Organization from disabling AWS CloudTrail logging across all member accounts, including the management account. Which mechanism should the security team use to implement this control?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security engineer is reviewing the AWS Shared Responsibility Model for a workload that uses Amazon RDS for MySQL. Under this model, which of the following tasks is the responsibility of the CUSTOMER?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Patching the underlying host operating system that runs the RDS database instance."},{"id":"b","text":"Managing the physical security of the data center where the RDS instance resides."},{"id":"c","text":"Configuring database security groups and managing database user accounts and access controls."},{"id":"d","text":"Applying patches to the MySQL database engine binary managed by the RDS service."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Under the AWS Shared Responsibility Model, Amazon RDS is a managed service, which means AWS is responsible for the undifferentiated heavy lifting: patching the host OS (Option A), physical data center security (Option B), and patching the database engine binary (Option D). The customer, however, retains responsibility for security 'in' the cloud — this includes configuring security groups (network-level access controls to the DB instance), creating and managing database user accounts, assigning appropriate database privileges, and enabling/configuring features such as encryption at rest and in transit. These are all within the customer's control plane.$patch$, $patch$Security Foundations and Governance$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://aws.amazon.com/compliance/shared-responsibility-model/","label":"AWS Shared Responsibility Model"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/UserGuide/UsingWithRDS.html","label":"Amazon RDS Security – Shared Responsibility"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'SCS-C03'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security engineer is reviewing the AWS Shared Responsibility Model for a workload that uses Amazon RDS for MySQL. Under this model, which of the following tasks is the responsibility of the CUSTOMER?$patch$);

-- ANS-C01: 5 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company has a single AWS Region deployment with multiple VPCs that need to communicate with each other and with an on-premises data center connected via AWS Direct Connect. The network architect wants to simplify routing and reduce the number of peering connections required. Which AWS service should the architect recommend to centralize connectivity between the VPCs and the on-premises network?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"AWS Transit Gateway"},{"id":"b","text":"VPC Peering"},{"id":"c","text":"AWS PrivateLink"},{"id":"d","text":"AWS Direct Connect Gateway"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$AWS Transit Gateway acts as a regional network hub that enables transitive routing between thousands of VPCs and on-premises networks through a single gateway. It eliminates the need for complex, full-mesh VPC peering arrangements and integrates natively with Direct Connect via a Transit Virtual Interface, making it the ideal centralized connectivity solution. VPC Peering is non-transitive and requires a separate peering connection between every pair of VPCs, which becomes unmanageable at scale. AWS PrivateLink is designed for exposing specific services privately, not for general VPC-to-VPC or VPC-to-on-premises routing. AWS Direct Connect Gateway on its own enables connectivity from on-premises to multiple VPCs across Regions but does not provide transitive routing between those VPCs — pairing it with Transit Gateway is the full solution, but Transit Gateway is the key component that addresses the centralized VPC-to-VPC routing requirement.$patch$, $patch$Network Design$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/tgw/what-is-transit-gateway.html","label":"AWS Transit Gateway — Official Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/direct-connect-transit-gateways.html","label":"AWS Transit Gateway with Direct Connect"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'ANS-C01'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company has a single AWS Region deployment with multiple VPCs that need to communicate with each other and with an on-premises data center connected via AWS Direct Connect. The network architect wants to simplify routing and reduce the number of peering connections required. Which AWS service should the architect recommend to centralize connectivity between the VPCs and the on-premises network?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer needs to connect an on-premises data center to an Amazon VPC using AWS Site-to-Site VPN. The on-premises customer gateway device has a statically routable public IP address. Which resource must the engineer create in AWS to serve as the AWS-side endpoint for the VPN connection?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"An Internet Gateway attached to the VPC"},{"id":"b","text":"A Virtual Private Gateway (VGW) attached to the VPC"},{"id":"c","text":"A NAT Gateway placed in a public subnet of the VPC"},{"id":"d","text":"A VPC Peering connection targeting the on-premises CIDR block"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A Virtual Private Gateway (VGW) is the AWS-side termination point for an AWS Site-to-Site VPN connection. It is attached to the VPC and works in conjunction with a Customer Gateway (CGW) resource—which represents the on-premises device—to establish the IPsec tunnels. An Internet Gateway provides outbound internet access for resources in a VPC but cannot terminate VPN connections. A NAT Gateway provides outbound internet access for private subnet resources and has no VPN capability. VPC Peering is used to route traffic between two AWS VPCs, not between AWS and on-premises networks.$patch$, $patch$Network Implementation$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpn/latest/s2svpn/VPC_VPN.html","label":"AWS Site-to-Site VPN — What is AWS Site-to-Site VPN?"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/vpn-connections.html","label":"AWS Virtual Private Gateway — VPN Connections"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'ANS-C01'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer needs to connect an on-premises data center to an Amazon VPC using AWS Site-to-Site VPN. The on-premises customer gateway device has a statically routable public IP address. Which resource must the engineer create in AWS to serve as the AWS-side endpoint for the VPN connection?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer needs to monitor the bandwidth utilization of an AWS Transit Gateway to identify potential bottlenecks across multiple VPCs. Which AWS service should the engineer use to view pre-built metrics such as BytesIn, BytesOut, and PacketDropCountBlackhole for the Transit Gateway?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"AWS CloudTrail"},{"id":"b","text":"Amazon CloudWatch"},{"id":"c","text":"AWS Config"},{"id":"d","text":"Amazon VPC Flow Logs"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Amazon CloudWatch natively collects and publishes Transit Gateway metrics — including BytesIn, BytesOut, PacketsIn, PacketsOut, BytesDropCountBlackhole, and PacketDropCountBlackhole — at one-minute granularity with no additional configuration required beyond enabling the metrics. These metrics allow engineers to monitor bandwidth utilization and packet drops in near real time. AWS CloudTrail (option a) records API calls for auditing purposes and does not provide network throughput metrics. AWS Config (option c) tracks resource configuration changes over time and is not a metrics or monitoring tool for live traffic. Amazon VPC Flow Logs (option d) capture IP traffic metadata at the ENI, subnet, or VPC level and can be used for traffic analysis, but they do not surface pre-aggregated Transit Gateway-specific metrics like BytesIn/BytesOut directly in a dashboard-ready form the way CloudWatch does, and they require additional processing (e.g., via Athena or CloudWatch Logs Insights) to derive utilization figures.$patch$, $patch$Network Management and Operation$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/tgw/transit-gateway-cloudwatch-metrics.html","label":"AWS Documentation – Transit Gateway CloudWatch Metrics"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/tgw/tgw-monitoring.html","label":"AWS Documentation – Monitoring Your Transit Gateway"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'ANS-C01'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer needs to monitor the bandwidth utilization of an AWS Transit Gateway to identify potential bottlenecks across multiple VPCs. Which AWS service should the engineer use to view pre-built metrics such as BytesIn, BytesOut, and PacketDropCountBlackhole for the Transit Gateway?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer needs to restrict outbound internet traffic from an Amazon VPC so that only traffic to approved external domains (e.g., api.example.com) is allowed, while all other outbound HTTP/HTTPS traffic is blocked. Which AWS service or feature should the engineer use to accomplish this with domain-based filtering?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"AWS Network Firewall with stateful domain list rules"},{"id":"b","text":"VPC Security Groups with outbound rules specifying resolved IP addresses"},{"id":"c","text":"AWS WAF web ACLs attached to a NAT Gateway"},{"id":"d","text":"Amazon Route 53 Resolver DNS Firewall with domain block-override rules"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$AWS Network Firewall supports stateful inspection rules that include domain list rule groups. These allow you to specify fully qualified domain names (FQDNs) and control outbound HTTP/HTTPS traffic based on the SNI (for TLS) or the HTTP Host header — meaning you can permit only approved domains and deny everything else. Security Groups (option b) operate on IP addresses and ports only; they cannot filter by domain name, and resolved IPs can change frequently making this approach unreliable. AWS WAF (option c) cannot be attached to a NAT Gateway — it integrates with CloudFront, ALB, API Gateway, and AppSync. Route 53 Resolver DNS Firewall (option d) can block DNS resolution for unapproved domains, but it does not prevent direct-IP connections; a determined workload could bypass it by using hard-coded IPs. AWS Network Firewall's domain list rules provide the most direct and reliable solution for domain-based egress filtering.$patch$, $patch$Network Security, Compliance, and Governance$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/network-firewall/latest/developerguide/stateful-rule-groups-domain-names.html","label":"AWS Network Firewall – Domain list rule groups"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/network-firewall/latest/developerguide/how-it-works.html","label":"AWS Network Firewall – How it works"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'ANS-C01'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer needs to restrict outbound internet traffic from an Amazon VPC so that only traffic to approved external domains (e.g., api.example.com) is allowed, while all other outbound HTTP/HTTPS traffic is blocked. Which AWS service or feature should the engineer use to accomplish this with domain-based filtering?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security team wants to ensure that all Amazon VPCs in their AWS Organization never have a default Security Group that permits any inbound or outbound traffic. They want this control enforced automatically and preventatively across all existing and future member accounts. Which approach best meets this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create an AWS Config rule with automatic remediation using AWS Systems Manager Automation to remove all rules from default Security Groups."},{"id":"b","text":"Use an AWS Organizations Service Control Policy (SCP) that denies the ec2:AuthorizeSecurityGroupIngress and ec2:AuthorizeSecurityGroupEgress actions on the default Security Group."},{"id":"c","text":"Deploy an AWS Lambda function triggered by CloudTrail events to revoke rules on default Security Groups whenever they are modified."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable AWS Security Hub with the AWS Foundational Security Best Practices standard, which will alert teams when default Security Groups contain rules."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$An AWS Organizations Service Control Policy (SCP) is a preventative control — it restricts what actions can be performed in member accounts before any change takes effect. By denying ec2:AuthorizeSecurityGroupIngress and ec2:AuthorizeSecurityGroupEgress scoped to the default Security Group (using a condition on the resource or group name), no principal in any member account can add rules to the default Security Group, satisfying the requirement for automatic, preventative enforcement across the entire Organization. AWS Config with remediation (option a) is a detective and corrective control; there is a window between when the rule is added and when it is remediated, making it reactive rather than preventative. A Lambda function triggered by CloudTrail (option c) is also reactive and subject to delay or failure. AWS Security Hub (option d) only provides visibility and alerting — it does not prevent the action from occurring.$patch$, $patch$Network Security, Compliance, and Governance$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/organizations/latest/userguide/orgs_manage_policies_scps.html","label":"AWS Organizations – Service Control Policies"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/userguide/ec2-controls.html#ec2-2","label":"AWS Security Best Practices – Restrict default Security Group"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'ANS-C01'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security team wants to ensure that all Amazon VPCs in their AWS Organization never have a default Security Group that permits any inbound or outbound traffic. They want this control enforced automatically and preventatively across all existing and future member accounts. Which approach best meets this requirement?$patch$);

-- MLA-C01-P1: 5 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A machine learning engineer is preparing a training dataset for a binary classification model in Amazon SageMaker. The dataset contains 95% negative samples and 5% positive samples. The engineer wants to address the class imbalance before training. Which combination of techniques is MOST appropriate to handle this imbalance directly during data preparation?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Apply SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique) to oversample the minority class, and use Amazon SageMaker Processing jobs to execute the transformation at scale."},{"id":"b","text":"Increase the number of epochs during model training and rely on the optimizer to naturally correct the imbalance over time."},{"id":"c","text":"Remove all negative samples until the dataset reaches a 50/50 ratio, then store the balanced dataset in Amazon S3."},{"id":"d","text":"Switch the model algorithm from binary classification to multi-class classification to redistribute the label distribution."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$SMOTE is a well-established oversampling technique that generates synthetic samples for the minority class by interpolating between existing minority-class data points, thereby improving class balance without simply duplicating data. Amazon SageMaker Processing jobs provide a scalable, managed environment to run data transformation scripts (e.g., using imbalanced-learn with SMOTE) on large datasets stored in S3. Option B is incorrect because increasing epochs does not address data-level imbalance and can cause the model to overfit the majority class further. Option C is incorrect because aggressively undersampling the majority class to 50/50 by discarding data can discard large volumes of potentially useful information. Option D is incorrect because changing the classification type does not resolve an underlying imbalance in the label distribution.$patch$, $patch$Data Preparation for Machine Learning$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/sagemaker/latest/dg/processing-job.html","label":"Amazon SageMaker Processing Jobs – AWS Documentation"},{"url":"https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/machine-learning/handle-class-imbalance-with-amazon-sagemaker/","label":"Handling Imbalanced Datasets – AWS Machine Learning Blog"},{"url":"https://imbalanced-learn.org/stable/references/generated/imblearn.over_sampling.SMOTE.html","label":"imbalanced-learn SMOTE API Reference"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'MLA-C01-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A machine learning engineer is preparing a training dataset for a binary classification model in Amazon SageMaker. The dataset contains 95% negative samples and 5% positive samples. The engineer wants to address the class imbalance before training. Which combination of techniques is MOST appropriate to handle this imbalance directly during data preparation?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data engineer is using AWS Glue DataBrew to profile a raw dataset that will be used to train a regression model in Amazon SageMaker. During profiling, she discovers that a numeric feature column has approximately 18% missing values. The feature is known to be moderately correlated with the target variable. Which strategy BEST balances data fidelity and model performance when handling these missing values?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Drop the entire feature column because any missing data in a predictor column makes it unsuitable for regression modeling."},{"id":"b","text":"Impute the missing values using the column median, configured as a DataBrew recipe step, then store the transformed dataset back to Amazon S3 for training."},{"id":"c","text":"Replace all missing values with zero, as this is the safest numeric placeholder and will not affect model convergence."},{"id":"d","text":"Duplicate the rows that contain missing values so that the model is exposed to more examples with that pattern during training."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Median imputation is a robust strategy for numeric features with missing values, particularly when the distribution may be skewed, because the median is not influenced by outliers the way the mean is. Since the feature is moderately correlated with the target, retaining it via imputation is preferable to dropping it entirely. AWS Glue DataBrew supports median imputation natively as a recipe step, making it straightforward to apply and reproduce as part of a repeatable data preparation pipeline, with the output written back to S3 for SageMaker consumption. Option A is incorrect because dropping a moderately correlated feature discards useful signal; 18% missingness is manageable through imputation. Option C is incorrect because replacing with zero introduces a spurious value that distorts the feature's statistical distribution and can mislead the model, especially for features where zero is not a meaningful sentinel. Option D is incorrect because duplicating incomplete rows does not resolve the missing value problem—it simply amplifies rows with unknown data, which can bias training.$patch$, $patch$Data Preparation for Machine Learning$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/databrew/latest/dg/recipe-actions.FILL_MISSING_VALUES.html","label":"AWS Glue DataBrew – Handling Missing Values in Recipes"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/databrew/latest/dg/profile-overview.html","label":"AWS Glue DataBrew – Data Profiling Overview"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/sagemaker/latest/dg/feature-store-getting-started.html","label":"Feature Engineering for Machine Learning – Amazon SageMaker Developer Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'MLA-C01-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data engineer is using AWS Glue DataBrew to profile a raw dataset that will be used to train a regression model in Amazon SageMaker. During profiling, she discovers that a numeric feature column has approximately 18% missing values. The feature is known to be moderately correlated with the target variable. Which strategy BEST balances data fidelity and model performance when handling these missing values?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A machine learning engineer is training a deep neural network on Amazon SageMaker to classify medical images. The model is achieving very high accuracy on the training dataset but significantly lower accuracy on the validation dataset. The engineer wants to address this issue without collecting additional training data. Which technique should the engineer implement FIRST to mitigate this problem?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Increase the number of layers and neurons in the neural network to improve model capacity."},{"id":"b","text":"Apply L2 regularization (weight decay) to penalize large weights and reduce model complexity."},{"id":"c","text":"Switch the optimizer from Adam to SGD to achieve a lower training loss."},{"id":"d","text":"Increase the number of training epochs to allow the model to converge more fully."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The scenario describes a classic overfitting problem: high training accuracy but poor validation accuracy. L2 regularization (weight decay) adds a penalty proportional to the square of the model's weights to the loss function, discouraging the model from fitting noise in the training data and thereby improving generalization to unseen data — making it the correct first mitigation step. Option A (increasing model capacity) would worsen overfitting by making the model even more complex. Option C (switching optimizers) does not address overfitting and may not improve generalization. Option D (more training epochs) would further overfit the model to the training data.$patch$, $patch$ML Model Development$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/sagemaker/latest/dg/deepinsight-on-sagemaker.html","label":"Amazon SageMaker – Prevent Overfitting with Regularization"},{"url":"https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/machine-learning/build-a-more-accurate-machine-learning-model-by-avoiding-overfitting/","label":"AWS Machine Learning Blog – Regularization Techniques for Deep Learning"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'MLA-C01-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A machine learning engineer is training a deep neural network on Amazon SageMaker to classify medical images. The model is achieving very high accuracy on the training dataset but significantly lower accuracy on the validation dataset. The engineer wants to address this issue without collecting additional training data. Which technique should the engineer implement FIRST to mitigate this problem?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data scientist at a financial services company is using Amazon SageMaker to train an XGBoost model to predict loan default risk. After hyperparameter tuning, the model performs well, but the team needs to understand which features are contributing most to individual predictions in order to satisfy regulatory explainability requirements. Which SageMaker feature should the data scientist use to meet this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Amazon SageMaker Debugger, to capture tensor outputs and identify training anomalies during the training job."},{"id":"b","text":"Amazon SageMaker Clarify, to compute SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) values that attribute feature importance to individual predictions."},{"id":"c","text":"Amazon SageMaker Model Monitor, to track data drift and feature distribution changes in the production endpoint."},{"id":"d","text":"Amazon SageMaker Experiments, to track, compare, and visualize the results of multiple training runs."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Amazon SageMaker Clarify provides model explainability capabilities by computing SHAP values, which quantify each feature's contribution to individual predictions. This directly satisfies regulatory explainability requirements for models used in financial decisions. Option A (SageMaker Debugger) is designed to identify training issues like vanishing gradients or overfit, not to explain individual predictions. Option C (SageMaker Model Monitor) watches for data and model drift in production but does not explain predictions. Option D (SageMaker Experiments) is a tracking and comparison tool for training runs, not an explainability solution.$patch$, $patch$ML Model Development$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/sagemaker/latest/dg/clarify-model-explainability.html","label":"Amazon SageMaker Clarify – Model Explainability"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/sagemaker/latest/dg/clarify-shapley-values.html","label":"Amazon SageMaker Clarify – SHAP Values for Explainability"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'MLA-C01-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data scientist at a financial services company is using Amazon SageMaker to train an XGBoost model to predict loan default risk. After hyperparameter tuning, the model performs well, but the team needs to understand which features are contributing most to individual predictions in order to satisfy regulatory explainability requirements. Which SageMaker feature should the data scientist use to meet this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A machine learning engineer has trained a custom PyTorch model and needs to deploy it on Amazon SageMaker for real-time inference. The model requires a custom inference script to handle pre-processing and post-processing logic. The engineer wants to ensure the deployment is reproducible and version-controlled. Which combination of steps correctly deploys the model with a custom inference script on SageMaker?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Upload the model artifacts to Amazon S3, create a SageMaker Model object referencing the S3 URI and a custom inference.py script inside a 'code/' directory of the model tar.gz, then create an EndpointConfig and deploy an Endpoint using a built-in PyTorch serving container."},{"id":"b","text":"Upload the model artifacts directly to the SageMaker Endpoint without an S3 intermediate step, embed the inference script in the EndpointConfig JSON, and deploy using the default SageMaker container."},{"id":"c","text":"Package the model and inference script into a Docker image, push it to Amazon RDS, reference the RDS URI in the SageMaker Model object, and deploy the Endpoint."},{"id":"d","text":"Store the model artifacts in Amazon DynamoDB, create a Lambda function containing the inference script, and attach the Lambda function ARN to a SageMaker EndpointConfig for real-time inference."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option A is correct. When deploying a custom PyTorch model on SageMaker for real-time inference, the standard approach is to: (1) package model artifacts (model weights, etc.) along with a custom 'inference.py' script inside a 'code/' directory into a compressed tar.gz file, (2) upload this archive to Amazon S3, (3) create a SageMaker Model object that references the S3 URI and specifies a pre-built SageMaker PyTorch serving container image, then (4) create an EndpointConfig and deploy an Endpoint. SageMaker automatically detects the inference.py entry point within the code/ directory and uses it for pre/post-processing. Option B is incorrect because SageMaker requires model artifacts to be stored in S3; you cannot upload directly to an Endpoint, and inference scripts cannot be embedded in EndpointConfig JSON. Option C is incorrect because Amazon RDS is a relational database service and cannot store Docker images; Amazon ECR (Elastic Container Registry) is the correct service for custom container images. Option D is incorrect because SageMaker real-time Endpoints do not support Lambda function ARNs in EndpointConfig; Lambda is a separate invocation mechanism and is not natively integrated as a SageMaker inference backend in this manner.$patch$, $patch$Deployment and Orchestration of ML Workflows$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/sagemaker/latest/dg/pytorch-serving-container.html","label":"Deploy PyTorch Models with SageMaker – Custom Inference Scripts"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/sagemaker/latest/dg/realtime-endpoints-deployment.html","label":"Amazon SageMaker – Create a Model (Developer Guide)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/sagemaker/latest/dg/model-access-training-data.html","label":"Package and Upload Model Artifacts to Amazon S3"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'MLA-C01-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A machine learning engineer has trained a custom PyTorch model and needs to deploy it on Amazon SageMaker for real-time inference. The model requires a custom inference script to handle pre-processing and post-processing logic. The engineer wants to ensure the deployment is reproducible and version-controlled. Which combination of steps correctly deploys the model with a custom inference script on SageMaker?$patch$);

-- DOP-C02-P4: 5 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team manages a large AWS environment using AWS CloudFormation. They have a stack that provisions an Amazon RDS Multi-AZ instance, several EC2 instances in an Auto Scaling group, and an Application Load Balancer. During a routine stack update, the team discovers that a change to the RDS instance's DB parameter group requires a replacement of the resource. The team is concerned about data loss and service disruption during the update. Which combination of CloudFormation features should the team use to ensure the RDS data is preserved and the update can be safely rolled back if the new stack state is unhealthy?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable a CloudFormation Stack Policy to prevent updates to the RDS resource, then manually snapshot the RDS instance before applying the change outside of CloudFormation."},{"id":"b","text":"Use the DeletionPolicy attribute set to 'Snapshot' on the RDS resource and enable CloudFormation Stack rollback triggers with an Amazon CloudWatch alarm that monitors database connectivity, so that a snapshot is taken before deletion and the stack rolls back automatically if the alarm fires during the update."},{"id":"c","text":"Set the UpdateReplacePolicy attribute to 'Retain' on the RDS resource and use a CloudFormation change set to preview the replacement, then manually verify the new instance before deleting the old one."},{"id":"d","text":"Use the DeletionPolicy attribute set to 'Retain' on the RDS resource and enable CloudFormation drift detection after the update to ensure the new RDS instance matches the desired template configuration."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option B is correct because it combines two complementary CloudFormation safety mechanisms tailored to the specific risk of an RDS resource replacement. Setting 'DeletionPolicy: Snapshot' on the RDS resource ensures that CloudFormation automatically takes a DB snapshot before deleting the old instance during a replacement update — preserving data and enabling point-in-time recovery. Coupling this with CloudFormation rollback triggers (using a CloudWatch alarm monitoring database connectivity) means that if the new RDS instance fails to come online correctly within the monitoring window, CloudFormation will automatically roll the stack back to its previous known-good state. Together these features address both data preservation and automated remediation of a failed update.

Option A is incorrect because a Stack Policy only restricts who can update a resource and does not protect data; manually snapshotting outside CloudFormation and making changes outside the stack defeats the purpose of IaC and leaves the stack in a drifted state.

Option C is partially useful — UpdateReplacePolicy: Retain prevents the old instance from being deleted during a replacement — but 'Retain' means the old resource is simply abandoned (not snapshotted), and there is no automated rollback mechanism. Manual verification adds human latency and error risk.

Option D is incorrect because 'DeletionPolicy: Retain' only prevents deletion when the stack itself is deleted, not during an in-stack replacement update (for that you need UpdateReplacePolicy). Drift detection does not prevent or roll back a failed update; it only identifies configuration differences after the fact.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/aws-attribute-deletionpolicy.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – DeletionPolicy attribute"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/aws-attribute-updatereplacepolicy.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – UpdateReplacePolicy attribute"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/using-cfn-rollback-triggers.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – Stack rollback triggers"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/protect-stack-resources.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – Stack policies"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team manages a large AWS environment using AWS CloudFormation. They have a stack that provisions an Amazon RDS Multi-AZ instance, several EC2 instances in an Auto Scaling group, and an Application Load Balancer. During a routine stack update, the team discovers that a change to the RDS instance's DB parameter group requires a replacement of the resource. The team is concerned about data loss and service disruption during the update. Which combination of CloudFormation features should the team use to ensure the RDS data is preserved and the update can be safely rolled back if the new stack state is unhealthy?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team manages a mission-critical e-commerce application deployed across three AWS Regions (us-east-1, eu-west-1, ap-southeast-1) using Amazon Route 53 latency-based routing. The application uses Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL as its primary database. During a recent incident, a full regional failure in us-east-1 caused significant downtime because the RDS read replicas in the other regions could not be automatically promoted without manual intervention. The team must redesign the database tier to achieve an RTO of less than 15 minutes and an RPO of less than 30 seconds for any single-region failure, with promotion happening automatically. Which solution BEST meets these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Replace Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL with Amazon Aurora Global Database. Enable the managed planned failover feature and configure an Amazon CloudWatch alarm that triggers an AWS Lambda function via Amazon EventBridge to invoke the failover API when the primary region's Aurora cluster becomes unhealthy."},{"id":"b","text":"Keep Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL and configure Multi-AZ within each region. Use AWS Database Migration Service (DMS) with ongoing replication between regions and write an AWS Lambda function triggered by CloudWatch alarms to promote the replica in a secondary region when the primary becomes unhealthy."},{"id":"c","text":"Replace Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL with Amazon DynamoDB Global Tables. Configure DynamoDB Streams and use AWS AppSync to handle all relational query patterns previously handled by PostgreSQL, ensuring multi-region active-active writes."},{"id":"d","text":"Replace Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL with Amazon Aurora Global Database and enable the Aurora Global Database unplanned failover (detach-and-promote). Use Amazon Route 53 Application Recovery Controller (ARC) with readiness checks and routing controls to automate DNS failover when the primary region fails, triggering the detach-and-promote via an AWS Systems Manager Automation runbook."},{"id":"e","text":"Keep Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL with cross-region read replicas and configure AWS Elastic Disaster Recovery (DRS) to continuously replicate the primary RDS instance. Use an Amazon EventBridge rule to invoke a Step Functions state machine that promotes the read replica and updates Route 53 records upon detecting a failure."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["d"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option D is the best solution. Amazon Aurora Global Database provides cross-region replication with a typical replication lag of under 1 second, satisfying the RPO < 30 seconds requirement. The unplanned failover (detach-and-promote) process allows a secondary region's Aurora cluster to be promoted to a standalone primary in under 1 minute for the database tier itself, meeting the RTO < 15 minutes requirement. Amazon Route 53 Application Recovery Controller (ARC) provides purpose-built automated DNS failover with routing controls and readiness checks, ensuring the application traffic is redirected only when the secondary region is truly ready. Orchestrating this via a Systems Manager Automation runbook allows the entire failover process — database promotion, DNS rerouting — to be automated end-to-end without manual intervention.

Option A is partially correct (Aurora Global Database satisfies replication needs) but 'managed planned failover' is designed for planned maintenance with a synchronized switchover, not unplanned regional failure. A Lambda-based custom failover lacks the reliability and readiness-check sophistication of Route 53 ARC for automated unplanned failover.

Option B is incorrect because standard RDS PostgreSQL cross-region read replicas have higher replication lag than Aurora Global Database (potentially minutes, not sub-second), making the RPO < 30 seconds target unreliable. AWS DMS for replication adds operational complexity and latency. This solution also cannot guarantee the RTO/RPO targets.

Option C is incorrect because migrating a relational PostgreSQL workload to DynamoDB Global Tables is a significant architectural change that may not be feasible without re-engineering the entire application layer. DynamoDB does not natively support relational query patterns, and this does not address the actual requirement of failing over an existing PostgreSQL-compatible workload.

Option E is incorrect because AWS Elastic Disaster Recovery (DRS) is designed for EC2-based workloads and server replication, not for RDS database instances. RDS cross-region read replicas do have higher replication lag than Aurora Global Database. Furthermore, promoting an RDS read replica involves potential data loss and a longer, less predictable promotion time, making both the RPO and RTO targets harder to meet consistently.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/AuroraUserGuide/aurora-global-database.html","label":"Amazon Aurora Global Database – Overview"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/AuroraUserGuide/aurora-global-database-disaster-recovery.html","label":"Aurora Global Database – Unplanned Failover (Detach and Promote)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/r53recovery/latest/dg/routing-control.html","label":"Amazon Route 53 Application Recovery Controller – Routing Controls"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/r53recovery/latest/dg/recovery-readiness.html","label":"Amazon Route 53 ARC – Readiness Checks"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/systems-manager/latest/userguide/systems-manager-automation.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Automation – Runbook Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team manages a mission-critical e-commerce application deployed across three AWS Regions (us-east-1, eu-west-1, ap-southeast-1) using Amazon Route 53 latency-based routing. The application uses Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL as its primary database. During a recent incident, a full regional failure in us-east-1 caused significant downtime because the RDS read replicas in the other regions could not be automatically promoted without manual intervention. The team must redesign the database tier to achieve an RTO of less than 15 minutes and an RPO of less than 30 seconds for any single-region failure, with promotion happening automatically. Which solution BEST meets these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team manages a large-scale microservices application deployed on Amazon ECS with hundreds of tasks spread across multiple clusters. The team wants to implement a centralized logging solution that: (1) collects logs from all ECS tasks without modifying application container images, (2) enriches log records with ECS metadata such as cluster name, task ID, and container name, (3) routes error-level logs to Amazon OpenSearch Service for real-time analysis, and (4) routes all other logs to Amazon S3 for long-term archival at lowest cost. Which approach BEST satisfies all of these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Deploy the CloudWatch agent as a sidecar container in every ECS task definition. Configure the agent to publish all logs to a single CloudWatch Logs log group, then create two CloudWatch Logs subscription filters — one with a filter pattern of '?ERROR' forwarding to a Lambda function that writes to OpenSearch, and one with an empty pattern forwarding to Kinesis Data Firehose delivering to S3."},{"id":"b","text":"Enable the AWS FireLens log router by adding a 'firelens-router' container using the 'aws-for-fluent-bit' image to each ECS task definition. Set the log driver to 'awsfirelens' on application containers. Configure a Fluent Bit filter plugin to append ECS metadata using the built-in 'ecs' metadata endpoint, then define two Fluent Bit OUTPUT plugins: one routing records matching 'log contains ERROR' to Amazon OpenSearch Service via the opensearch plugin, and one routing all remaining records to Amazon S3 via Kinesis Data Firehose using the kinesis_firehose plugin."},{"id":"c","text":"Use the 'awslogs' log driver on all ECS task definitions to send logs directly to CloudWatch Logs. Deploy an Amazon Kinesis Data Streams consumer Lambda that reads from the stream, parses log levels, and conditionally writes to OpenSearch or S3. Use ECS task-level environment variables to inject metadata into log lines before they are emitted."},{"id":"d","text":"Configure an Amazon EventBridge rule that triggers on ECS task state change events and invokes a Lambda function to pull logs from the ECS task's stdout via the ECS DescribeTasks API. The Lambda function parses the log level and writes error logs to OpenSearch and all other logs to S3, tagging each record with the task ARN for metadata enrichment."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option B is correct because AWS FireLens is the AWS-native mechanism specifically designed to add a log routing sidecar (aws-for-fluent-bit) to ECS task definitions without modifying application container images — the application containers simply set their log driver to 'awsfirelens'. The built-in ECS task metadata endpoint (v4) is natively supported by the Fluent Bit 'ecs' filter plugin, which automatically enriches log records with cluster name, task ID, container name, and other metadata. Fluent Bit's powerful routing rules let you split the stream: error records go directly to Amazon OpenSearch Service via the 'opensearch' output plugin, while all other records flow to Kinesis Data Firehose (kinesis_firehose plugin) and then to S3 for cost-efficient archival — satisfying all four requirements in a single, cohesive solution. Option A fails requirement (2) because the CloudWatch agent does not natively enrich logs with ECS metadata in the same automated fashion, and using two subscription filters pointing to different destinations on the same log group is architecturally complex and introduces duplication risk; it also requires modifying task definitions to include a sidecar but uses a heavier agent. Option C uses the 'awslogs' driver which does not support automatic ECS metadata enrichment and requires injecting metadata manually via environment variables, violating requirement (2); additionally, ECS DescribeTasks does not stream logs — logs go to CloudWatch, not to a Kinesis stream by default. Option D is fundamentally flawed: ECS does not expose a real-time log-pull API from task stdout; logs must be shipped via a log driver. EventBridge ECS state change events do not carry log content, making this approach unworkable for continuous log routing.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/using_firelens.html","label":"AWS FireLens – Custom Log Routing for Amazon ECS"},{"url":"https://github.com/aws/aws-for-fluent-bit","label":"AWS for Fluent Bit – GitHub (aws-for-fluent-bit image)"},{"url":"https://docs.fluentbit.io/manual/pipeline/filters/ecs-metadata","label":"Fluent Bit ECS Task Metadata Filter"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/task-metadata-endpoint-v4.html","label":"Amazon ECS Task Metadata Endpoint v4"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/firehose/latest/dev/basic-deliver.html","label":"Kinesis Data Firehose Destination – Amazon S3"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/opensearch-service/latest/developerguide/ingestion.html","label":"Amazon OpenSearch Service – Ingestion Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
