INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is running a multi-tier e-commerce application on AWS. During a major sales event, an Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling group in the application tier begins launching instances that repeatedly fail their Elastic Load Balancing (ELB) health checks and are immediately terminated. This creates a continuous launch-and-terminate loop, causing degraded performance. An on-call engineer needs to investigate the root cause without disrupting the Auto Scaling group's desired capacity or triggering further automated replacements. Which approach should the engineer take to isolate a failing instance for forensic investigation while maintaining application stability?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Temporarily set the Auto Scaling group's minimum and maximum capacity to zero, SSH into one of the terminating instances before it is removed, and capture logs before scaling the group back up."},{"id":"b","text":"Place a specific instance into the Standby state using the EnterStandby API action, detaching it from the load balancer while keeping it running, then investigate the instance independently without affecting the Auto Scaling group's desired capacity."},{"id":"c","text":"Detach the Auto Scaling group from the load balancer, disable all scaling policies, and then review CloudWatch metrics to identify the failing instance."},{"id":"d","text":"Create an Amazon EventBridge rule that triggers an AWS Lambda function on EC2 instance launch events to automatically snapshot the instance's root EBS volume before termination occurs, then analyze the snapshot offline."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Placing an instance into the Standby state via the EnterStandby API (or through the console) is the correct and surgical approach. When an instance enters Standby, it is removed from the load balancer target group (stopping health check failures from triggering replacement), its lifecycle state changes to 'Standby', and it no longer counts against the group's healthy instance count — but the desired capacity is automatically incremented by one so a replacement is launched to maintain capacity. This allows the engineer to SSH into the isolated instance, inspect application logs, review system state, and diagnose the root cause without destabilizing the group. 

Option A is disruptive — setting capacity to zero terminates all running instances and causes a full service outage. Option C detaches the entire group from the load balancer, which is overly broad and risks a wider outage; it also does not isolate a single instance for investigation. Option D (EBS snapshot via EventBridge + Lambda) is a useful pattern for automated forensics but it does not stop the loop — the instance is still terminated and replaced continuously — and the snapshot approach alone does not give you a live interactive environment for investigation. The Standby lifecycle hook is the purpose-built AWS mechanism for this exact scenario.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/as-enter-exit-standby.html","label":"Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling – Temporarily removing instances from your Auto Scaling group (Standby state)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/ec2-auto-scaling-health-checks.html","label":"Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling – Health checks for Auto Scaling instances"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/ec2-auto-scaling-lifecycle.html","label":"Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling – Auto Scaling instance lifecycle"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
