INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is operating a multi-account AWS environment managed through AWS Organizations. The security team requires that all Amazon S3 buckets across every member account must never allow public access, and any attempt to disable the S3 Block Public Access settings at the account level must be automatically remediated within 15 minutes. The solution must be implemented centrally and must not rely on manual intervention per account. Which combination of AWS services and configurations will BEST meet these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Deploy an AWS Config rule (s3-account-level-public-access-blocks-periodic) as a Service Control Policy (SCP) in AWS Organizations, and use an SCP Deny statement to prevent changes to S3 Block Public Access settings on all member accounts."},{"id":"b","text":"Enable AWS Security Hub with the AWS Foundational Security Best Practices standard in the delegated administrator account, and configure Security Hub to automatically send findings to Amazon EventBridge, which triggers an AWS Lambda function to re-enable S3 Block Public Access settings on the offending account using AWS Organizations APIs."},{"id":"c","text":"Use AWS Config with a delegated administrator account to deploy the s3-account-level-public-access-blocks-periodic managed rule across all member accounts via an Organization Config Rule, and configure an AWS Config Remediation Action using AWS Systems Manager Automation document AWS-ConfigureS3BucketPublicAccessBlock to automatically re-enable all Block Public Access settings within the required time window."},{"id":"d","text":"Create an AWS CloudFormation StackSet targeting all member accounts that deploys an Amazon EventBridge scheduled rule every 15 minutes, invoking an AWS Lambda function that calls s3control:PutPublicAccessBlock to enforce Block Public Access settings on each account."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option C is correct because AWS Config Organization Config Rules allow a delegated administrator to centrally deploy Config rules across all existing and future member accounts in an organization without requiring per-account setup. The managed rule 's3-account-level-public-access-blocks-periodic' specifically evaluates whether the S3 Block Public Access settings are enabled at the account level on a periodic basis. Pairing this with an AWS Config Remediation Action that references the SSM Automation document 'AWS-ConfigureS3BucketPublicAccessBlock' enables fully automated, event-driven remediation that can be configured to trigger within the 15-minute window required by the security team — satisfying both the centralized management and automated remediation requirements.

Option A is incorrect because SCPs are authorization guardrails that restrict IAM permissions; they are not Config rules and cannot evaluate or remediate configuration drift. An SCP can prevent future disable actions but cannot detect or remediate a misconfiguration that already exists, nor does it provide the detection + remediation loop required.

Option B is incorrect because while Security Hub can aggregate findings and EventBridge can trigger Lambda, the AWS Organizations API does not expose a direct call to set S3 Block Public Access at the account level of a member account from a management account cross-account without additional cross-account role assumptions and considerable custom code. This approach is more complex, less native, and harder to guarantee the 15-minute SLA compared to the native Config remediation integration.

Option D is incorrect because a scheduled Lambda running every 15 minutes is a polling anti-pattern that introduces unnecessary compute cost and latency. It also requires maintaining a CloudFormation StackSet with Lambda code across all accounts and does not leverage AWS Config's native compliance tracking, reporting, or audit trail — making governance harder to demonstrate to auditors.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/config-rule-multi-account-deployment.html","label":"AWS Config Organization Rules - AWS Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/s3-account-level-public-access-blocks-periodic.html","label":"AWS Config Managed Rule: s3-account-level-public-access-blocks-periodic"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/remediation.html","label":"AWS Config Remediation Actions"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/access-control-block-public-access.html","label":"Amazon S3 Block Public Access - AWS Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/set-up-aggregator-cli.html#register-a-delegated-administrator","label":"AWS Organizations Delegated Administrator for AWS Config"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P4'
