INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team manages a large AWS environment using AWS CloudFormation. They have a stack that provisions an Amazon RDS Multi-AZ instance, several Auto Scaling groups, and associated networking resources. During a recent deployment, a change to the RDS instance's DBInstanceClass caused CloudFormation to interrupt the database workload unexpectedly. The team wants to prevent future stack updates from unintentionally modifying or replacing the RDS instance while still allowing updates to other resources in the same stack. The solution must not require splitting the stack. Which CloudFormation feature should the team implement to meet this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Add a DeletionPolicy attribute set to Retain on the RDS resource in the CloudFormation template to preserve it on delete or replace operations."},{"id":"b","text":"Enable termination protection on the entire CloudFormation stack to prevent any updates from being applied to any resource in the stack."},{"id":"c","text":"Apply a CloudFormation Stack Policy that explicitly denies Update:Modify, Update:Replace, and Update:Delete actions on the specific RDS logical resource ID, while allowing all actions on all other resources."},{"id":"d","text":"Use a CloudFormation change set to preview changes and manually reject the change set if it targets the RDS instance before executing any update."},{"id":"e","text":"Set the UpdateReplacePolicy attribute to Snapshot on the RDS resource so that any replacement operation creates a snapshot instead of deleting the instance."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A CloudFormation Stack Policy is a JSON document that defines which update actions are allowed or denied on specific resources within a stack. By applying a Stack Policy that explicitly denies Update:Modify, Update:Replace, and Update:Delete on the RDS logical resource (using its LogicalResourceId), the team prevents any stack update from inadvertently changing the database — while all other resources in the same stack remain fully updatable. This is the only mechanism that grants granular, per-resource update protection without splitting the stack. Option A (DeletionPolicy: Retain) only controls behavior when a resource is removed or replaced during deletion — it does not block update modifications. Option B (termination protection) prevents the entire stack from being deleted, but does not block resource-level updates within a running stack. Option D (change sets) improves visibility but requires manual human review every time; it is a process control, not an enforceable guardrail — a team member could still execute a harmful change set. Option E (UpdateReplacePolicy: Snapshot) creates a snapshot before replacement but does not prevent the replacement from occurring; it is a data-preservation measure, not an update-prevention mechanism.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/protect-stack-resources.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation Stack Policies – AWS Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/aws-attribute-deletionpolicy.html","label":"DeletionPolicy and UpdateReplacePolicy Attributes – AWS Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/using-cfn-protect-stacks.html","label":"CloudFormation Stack Termination Protection – AWS Documentation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team manages a large AWS environment using AWS CloudFormation. They have a stack that provisions an Amazon RDS Multi-AZ instance, several Auto Scaling groups, and associated networking resources. During a recent deployment, a change to the RDS instance's DBInstanceClass caused CloudFormation to interrupt the database workload unexpectedly. The team wants to prevent future stack updates from unintentionally modifying or replacing the RDS instance while still allowing updates to other resources in the same stack. The solution must not require splitting the stack. Which CloudFormation feature should the team implement to meet this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team manages a globally distributed e-commerce application running on AWS. The application uses an Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL Multi-AZ instance as its primary database. During a recent failover drill, the team observed that the application experienced approximately 90 seconds of downtime before successfully reconnecting to the new primary instance. The RDS DNS TTL was already set to 5 seconds on the application servers. After investigation, the team determines that the application connection pool is caching the resolved IP address and does not honor the updated DNS record after failover. The team also needs to ensure that read-heavy reporting queries do not impact the primary instance during normal operations. Which combination of changes should the team implement to MOST effectively minimize failover downtime and isolate read traffic? (Select ONE)$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Migrate the database to Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL with Multi-AZ enabled. Configure the application to use the Aurora cluster endpoint for writes and the Aurora reader endpoint for read-heavy reporting queries. Update the connection pool library to use TCP keepalive settings and set the connection timeout to detect stale connections within 5 seconds."},{"id":"b","text":"Keep the existing RDS Multi-AZ instance. Add an ElastiCache for Redis cluster in front of the database to cache reporting query results. Configure the application connection pool to close and reopen connections every 30 seconds regardless of connection health."},{"id":"c","text":"Migrate the database to Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL with Multi-AZ enabled. Configure the application to use only the Aurora cluster endpoint for all traffic, including reporting queries, and increase the connection pool size to absorb failover spikes."},{"id":"d","text":"Keep the existing RDS Multi-AZ instance and add an RDS read replica in a second Availability Zone. Configure the application to send all traffic through an Application Load Balancer target group that distributes connections between the primary and read replica instances."},{"id":"e","text":"Migrate the database to Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL Global Database across two AWS Regions. Configure the application to use the primary Region cluster endpoint for writes and a Route 53 latency-based record pointing to both regional reader endpoints for reporting queries, without modifying the connection pool behavior."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option A is correct because Aurora PostgreSQL with Multi-AZ significantly reduces failover time compared to standard RDS Multi-AZ — Aurora typically completes a failover in under 30 seconds (often under 15 seconds) because it uses a shared distributed storage layer and only needs to promote a replica rather than restore from a standby. The Aurora cluster endpoint (writer endpoint) always resolves to the current primary after failover, and the reader endpoint automatically distributes read traffic across Aurora Replicas, directly solving both the failover latency problem and the read isolation requirement. Configuring TCP keepalive and short connection timeouts ensures the connection pool detects broken connections quickly and re-resolves the DNS to the new primary. Option B is incorrect because ElastiCache does not solve the root cause of connection pool IP caching during RDS failover; arbitrarily recycling connections every 30 seconds is disruptive and not a reliable failover mechanism. Option C is incorrect because routing all traffic — including heavy reporting queries — through the writer endpoint defeats the purpose of Aurora Replicas and puts unnecessary load on the primary instance. Option D is incorrect because an Application Load Balancer is not designed to proxy database TCP connections for PostgreSQL; ALBs operate at HTTP layer 7 and cannot natively load-balance PostgreSQL wire protocol connections this way. Option E is incorrect because Aurora Global Database is designed for cross-region disaster recovery with RPOs of under 1 second and RTOs of under 1 minute via managed failover, but it does not resolve the connection pool IP-caching problem within a region, and failing to modify the connection pool behavior leaves the original root cause unaddressed.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/AuroraUserGuide/Concepts.AuroraHighAvailability.html","label":"Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL — High Availability and Failover"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/AuroraUserGuide/Aurora.Overview.Endpoints.html","label":"Amazon Aurora Connection Management — Cluster and Reader Endpoints"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/UserGuide/Concepts.MultiAZ.html","label":"Amazon RDS Multi-AZ Deployments — Failover Process"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/AuroraUserGuide/aurora-global-database-disaster-recovery.html","label":"Aurora Global Database — Managed Planned Failover"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team manages a globally distributed e-commerce application running on AWS. The application uses an Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL Multi-AZ instance as its primary database. During a recent failover drill, the team observed that the application experienced approximately 90 seconds of downtime before successfully reconnecting to the new primary instance. The RDS DNS TTL was already set to 5 seconds on the application servers. After investigation, the team determines that the application connection pool is caching the resolved IP address and does not honor the updated DNS record after failover. The team also needs to ensure that read-heavy reporting queries do not impact the primary instance during normal operations. Which combination of changes should the team implement to MOST effectively minimize failover downtime and isolate read traffic? (Select ONE)$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is running a microservices application on Amazon ECS (Fargate launch type) across three AWS regions. They use Amazon CloudWatch Container Insights to collect metrics and logs. Recently, the team noticed intermittent latency spikes in one region but cannot correlate them with specific containers or tasks because logs from multiple services are mixed in a single CloudWatch Log Group. They need a solution that: (1) enables per-service log isolation, (2) allows cross-region aggregation of structured logs for a unified operational view, (3) supports near-real-time anomaly detection on latency metrics without managing additional compute infrastructure, and (4) retains raw logs for 13 months to meet compliance requirements. Which combination of actions satisfies ALL of these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Configure each ECS task definition to use the awslogs log driver with a unique Log Group per service (e.g., /ecs/service-name). Enable CloudWatch Log Insights cross-log-group queries for aggregation. Enable CloudWatch Anomaly Detection on the ECSService/CPUUtilization and custom latency metrics. Set each Log Group's retention policy to 395 days."},{"id":"b","text":"Configure each ECS task definition to use the awsfirelens log driver routing logs to Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose, which delivers to Amazon S3 (for 13-month retention) and to a separate CloudWatch Log Group per service. Use CloudWatch Cross-Account Observability to aggregate logs across regions into a monitoring account. Enable CloudWatch Anomaly Detection on latency metrics in each region. Set each Log Group's retention policy to 395 days."},{"id":"c","text":"Configure each ECS task definition to use the awslogs log driver writing to a single shared CloudWatch Log Group, and use CloudWatch Logs metric filters with service-name prefixes to isolate per-service data. Deploy an AWS Lambda function triggered by CloudWatch Logs subscriptions to replicate logs cross-region. Use Amazon Lookout for Metrics for anomaly detection on latency, and configure S3 lifecycle rules to expire objects after 395 days."},{"id":"d","text":"Configure each ECS task definition to use the awsfirelens log driver routing to Amazon OpenSearch Service (one domain per region). Use cross-cluster replication for cross-region aggregation. Deploy an AWS Lambda function on a schedule to run anomaly detection queries against OpenSearch. Archive logs to S3 using OpenSearch index snapshots and configure a lifecycle policy to retain them for 395 days."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option B satisfies all four requirements: (1) Per-service log isolation — using the awsfirelens log driver with Kinesis Data Firehose allows structured routing of logs to dedicated CloudWatch Log Groups per service, cleanly isolating each service's logs rather than mixing them. (2) Cross-region aggregation — CloudWatch Cross-Account Observability (the CloudWatch cross-region/cross-account feature) allows a central monitoring account to query and view Log Groups across regions without duplicating infrastructure. (3) Near-real-time anomaly detection without managing compute — CloudWatch Anomaly Detection uses ML models built directly into CloudWatch to detect anomalies on metric streams (including custom latency metrics) with no additional compute resources required. (4) 13-month (395-day) retention — CloudWatch Log Group retention can be set to 395 days natively, and Firehose simultaneously delivers raw logs to S3 for durable long-term storage. Option A fails because CloudWatch Log Insights cross-log-group queries require log groups to already exist in the same region and do not provide true cross-region aggregation in a unified view without Cross-Account Observability. Option C fails because it uses a single shared Log Group (violating requirement 1) and relies on Lambda for cross-region replication (additional compute infrastructure, violating requirement 3). Option D fails because OpenSearch cross-cluster replication is complex infrastructure to manage and Lambda-based scheduled anomaly detection is not 'near-real-time' and requires managing additional compute.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/using_firelens.html","label":"AWS FireLens – Custom log routing for Amazon ECS"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/CloudWatch-Unified-Cross-Account.html","label":"Amazon CloudWatch Cross-Account Observability"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/CloudWatch_Anomaly_Detection.html","label":"CloudWatch Anomaly Detection"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/logs/Working-with-log-groups-and-streams.html#SettingLogRetention","label":"CloudWatch Logs retention policy settings"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/firehose/latest/dev/create-destination.html#create-destination-s3","label":"Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose – Delivering to Amazon S3"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is running a microservices application on Amazon ECS (Fargate launch type) across three AWS regions. They use Amazon CloudWatch Container Insights to collect metrics and logs. Recently, the team noticed intermittent latency spikes in one region but cannot correlate them with specific containers or tasks because logs from multiple services are mixed in a single CloudWatch Log Group. They need a solution that: (1) enables per-service log isolation, (2) allows cross-region aggregation of structured logs for a unified operational view, (3) supports near-real-time anomaly detection on latency metrics without managing additional compute infrastructure, and (4) retains raw logs for 13 months to meet compliance requirements. Which combination of actions satisfies ALL of these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is running a critical e-commerce platform on AWS. During a Black Friday sale, an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances begins experiencing intermittent failures. CloudWatch alarms fire indicating that roughly 30% of instances are failing their ELB health checks, but the instances still show a status of 'InService' within the Auto Scaling group. The on-call engineer needs to immediately isolate the unhealthy instances for forensic analysis WITHOUT terminating them, while simultaneously ensuring new healthy capacity is launched to restore service. Which combination of actions should the engineer take?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Place the unhealthy instances into the 'Standby' state using the EnterStandby API call, then manually trigger a scaling activity by updating the Auto Scaling group's desired capacity to compensate for the removed instances, and attach an IAM instance profile to the standby instances to allow SSM Session Manager access for forensic investigation."},{"id":"b","text":"Detach the unhealthy instances from the Auto Scaling group using the DetachInstances API call with the 'ShouldDecrementDesiredCapacity' flag set to false, then use EC2 Instance Connect or SSM Session Manager on the detached instances for forensic investigation, while the Auto Scaling group automatically launches replacement instances to meet the unchanged desired capacity."},{"id":"c","text":"Terminate the unhealthy instances immediately and rely on the Auto Scaling group's health check replacement mechanism to launch new instances, then retrieve instance logs from CloudWatch Logs Insights before termination completes using lifecycle hooks configured on the 'EC2_INSTANCE_TERMINATING' transition."},{"id":"d","text":"Suspend the 'HealthCheck' and 'ReplaceUnhealthy' Auto Scaling processes using the SuspendProcesses API call, manually deregister the unhealthy instances from the load balancer target group, launch replacement On-Demand instances separately outside the Auto Scaling group, and then re-enable the suspended processes after forensic analysis is complete."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option B is correct because DetachInstances with 'ShouldDecrementDesiredCapacity=false' is the ideal forensic isolation mechanism. When this flag is set to false, the Auto Scaling group's desired capacity remains unchanged, so the group immediately launches replacement instances to compensate — restoring healthy capacity automatically. The detached instances become standalone EC2 instances that are no longer managed by the Auto Scaling group lifecycle (they won't be terminated), allowing engineers to safely perform forensic analysis via SSM Session Manager or EC2 Instance Connect. Option A is incorrect because the 'Standby' state keeps instances under Auto Scaling group management (they are still counted toward desired capacity if ShouldDecrementDesiredCapacity=false is not used correctly), and more critically, entering Standby does adjust desired capacity by default, meaning replacement instances are NOT automatically launched unless desired capacity is manually incremented afterward — making it a more error-prone two-step process compared to Detach. Additionally, attaching an IAM instance profile is a separate concern that does not directly address the isolation and replacement requirement. Option C is incorrect because terminating the instances destroys the evidence needed for forensic analysis. Lifecycle hooks on 'EC2_INSTANCE_TERMINATING' introduce latency but do not preserve the instance for hands-on investigation; logs alone are insufficient for deep forensic analysis of a running process or memory state. Option D is incorrect because suspending 'HealthCheck' and 'ReplaceUnhealthy' processes prevents the Auto Scaling group from healing itself, and manually launching instances outside the group introduces unmanaged capacity that won't benefit from group-level policies or target tracking. This approach is operationally risky during an active incident.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/detach-instance-asg.html","label":"Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling – Detach EC2 instances from your Auto Scaling group"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/as-enter-exit-standby.html","label":"Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling – Temporarily removing instances from your Auto Scaling group (Standby state)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/as-suspend-resume-processes.html","label":"Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling – Suspending and resuming scaling processes"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/systems-manager/latest/userguide/session-manager-working-with-sessions-start.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Session Manager – Connect to a managed instance"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is running a critical e-commerce platform on AWS. During a Black Friday sale, an Auto Scaling group of EC2 instances begins experiencing intermittent failures. CloudWatch alarms fire indicating that roughly 30% of instances are failing their ELB health checks, but the instances still show a status of 'InService' within the Auto Scaling group. The on-call engineer needs to immediately isolate the unhealthy instances for forensic analysis WITHOUT terminating them, while simultaneously ensuring new healthy capacity is launched to restore service. Which combination of actions should the engineer take?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineering team at a financial services company manages hundreds of AWS accounts through AWS Organizations. A new regulatory requirement mandates that all Amazon S3 buckets across every account must never have Block Public Access settings disabled at the bucket level, and any non-compliant bucket must be automatically remediated within 15 minutes of detection. The solution must also generate an audit trail of all remediation actions taken. Which combination of AWS services and configurations will meet these requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Deploy an AWS Config Organization Conformance Pack using the managed rule 's3-bucket-level-public-access-prohibited' across all accounts. Configure an AWS Config Remediation Action linked to an AWS Systems Manager Automation document (AWS-DisableS3BucketPublicReadWrite) with auto-remediation enabled and a maximum auto-remediation attempts value of 5. Stream AWS Config configuration change events to AWS CloudTrail for the audit trail."},{"id":"b","text":"Create an AWS CloudTrail Organization Trail to detect S3 PutBucketPublicAccessBlock API calls. Use Amazon EventBridge rules to trigger an AWS Lambda function that re-enables Block Public Access on non-compliant buckets. Store Lambda invocation logs in Amazon CloudWatch Logs and export them to Amazon S3 for the audit trail."},{"id":"c","text":"Deploy an AWS Config Organization Conformance Pack using the managed rule 's3-bucket-level-public-access-prohibited' across all accounts. Configure an AWS Config Remediation Action linked to an AWS Systems Manager Automation document (AWS-ConfigureS3BucketPublicAccessBlock) with auto-remediation enabled, set the retry interval to satisfy the 15-minute SLA, and capture all remediation execution results in AWS CloudTrail via AWS Config delivery channel logs."},{"id":"d","text":"Use Amazon GuardDuty to detect S3 bucket policy changes across all Organization accounts. Configure an Amazon EventBridge rule to match GuardDuty findings of type 'Policy:S3/BucketBlockPublicAccessDisabled' and trigger an AWS Step Functions state machine that calls the S3 PutPublicAccessBlock API and writes remediation records to an Amazon DynamoDB table for auditing."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option C is correct because it combines the three required capabilities with the least operational overhead: (1) AWS Config Organization Conformance Packs deploy and manage Config rules centrally across all member accounts without per-account configuration, satisfying the multi-account mandate; (2) the managed rule 's3-bucket-level-public-access-prohibited' continuously evaluates bucket-level Block Public Access settings and flags non-compliant resources; (3) the AWS Systems Manager Automation document 'AWS-ConfigureS3BucketPublicAccessBlock' is specifically designed to enable all four Block Public Access flags on an S3 bucket, and enabling auto-remediation in AWS Config ensures remediation triggers automatically upon evaluation within the 15-minute window; (4) AWS Config delivers configuration change and compliance history (including remediation execution results) to an S3 delivery channel, and these events appear in AWS CloudTrail as AWS Config API calls, providing a durable audit trail — no additional custom code or infrastructure is required. Option A is incorrect because 'AWS-DisableS3BucketPublicReadWrite' removes public ACLs and bucket policies but does not specifically set the S3 Block Public Access flags, and CloudTrail alone does not record Config remediation execution details as an audit log without the Config delivery channel. Option B is incorrect because CloudTrail data events for S3 do not surface PutBucketPublicAccessBlock status changes in a way that reliably triggers 15-minute remediation; the event-driven Lambda approach also requires per-account IAM role provisioning and cross-account Lambda invocation plumbing, increasing operational overhead. Option D is incorrect because GuardDuty finding type 'Policy:S3/BucketBlockPublicAccessDisabled' may have detection latency exceeding 15 minutes, GuardDuty does not guarantee near-real-time evaluation of configuration changes, and a Step Functions + DynamoDB audit pattern adds significant operational complexity compared to the native Config remediation and delivery channel mechanism.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/conformance-pack-organization-apis.html","label":"AWS Config Organization Conformance Packs"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/s3-bucket-level-public-access-prohibited.html","label":"AWS Config Managed Rule: s3-bucket-level-public-access-prohibited"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/remediation.html","label":"AWS Config Automatic Remediation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/systems-manager-automation-runbooks/latest/userguide/automation-aws-configures3bucketpublicaccessblock.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Automation Document: AWS-ConfigureS3BucketPublicAccessBlock"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/access-control-block-public-access.html","label":"Amazon S3 Block Public Access"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/manage-delivery-channel.html","label":"AWS Config Delivery Channel"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
