-- DOP-C02-P6: 5 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is managing a multi-account AWS environment using AWS CloudFormation StackSets. They have a central StackSet that deploys IAM roles and Config rules across 50 AWS accounts in 6 regions. After a recent organizational restructuring, they need to update the StackSet to add a new IAM permission boundary to all deployed IAM roles. During a test rollout, they notice that accounts in one particular AWS Organizations OU are failing with the error 'StackInstanceNotFoundException' while all other OUs succeed. The team needs to ensure the update completes successfully across all accounts with minimal operational overhead and without losing drift detection history. Which combination of actions should the DevOps engineer take to resolve this issue and complete the rollout? (Select ONE)$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Delete all stack instances in the failing OU and re-create the StackSet deployment targeting that OU separately, then use AWS Config aggregator to manually reconstruct drift detection history from historical snapshots stored in S3."},{"id":"b","text":"Use the 'aws cloudformation list-stack-instances' command to identify accounts in the failing OU that are missing stack instances, use 'create-stack-instances' to provision the missing instances in those specific accounts, then re-run the StackSet update operation with UNION fault tolerance set to allow the previously failing accounts to be included in the same update wave."},{"id":"c","text":"Increase the StackSet operation's 'MaxConcurrentPercentage' to 100% and 'FailureTolerancePercentage' to 50%, then retry the update so that failing accounts are skipped automatically and the remaining accounts complete the update."},{"id":"d","text":"Detach the failing OU from the StackSet deployment targets, update the StackSet for the remaining OUs, then re-attach the failing OU by adding it back as a deployment target so that CloudFormation automatically reconciles and updates the missing stack instances during the next scheduled drift detection cycle."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option B is correct because 'StackInstanceNotFoundException' typically occurs when CloudFormation StackSets attempts to update stack instances that do not exist in certain accounts — often caused by accounts being moved between OUs after the StackSet was initially deployed, or accounts that were added to the OU after the StackSet deployment without explicitly creating instances in them. The correct remediation is to first identify the affected accounts using 'list-stack-instances', then explicitly provision the missing stack instances using 'create-stack-instances' targeting those specific accounts and regions. Once the instances exist, the pending update operation can be re-run and will succeed. This approach preserves drift detection history on all existing stack instances because no instances are deleted or replaced. Option A is incorrect because deleting and re-creating stack instances destroys drift detection history and introduces unnecessary operational overhead. Option C is incorrect because raising fault tolerance percentages only masks the failure by allowing the operation to be marked successful even when accounts are skipped — it does not resolve the underlying missing stack instance problem and those accounts remain out of compliance. Option D is incorrect because CloudFormation StackSets does not automatically reconcile or create missing stack instances during drift detection cycles; drift detection only evaluates existing instances and does not provision new ones.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/stacksets-getting-started-create.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation StackSets - Create Stack Instances"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/stacksets-concepts.html#stackset-ops-options","label":"AWS CloudFormation StackSets Operations and Fault Tolerance"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/stacksets-drift.html","label":"Detecting Unmanaged Configuration Changes to Stacks and Stack Sets"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/reference/cloudformation/create-stack-instances.html","label":"AWS CLI - create-stack-instances Reference"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is managing a multi-account AWS environment using AWS CloudFormation StackSets. They have a central StackSet that deploys IAM roles and Config rules across 50 AWS accounts in 6 regions. After a recent organizational restructuring, they need to update the StackSet to add a new IAM permission boundary to all deployed IAM roles. During a test rollout, they notice that accounts in one particular AWS Organizations OU are failing with the error 'StackInstanceNotFoundException' while all other OUs succeed. The team needs to ensure the update completes successfully across all accounts with minimal operational overhead and without losing drift detection history. Which combination of actions should the DevOps engineer take to resolve this issue and complete the rollout? (Select ONE)$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team manages a multi-tier e-commerce application deployed across three AWS Regions: us-east-1 (primary), eu-west-1, and ap-southeast-1. The application uses Amazon Aurora Global Database for its data layer and Amazon DynamoDB global tables for session management. During a recent incident, a full Regional failure in us-east-1 caused an unplanned outage lasting 47 minutes because the team lacked a tested failover runbook. Leadership has mandated an RTO of 5 minutes and an RPO of 30 seconds for all Tier-1 workloads. The team must implement an automated, cross-Regional failover mechanism that promotes a secondary Aurora cluster, re-routes traffic, and validates application health — all without manual intervention. Which combination of AWS services and configuration steps will BEST meet the RTO and RPO requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Configure Amazon Route 53 Application Recovery Controller (ARC) with routing controls and safety rules. Use AWS Systems Manager Automation runbooks triggered by an Amazon CloudWatch alarm on the primary Region to flip Route 53 routing controls, initiate an Aurora Global Database managed planned failover (or unplanned detach-and-promote), and run health-check assertions. Store Aurora cluster ARNs and endpoint mappings in AWS AppConfig so the automation document can dynamically resolve targets without hardcoded values."},{"id":"b","text":"Deploy an AWS Lambda function in each Region that polls a custom health endpoint every 60 seconds. When the function detects a failure, it updates an Amazon Route 53 weighted routing policy to shift 100% of weight to the secondary Region and sends an Amazon SNS notification to the on-call engineer, who then manually promotes the Aurora secondary cluster using the AWS Management Console."},{"id":"c","text":"Use AWS Global Accelerator with endpoint weights set to 100/0 between Regions. Configure an AWS CloudFormation StackSet that, upon stack drift detection, re-deploys the entire application stack in the secondary Region from scratch including a new Aurora cluster restored from the latest automated snapshot, targeting a full re-provisioning time of under 30 minutes."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable Amazon Aurora Multi-AZ within us-east-1 and configure cross-Region read replicas promoted manually during a failure. Use Amazon Route 53 latency-based routing without health checks to direct users and rely on client-side retry logic with exponential back-off to tolerate the failover window, accepting an RTO of up to 20 minutes."},{"id":"e","text":"Implement AWS Resilience Hub to continuously assess the workload and auto-remediate failures. Configure Resilience Hub to automatically perform Aurora Global Database failover and update Route 53 DNS records when the resilience score drops below the defined threshold, without requiring any additional runbooks or CloudWatch alarms."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option A is correct because it combines the right services with the right level of automation to achieve a 5-minute RTO and 30-second RPO. Route 53 Application Recovery Controller (ARC) provides pre-staged routing controls with safety rules that prevent split-brain scenarios during failover — critical for multi-Region active-passive architectures. AWS Systems Manager Automation runbooks enable fully automated, auditable orchestration that can execute in parallel: (1) triggering an Aurora Global Database managed failover (which preserves replication lag typically under 1 second, satisfying the 30-second RPO), (2) atomically flipping ARC routing controls to redirect traffic, and (3) running synthetic health checks to validate readiness before completing. Using AWS AppConfig for dynamic endpoint resolution avoids hardcoded values that break when cluster ARNs change after promotion. Together, this architecture can achieve failover in 2–4 minutes when pre-tested. Option B fails the RTO because manual Aurora promotion is required — human response time alone exceeds 5 minutes under incident pressure, and a 60-second polling interval introduces unnecessary detection lag. Option C fails because restoring from a snapshot (even the latest automated snapshot) has an RPO of up to 5 minutes for Aurora and a provisioning time measured in tens of minutes — far exceeding both targets. Global Accelerator alone does not orchestrate database failover. Option D fails both targets: Multi-AZ protects against Availability Zone failures but not Regional failures, cross-Region read replica promotion is a manual process, and the stated RTO of 20 minutes is explicitly out of scope. Latency-based routing without health checks will continue sending traffic to an unhealthy Region. Option E is a common distractor — AWS Resilience Hub is an assessment and recommendation tool that calculates resilience scores and can trigger AWS FIS experiments, but it does NOT autonomously execute production failovers or modify Route 53 routing in real time. It requires separate automation (such as Systems Manager runbooks) to act on its findings.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/r53recovery/latest/dg/routing-control.html","label":"Amazon Route 53 Application Recovery Controller – Routing Controls"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/AuroraUserGuide/aurora-global-database-disaster-recovery.html","label":"Amazon Aurora Global Database – Managed Planned Failover"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/systems-manager/latest/userguide/systems-manager-automation.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Automation – Runbook Reference"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/appconfig/latest/userguide/what-is-appconfig.html","label":"AWS AppConfig – Feature Flags and Dynamic Configuration"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/resilience-hub/latest/userguide/what-is.html","label":"AWS Resilience Hub – Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team manages a multi-tier e-commerce application deployed across three AWS Regions: us-east-1 (primary), eu-west-1, and ap-southeast-1. The application uses Amazon Aurora Global Database for its data layer and Amazon DynamoDB global tables for session management. During a recent incident, a full Regional failure in us-east-1 caused an unplanned outage lasting 47 minutes because the team lacked a tested failover runbook. Leadership has mandated an RTO of 5 minutes and an RPO of 30 seconds for all Tier-1 workloads. The team must implement an automated, cross-Regional failover mechanism that promotes a secondary Aurora cluster, re-routes traffic, and validates application health — all without manual intervention. Which combination of AWS services and configuration steps will BEST meet the RTO and RPO requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team manages a large-scale microservices application deployed on Amazon ECS (Fargate). Each service emits structured JSON logs to Amazon CloudWatch Logs. The team needs to implement a solution that: (1) detects when any individual service's error rate (log entries containing '"level":"ERROR"') exceeds 5% of total log entries within a 5-minute window, (2) triggers an automated remediation workflow via AWS Step Functions, and (3) retains aggregated per-service error-rate metrics in CloudWatch for 15 months for compliance auditing. Which combination of steps will satisfy ALL three requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create a CloudWatch Logs Metric Filter on each service's log group that increments a custom metric 'ErrorCount' for each ERROR log entry and a second Metric Filter that increments 'TotalCount' for every log entry. Create a CloudWatch Metric Math expression (ErrorCount / TotalCount * 100) as a CloudWatch Alarm with a 5-minute period and a threshold of 5. Configure the alarm's SNS action to trigger an AWS Lambda function that starts the Step Functions execution. Set the CloudWatch custom metric storage resolution to standard (60-second) and configure a 15-month metric retention policy via the PutMetricData API's StorageResolution parameter."},{"id":"b","text":"Create a CloudWatch Logs Metric Filter on each service's log group that increments a custom metric 'ErrorCount' for each ERROR log entry and a separate Metric Filter incrementing 'TotalCount' for every log entry. Publish both metrics under the same CloudWatch custom namespace. Build a CloudWatch Alarm using a Metric Math expression (m1/m2*100) with a 5-minute evaluation period and a threshold of 5. Configure the alarm to directly invoke the Step Functions state machine via an Amazon EventBridge Pipe. Set the CloudWatch metric's default retention to 15 months (63 weeks) using the aws cloudwatch put-metric-data command's '--storage-resolution' flag and enable Extended Metrics."},{"id":"c","text":"Create a CloudWatch Logs Metric Filter on each service's log group to emit a custom metric 'ErrorCount' for ERROR-level entries and another Metric Filter to emit 'TotalCount' for all entries, both under a shared CloudWatch custom namespace. Define a CloudWatch Alarm using Metric Math (ErrorCount / TotalCount * 100) with a 5-minute period and a threshold of 5. Set the alarm action to publish to an SNS topic that triggers a Lambda function, which in turn calls StartExecution on the Step Functions state machine. Adjust the CloudWatch custom metric retention period to 63 weeks (approximately 15 months) via the AWS Console or PutMetricDataAPI namespace-level settings, which CloudWatch supports for custom metrics."},{"id":"d","text":"Deploy a CloudWatch Logs subscription filter on each service's log group to stream logs to Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose, which delivers to Amazon S3. Use an AWS Glue crawler to catalog the S3 data, then run hourly Amazon Athena queries to calculate error rates. Trigger an EventBridge Scheduled Rule every 5 minutes to invoke a Lambda function that executes the Athena query, evaluates the result, and starts the Step Functions execution if the threshold is exceeded. Store aggregated metrics back in CloudWatch using PutMetricData for 15-month retention."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option C is correct because it satisfies all three requirements using native CloudWatch capabilities with minimal operational overhead. (1) CloudWatch Logs Metric Filters are the native, lowest-overhead mechanism for converting log patterns into CloudWatch metrics — one filter counts ERROR entries and another counts all entries. A Metric Math alarm (ErrorCount / TotalCount * 100) with a 5-minute period accurately computes the error rate without requiring any additional compute. (2) An SNS topic triggering a Lambda function that calls Step Functions StartExecution is the standard, well-documented integration pattern; CloudWatch Alarms cannot invoke Step Functions directly without Lambda or EventBridge as an intermediary — and using EventBridge Pipes (option B) for alarm-to-Step Functions integration adds unnecessary complexity versus a simple SNS→Lambda→Step Functions chain. (3) CloudWatch custom metrics have a configurable retention period; the maximum supported retention is 15 months (63 weeks), which satisfies the compliance requirement. This is set at the namespace/metric level and does not require any special '--storage-resolution' flag on PutMetricData (which controls granularity, not retention — making option A's claim incorrect). Option A is incorrect because CloudWatch Alarms already support Metric Math natively without needing Lambda for the alarm action itself for detection, but more critically it conflates '--storage-resolution' (high-resolution vs. standard granularity) with retention policy configuration, which are separate concepts. Option B is incorrect because CloudWatch Alarms do not integrate directly with EventBridge Pipes for Step Functions invocation in a standard supported pattern, and the '--storage-resolution' flag does not control retention. Option D is incorrect because it introduces Kinesis, Glue, Athena, and scheduled Lambda functions — a highly complex architecture that violates the least operational overhead requirement when native CloudWatch Metric Filters and alarms accomplish the same goal.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/logs/MonitoringLogData.html","label":"CloudWatch Logs Metric Filters – AWS Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/using-metric-math.html","label":"Using Metric Math with CloudWatch Alarms"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/cloudwatch_concepts.html#metrics-retention","label":"CloudWatch Metrics Retention – AWS Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/step-functions/latest/dg/concepts-amazon-states-language.html","label":"Invoking AWS Step Functions from Amazon SNS via Lambda"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/APIReference/API_MetricDatum.html","label":"PutMetricData – StorageResolution Parameter"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team manages a large-scale microservices application deployed on Amazon ECS (Fargate). Each service emits structured JSON logs to Amazon CloudWatch Logs. The team needs to implement a solution that: (1) detects when any individual service's error rate (log entries containing '"level":"ERROR"') exceeds 5% of total log entries within a 5-minute window, (2) triggers an automated remediation workflow via AWS Step Functions, and (3) retains aggregated per-service error-rate metrics in CloudWatch for 15 months for compliance auditing. Which combination of steps will satisfy ALL three requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is operating a multi-tier e-commerce application on AWS. During a Black Friday sale, an Amazon CloudWatch alarm triggers indicating that the application's order-processing service is experiencing a sudden spike in error rates, with HTTP 500 responses climbing above 40%. The team has AWS Systems Manager (SSM) Automation runbooks, AWS Lambda functions, and Amazon EventBridge rules already configured. The application runs on Amazon ECS (Fargate), uses Amazon RDS Multi-AZ for its database, and sits behind an Application Load Balancer. The on-call engineer suspects a bad deployment pushed 20 minutes ago is the root cause. Which combination of actions represents the MOST operationally effective automated incident response to immediately mitigate customer impact while preserving forensic evidence for post-incident review?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Trigger an SSM Automation runbook via EventBridge that: (1) captures the current ECS task definition ARN and stores it in AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store, (2) rolls back the ECS service to the previous task definition revision using the UpdateService API, (3) takes an RDS manual snapshot for forensic preservation, and (4) publishes a notification to an Amazon SNS topic to alert stakeholders — all without human intervention."},{"id":"b","text":"Manually SSH into the underlying EC2 instances hosting the ECS tasks, capture application logs, terminate the bad tasks individually, and then redeploy the previous Docker image by updating the ECS service through the AWS Management Console."},{"id":"c","text":"Increase the ECS service's desired task count to absorb additional load, disable the CloudWatch alarm temporarily to reduce noise, and schedule a maintenance window through AWS Systems Manager to perform the rollback during off-peak hours."},{"id":"d","text":"Detach the Application Load Balancer target group from the ECS service, redirect traffic to a static S3-hosted maintenance page using Route 53 weighted routing, and delete the current ECS task definition to prevent further bad deployments, then manually redeploy from source."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option A is correct because it embodies AWS best practices for automated incident response with forensic preservation. (1) Storing the current task definition ARN in Parameter Store creates an auditable record before any change — critical for post-incident review. (2) Rolling back the ECS service to the previous task definition revision via UpdateService is the fastest, least-disruptive mitigation for a bad deployment on Fargate — ECS drains connections gracefully and launches replacement tasks without downtime. (3) An RDS manual snapshot preserves the database state at the time of the incident, satisfying forensic and compliance requirements without impacting availability (Multi-AZ remains operational). (4) SNS notification ensures stakeholder communication aligns with incident management protocols. Automating all steps through an EventBridge-triggered SSM Automation runbook reduces MTTR and eliminates human error under pressure. — Option B is wrong because Fargate tasks have no underlying EC2 instances to SSH into, and a manual console-driven process is slow and error-prone during a high-severity incident. — Option C is wrong because scaling up does not fix application-level 500 errors caused by a bad code deployment; disabling an alarm destroys observability; and deferring a rollback to off-peak hours prolongs customer impact during peak sales. — Option D is wrong because deleting a task definition revision is a destructive action that complicates future deployments and forensic review; Route 53 weighted routing changes propagate via DNS TTL and are not instantaneous; and serving a static maintenance page is a last resort, not a preferred mitigation when a clean rollback is available.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/update-service.html","label":"Amazon ECS — Updating a Service (Rolling Rollback)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/systems-manager/latest/userguide/systems-manager-automation.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Automation — Runbook Concepts"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/eventbridge/latest/userguide/eb-service-event.html","label":"Amazon EventBridge — Using EventBridge with AWS Services"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/UserGuide/USER_CreateSnapshot.html","label":"Amazon RDS — Creating a DB Snapshot"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/wellarchitected/latest/operational-excellence-pillar/respond-to-events.html","label":"AWS Well-Architected Framework — Operational Excellence Pillar (Respond to Events)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is operating a multi-tier e-commerce application on AWS. During a Black Friday sale, an Amazon CloudWatch alarm triggers indicating that the application's order-processing service is experiencing a sudden spike in error rates, with HTTP 500 responses climbing above 40%. The team has AWS Systems Manager (SSM) Automation runbooks, AWS Lambda functions, and Amazon EventBridge rules already configured. The application runs on Amazon ECS (Fargate), uses Amazon RDS Multi-AZ for its database, and sits behind an Application Load Balancer. The on-call engineer suspects a bad deployment pushed 20 minutes ago is the root cause. Which combination of actions represents the MOST operationally effective automated incident response to immediately mitigate customer impact while preserving forensic evidence for post-incident review?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is managing a multi-account AWS environment using AWS Organizations. They need to enforce a policy that prevents any IAM principal in member accounts from disabling AWS CloudTrail logging or deleting CloudTrail trails, even if those principals have AdministratorAccess. The policy must not interfere with the management account's ability to administer CloudTrail centrally. Which solution meets these requirements with the least operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create an IAM permission boundary in each member account that explicitly denies cloudtrail:StopLogging and cloudtrail:DeleteTrail, and attach it to every IAM role and user in those accounts."},{"id":"b","text":"Create a Service Control Policy (SCP) at the AWS Organizations root or an organizational unit (OU) level that contains an explicit Deny for cloudtrail:StopLogging and cloudtrail:DeleteTrail, and apply it to all member accounts while excluding the management account."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable AWS Config with a managed rule for cloudtrail-enabled in each member account and configure an AWS Lambda auto-remediation function that re-enables CloudTrail whenever it is stopped."},{"id":"d","text":"Use an AWS CloudFormation StackSet deployed from the management account to provision an IAM policy with Deny statements for cloudtrail:StopLogging and cloudtrail:DeleteTrail, and attach it to the root of each member account's IAM hierarchy."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option B is correct. Service Control Policies (SCPs) are the purpose-built AWS Organizations feature for enforcing guardrails across member accounts. An SCP with an explicit Deny for cloudtrail:StopLogging and cloudtrail:DeleteTrail applied at the root or OU level overrides even AdministratorAccess in member accounts, because SCPs define the maximum permissions boundary for all principals in those accounts. SCPs do not apply to the management account by design, satisfying the requirement to leave central administration unaffected. This is the lowest-overhead solution because it requires a single policy change rather than per-account or per-principal configuration. Option A is incorrect because permission boundaries must be individually attached to every IAM identity; any new role or user created without the boundary would be unprotected, and this approach has high operational overhead. Option C is incorrect because AWS Config with auto-remediation is detective and reactive — there is a window between when CloudTrail is stopped and when Lambda re-enables it, meaning logs could be lost. It does not preventively block the action. Option D is incorrect because IAM policies cannot be attached to the 'root' of an account's IAM hierarchy as a blanket control; they must be attached to specific identities or groups, and StackSets do not reduce the per-account attachment overhead enough to match SCPs.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/organizations/latest/userguide/orgs_manage_policies_scps.html","label":"AWS Organizations – Service Control Policies (SCPs)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/awscloudtrail/latest/userguide/best-practices-security.html","label":"AWS CloudTrail – Protecting CloudTrail with SCPs"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/organizations/latest/userguide/orgs_manage_policies_scps.html#scp-effects-on-root","label":"AWS Organizations – SCP Effects on the Management Account"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P6'
