-- ACE-P2: 3 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Your company is designing a new e-commerce platform on Google Cloud. The application tier requires virtual machines that can handle unpredictable traffic spikes, while the database tier needs consistent high-performance storage with low latency. The solution must also minimize costs during periods of low traffic. Which combination of Google Cloud services and configurations best satisfies these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Use a Managed Instance Group (MIG) with autoscaling for the application tier and Cloud Spanner for the database tier."},{"id":"b","text":"Use a Managed Instance Group (MIG) with autoscaling for the application tier and Cloud SQL with SSD persistent disks for the database tier."},{"id":"c","text":"Use individual Compute Engine VMs with manual scaling for the application tier and Firestore in Datastore mode for the database tier."},{"id":"d","text":"Use Google Kubernetes Engine (GKE) with cluster autoscaler for the application tier and Bigtable for the database tier."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option B is correct because a Managed Instance Group (MIG) with autoscaling allows the application tier to automatically add or remove VM instances in response to traffic spikes, minimizing costs during low-traffic periods by scaling down. Cloud SQL with SSD persistent disks provides consistent, high-performance, low-latency relational database storage suitable for an e-commerce platform. Option A is incorrect because Cloud Spanner, while highly scalable and globally distributed, is significantly more expensive than Cloud SQL and is best suited for globally distributed workloads requiring horizontal scaling — it is over-engineered and cost-inefficient for most standard e-commerce use cases. Option C is incorrect because manual scaling does not address unpredictable traffic spikes and increases operational overhead. Option D is incorrect because while GKE with cluster autoscaler is a valid approach, Bigtable is a NoSQL wide-column store optimized for very high-throughput analytical and time-series workloads, not the transactional relational workloads typical of e-commerce platforms.$patch$, $patch$Planning and configuring a cloud solution$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/compute/docs/instance-groups/creating-groups-of-managed-instances","label":"Google Cloud - Managed Instance Groups Overview"},{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/compute/docs/autoscaler","label":"Google Cloud - Autoscaling Groups of Instances"},{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/sql/docs/introduction","label":"Google Cloud - Cloud SQL Overview"},{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/storage-options","label":"Google Cloud - Storage Options Comparison"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'ACE-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Your company is designing a new e-commerce platform on Google Cloud. The application tier requires virtual machines that can handle unpredictable traffic spikes, while the database tier needs consistent high-performance storage with low latency. The solution must also minimize costs during periods of low traffic. Which combination of Google Cloud services and configurations best satisfies these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Your team runs a production workload on Google Kubernetes Engine (GKE). A critical Deployment named `api-server` in the `prod` namespace is experiencing degraded performance. You suspect a recent rollout introduced a regression. You need to immediately revert the Deployment to its previous stable version with the least disruption to running pods. Which command should you run?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"kubectl delete deployment api-server -n prod && kubectl apply -f api-server-previous.yaml"},{"id":"b","text":"kubectl rollout undo deployment/api-server -n prod"},{"id":"c","text":"kubectl rollout restart deployment/api-server -n prod"},{"id":"d","text":"kubectl scale deployment api-server --replicas=0 -n prod && kubectl scale deployment api-server --replicas=3 -n prod"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option B (`kubectl rollout undo deployment/api-server -n prod`) is the correct and least-disruptive approach. Kubernetes stores a rollout history for Deployments, and the `rollout undo` command atomically reverts to the previous ReplicaSet using a rolling update strategy, ensuring pods are replaced gradually without downtime. Option A (delete and re-apply) causes unnecessary downtime by tearing down the entire Deployment before recreating it, and requires a previously saved manifest. Option C (`rollout restart`) performs a rolling restart of the current Deployment revision — it does NOT revert to a prior version; it simply recycles pods on the same image. Option D (scaling to zero then back up) also causes a brief outage and does not revert the container image or configuration to a prior revision.$patch$, $patch$Ensuring successful operation of a cloud solution$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/kubernetes-engine/docs/how-to/updating-apps","label":"Google Cloud – GKE Rolling Updates and Rollbacks"},{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/kubectl/generated/kubectl_rollout/kubectl_rollout_undo/","label":"Kubernetes Docs – kubectl rollout undo"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'ACE-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Your team runs a production workload on Google Kubernetes Engine (GKE). A critical Deployment named `api-server` in the `prod` namespace is experiencing degraded performance. You suspect a recent rollout introduced a regression. You need to immediately revert the Deployment to its previous stable version with the least disruption to running pods. Which command should you run?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Your organization has a team of developers who need to deploy new versions of an application to a specific Google Kubernetes Engine (GKE) cluster in the 'us-central1' region. They should be able to deploy workloads and manage Kubernetes objects within the 'dev-namespace' namespace only, but must NOT have the ability to create or delete the cluster itself, or access any other namespaces. Which combination of steps best satisfies this requirement using the principle of least privilege?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Grant the developers the primitive 'Editor' role at the project level, and use a Kubernetes NetworkPolicy to restrict access to 'dev-namespace'."},{"id":"b","text":"Grant the developers the 'container.developer' predefined IAM role at the project level, which automatically restricts them to a single namespace."},{"id":"c","text":"Grant the developers the 'container.clusterViewer' IAM role at the project level so they can authenticate to the cluster, then create a Kubernetes RoleBinding in 'dev-namespace' that binds them to the built-in 'edit' ClusterRole."},{"id":"d","text":"Grant the developers the 'container.clusterAdmin' IAM role scoped to the specific GKE cluster resource, and rely on RBAC to limit their actions to 'dev-namespace'."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The correct approach is a two-layer model combining IAM and Kubernetes RBAC. First, the 'container.clusterViewer' IAM role gives developers the minimum GCP-level permission needed to authenticate against and describe the cluster (via 'gcloud container clusters get-credentials') without granting any ability to create, modify, or delete the cluster itself. Second, a Kubernetes RoleBinding (not a ClusterRoleBinding) within 'dev-namespace' that references the built-in 'edit' ClusterRole grants them full read/write access to most Kubernetes resource types scoped strictly to that namespace. This satisfies least privilege at both the GCP IAM layer and the Kubernetes RBAC layer.

Option A is wrong because the 'Editor' primitive role is overly broad — it grants wide permissions across all GCP services at the project level, violating least privilege.

Option B is wrong because the 'container.developer' role grants permissions at the GCP API level (e.g., deploying to GKE) but does NOT inherently restrict access to a single Kubernetes namespace; namespace isolation is a Kubernetes RBAC concern, not a flat IAM role feature.

Option D is wrong because 'container.clusterAdmin' grants full administrative control over GKE clusters at the GCP level, including the ability to create and delete clusters, which directly violates the stated requirement.$patch$, $patch$Configuring access and security$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/kubernetes-engine/docs/concepts/access-control","label":"GKE Access Control: IAM and RBAC interaction"},{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/kubernetes-engine/docs/how-to/iam#predefined","label":"GKE Predefined IAM Roles"},{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/access-authn-authz/rbac/","label":"Kubernetes RBAC: Using RBAC Authorization"},{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/kubernetes-engine/docs/how-to/hardening-your-cluster","label":"GKE Hardening your cluster's security"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'ACE-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Your organization has a team of developers who need to deploy new versions of an application to a specific Google Kubernetes Engine (GKE) cluster in the 'us-central1' region. They should be able to deploy workloads and manage Kubernetes objects within the 'dev-namespace' namespace only, but must NOT have the ability to create or delete the cluster itself, or access any other namespaces. Which combination of steps best satisfies this requirement using the principle of least privilege?$patch$);

-- DA0-001-P4: 3 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data analyst is working with a large retail dataset and needs to identify natural groupings of customers based on purchasing behavior, without any prior knowledge of how many groups exist or what they represent. Which data mining technique is MOST appropriate for this task?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Decision tree classification"},{"id":"b","text":"K-means clustering"},{"id":"c","text":"Linear regression"},{"id":"d","text":"Association rule mining"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$K-means clustering is an unsupervised machine learning technique used to discover natural groupings (clusters) within a dataset when the categories are not known in advance. It is ideal when there are no predefined labels and the goal is to segment data into meaningful groups based on similarity — exactly what this scenario describes. Decision tree classification (A) is a supervised technique that requires labeled training data with known outcomes, making it unsuitable when groups are unknown. Linear regression (C) is used for predicting continuous numerical outcomes and is not designed for grouping or segmentation tasks. Association rule mining (D) is used to discover relationships or co-occurrence patterns between items (e.g., market basket analysis), not for grouping customers by behavioral similarity.$patch$, $patch$Data Mining$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/data","label":"CompTIA Data+ Exam Objectives (DA0-001)"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/training/books/data-study-guide","label":"CompTIA Data+ Study Guide – Data Mining Techniques"},{"url":"https://www.ibm.com/topics/k-means-clustering","label":"IBM – What is K-means Clustering?"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DA0-001-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data analyst is working with a large retail dataset and needs to identify natural groupings of customers based on purchasing behavior, without any prior knowledge of how many groups exist or what they represent. Which data mining technique is MOST appropriate for this task?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data analyst is preparing a dashboard for a retail executive team to compare monthly sales performance across five product categories over a two-year period. The executives need to identify both overall trends and relative category contributions at a glance. Which chart type BEST satisfies both of these requirements simultaneously?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Stacked area chart"},{"id":"b","text":"Pie chart"},{"id":"c","text":"Scatter plot"},{"id":"d","text":"Box-and-whisker plot"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A stacked area chart displays the total value over time (showing overall trends) while also illustrating each category's proportional contribution to the whole through layered, color-coded bands — making it ideal for this use case. A pie chart (b) shows proportions at only a single point in time and cannot convey trends across a two-year period. A scatter plot (c) is used to reveal correlations between two continuous variables, not to compare categorical contributions over time. A box-and-whisker plot (d) displays statistical distribution (median, quartiles, outliers) of a dataset and does not effectively communicate temporal trends or relative category contributions in the way the executives need.$patch$, $patch$Visualization$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/training/resources/exam-objectives/comptia-data-da0-001-exam-objectives","label":"CompTIA Data+ Exam Objectives (DA0-001) – Visualization Domain"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/data","label":"CompTIA Data+ Study Guide – Chart and Graph Types"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DA0-001-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data analyst is preparing a dashboard for a retail executive team to compare monthly sales performance across five product categories over a two-year period. The executives need to identify both overall trends and relative category contributions at a glance. Which chart type BEST satisfies both of these requirements simultaneously?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data steward at a financial services company discovers that the same customer appears in the database under three slightly different name spellings, each linked to a different account number. The data quality team needs to resolve this issue while ensuring future duplicates are prevented. Which combination of data quality processes BEST addresses both the immediate resolution and long-term prevention of this problem?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Data masking to anonymize the duplicate records, followed by implementing a data retention policy"},{"id":"b","text":"Master Data Management (MDM) to create a single golden record, combined with data validation rules at the point of entry"},{"id":"c","text":"Data archiving to move duplicate records to cold storage, followed by a periodic manual audit of new entries"},{"id":"d","text":"Data encryption to secure all three records, combined with role-based access control to prevent unauthorized edits"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Master Data Management (MDM) is the discipline used to define and manage the critical data of an organization — in this case, customer identity — by creating a single authoritative 'golden record' that consolidates conflicting or duplicate entries. This directly resolves the immediate problem of three inconsistent records. Pairing MDM with data validation rules (such as format checks, deduplication logic, or fuzzy-match alerts) at the point of entry prevents future duplicates from being created in the first place. Option A (data masking) is a privacy technique unrelated to deduplication. Option C (archiving) removes data from active use but does not reconcile or merge conflicting records, and manual audits alone are not a scalable prevention mechanism. Option D (encryption and RBAC) addresses data security, not data quality or duplication.$patch$, $patch$Data Governance, Quality, and Controls$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/data","label":"CompTIA Data+ Exam Objectives (DA0-001) — Domain 5: Data Governance, Quality, and Controls"},{"url":"https://www.dama.org/cpages/body-of-knowledge","label":"DAMA International — Data Management Body of Knowledge (DMBOK): Master Data Management"},{"url":"https://www.ibm.com/topics/master-data-management","label":"IBM — What is Master Data Management?"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DA0-001-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data steward at a financial services company discovers that the same customer appears in the database under three slightly different name spellings, each linked to a different account number. The data quality team needs to resolve this issue while ensuring future duplicates are prevented. Which combination of data quality processes BEST addresses both the immediate resolution and long-term prevention of this problem?$patch$);

-- PL-300-P3: 2 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Power BI report developer is building a sales performance report for regional managers. The report contains a bar chart showing total sales by product category. Regional managers have requested the ability to dynamically change the measure displayed in the chart — switching between Total Sales, Total Profit, and Units Sold — without the developer publishing multiple versions of the report. Which Power BI feature should the developer implement to satisfy this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create a calculated column for each measure and use a slicer to filter the visual"},{"id":"b","text":"Use the Field Parameters feature to allow users to dynamically swap measures in the visual"},{"id":"c","text":"Create a What-If parameter and reference it in a DAX expression to toggle between measures"},{"id":"d","text":"Use Bookmarks combined with Selection pane to show and hide separate visuals for each measure"},{"id":"e","text":"Enable the Drill-through feature on the bar chart and configure each measure as a drill-through target"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Field Parameters (introduced in Power BI Desktop May 2022) allow report authors to create a parameter table that contains references to measures and/or columns. When a slicer is placed on the canvas bound to a Field Parameter, end users can dynamically swap which measure or field is displayed in a visual at runtime — exactly what the regional managers require. 

Option A is incorrect: calculated columns are static, row-context values stored in the model and cannot be dynamically swapped via a slicer without complex workarounds. 

Option C is incorrect: What-If parameters generate a numeric range slicer used as a variable in DAX calculations (e.g., scenario analysis); they are not designed to switch between entirely different measures in a visual. 

Option D is incorrect: Bookmarks combined with the Selection pane can simulate toggling visuals, but this requires the developer to pre-build and maintain a separate visual per measure and manage bookmarks manually — it is not a single, scalable solution and does not let users truly swap fields dynamically in one visual. 

Option E is incorrect: Drill-through is used to navigate to a detail page filtered by a data point context; it does not enable switching measures within a single visual.$patch$, $patch$Visualize and analyze the data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/power-bi/create-reports/power-bi-field-parameters","label":"Create and use Field Parameters in Power BI Desktop – Microsoft Learn"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/power-bi/transform-model/desktop-what-if","label":"What-If parameters in Power BI Desktop – Microsoft Learn"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/power-bi/create-reports/desktop-bookmarks","label":"Bookmarks in Power BI Desktop – Microsoft Learn"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'PL-300-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Power BI report developer is building a sales performance report for regional managers. The report contains a bar chart showing total sales by product category. Regional managers have requested the ability to dynamically change the measure displayed in the chart — switching between Total Sales, Total Profit, and Units Sold — without the developer publishing multiple versions of the report. Which Power BI feature should the developer implement to satisfy this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Power BI developer has published several reports and dashboards to a Premium-capacity workspace. The organization requires that report consumers always see data that is no more than one hour old. The dataset currently uses a scheduled refresh configured for twice daily. The developer needs to implement a solution that meets the freshness requirement with the least administrative effort. What should the developer configure?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable incremental refresh on the dataset and set the detect data changes option to poll every 60 minutes."},{"id":"b","text":"Upgrade the workspace to a Fabric capacity and use the OneLake integration to stream data directly."},{"id":"c","text":"Configure the dataset to use automatic page refresh with a fixed interval of 60 minutes on each report page."},{"id":"d","text":"Set the scheduled refresh frequency on the dataset to every 1 hour using the dataset settings in the Power BI service, taking advantage of the Premium-capacity allowance of up to 48 refreshes per day."},{"id":"e","text":"Create a Power Automate flow that calls the Power BI REST API to trigger a dataset refresh every hour."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["d"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option D is correct because datasets hosted in a Premium (or Premium Per User) capacity workspace support up to 48 scheduled refreshes per day — one every 30 minutes at most — compared to only 8 per day on shared capacity. Configuring an hourly schedule (24 refreshes/day) directly in the dataset's Scheduled refresh settings in the Power BI service satisfies the ≤1-hour freshness requirement with minimal ongoing administrative effort. Option A (incremental refresh with detect data changes) reduces the volume of data refreshed but does not by itself increase refresh frequency beyond what is already scheduled; it still depends on the existing twice-daily schedule unless the schedule is also changed. Option B (Fabric/OneLake streaming) would require significant architectural change and is not the least-effort solution. Option C describes automatic page refresh, which is a report-level visual polling feature for DirectQuery or streaming datasets — it does not trigger a full dataset import refresh and does not apply here. Option E (Power Automate) is a valid workaround for shared capacity but adds administrative complexity and is unnecessary when Premium capacity natively supports the required frequency.$patch$, $patch$Deploy and maintain assets$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/power-bi/connect-data/refresh-scheduled-refresh","label":"Configure scheduled refresh – Power BI | Microsoft Learn"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/power-bi/enterprise/service-premium-what-is#capacity-nodes","label":"Power BI Premium capacity – refresh rate limits | Microsoft Learn"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/power-bi/create-reports/desktop-automatic-page-refresh","label":"Automatic page refresh in Power BI | Microsoft Learn"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'PL-300-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Power BI developer has published several reports and dashboards to a Premium-capacity workspace. The organization requires that report consumers always see data that is no more than one hour old. The dataset currently uses a scheduled refresh configured for twice daily. The developer needs to implement a solution that meets the freshness requirement with the least administrative effort. What should the developer configure?$patch$);

-- DA0-001-P2: 2 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data analyst is working with a large retail dataset and needs to identify natural groupings of customers based on purchasing behavior, without any pre-labeled categories. Which data mining technique is MOST appropriate for this task?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Linear regression"},{"id":"b","text":"K-means clustering"},{"id":"c","text":"Decision tree classification"},{"id":"d","text":"Logistic regression"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$K-means clustering is an unsupervised machine learning technique used to partition data into k distinct groups (clusters) based on feature similarity — no pre-labeled output variable is required. This makes it ideal for discovering natural customer segments from raw purchasing behavior. Linear regression (a) predicts a continuous numerical outcome and requires a labeled target variable, making it a supervised technique unsuitable here. Decision tree classification (c) is a supervised technique that requires labeled training data with predefined categories. Logistic regression (d) is also a supervised classification method that predicts categorical outcomes using labeled data. Since the scenario explicitly states there are no pre-labeled categories, only an unsupervised approach like K-means clustering fits.$patch$, $patch$Data Mining$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/data","label":"CompTIA Data+ Certification Exam Objectives (DA0-001)"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/content/guides/comptia-data-study-guide","label":"CompTIA Data+ Study Guide – Data Mining Techniques"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DA0-001-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data analyst is working with a large retail dataset and needs to identify natural groupings of customers based on purchasing behavior, without any pre-labeled categories. Which data mining technique is MOST appropriate for this task?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data analyst is preparing a dashboard for the sales leadership team to compare monthly revenue performance across five regional territories over a two-year period. The analyst wants to make it easy to identify trends over time for each region while also enabling quick visual comparison between regions at any given month. Which chart type BEST satisfies both of these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Stacked bar chart showing cumulative revenue per month across all regions"},{"id":"b","text":"Multi-line chart with each region represented by a distinct colored line plotted over the 24-month period"},{"id":"c","text":"Pie chart with slices representing each region's share of total two-year revenue"},{"id":"d","text":"Scatter plot with monthly revenue on the Y-axis and territory size on the X-axis"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A multi-line chart (also called a line graph with multiple series) is the best choice here because it simultaneously displays temporal trends for each region across the 24-month period via individual lines, and allows side-by-side comparison of regions at any specific month by reading the vertical positions of each line. Option A (stacked bar) shows cumulative totals but makes it difficult to read individual region trends or precise values at a given point in time. Option C (pie chart) is a static snapshot of proportional composition and cannot convey trends over time at all. Option D (scatter plot) is designed to show correlation between two continuous variables and is not suited for tracking multiple categorical series over a time dimension.$patch$, $patch$Visualization$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/data","label":"CompTIA Data+ Exam Objectives (DA0-001) – Visualization Domain"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/blog/your-next-step-comptia-data","label":"CompTIA Data+ Study Guide – Chart and Graph Selection"},{"url":"https://www.tableau.com/learn/whitepapers/which-chart-or-graph-is-right-for-you","label":"Tableau – Which Chart or Graph is Right for You?"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DA0-001-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data analyst is preparing a dashboard for the sales leadership team to compare monthly revenue performance across five regional territories over a two-year period. The analyst wants to make it easy to identify trends over time for each region while also enabling quick visual comparison between regions at any given month. Which chart type BEST satisfies both of these requirements?$patch$);

-- PMP-P6: 2 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A project manager is leading a cross-functional team that includes members from three different departments, each with its own reporting structure and cultural norms. Two senior team members from different departments have developed a persistent conflict over task ownership that is beginning to affect team morale and delivery timelines. The project sponsor has asked the project manager to resolve the situation quickly. Which approach should the project manager take FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Escalate the conflict immediately to the functional managers of both team members so they can resolve it through their respective chains of command."},{"id":"b","text":"Meet privately with each team member to understand their perspectives, then facilitate a structured conversation between them to collaboratively define task ownership boundaries."},{"id":"c","text":"Reassign one of the conflicting team members to a different project to eliminate the interpersonal friction and protect the delivery schedule."},{"id":"d","text":"Document the conflict in the risk register and continue monitoring it while allowing the team to self-resolve without intervention."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The PMI PMBOK Guide and Agile Practice Guide emphasize that a project manager should first seek to understand all perspectives before intervening in a team conflict. Meeting privately with each party (active listening) and then facilitating a collaborative problem-solving session represents the 'Collaborate/Problem Solve' conflict resolution technique, which is generally considered the most effective first approach for persistent interpersonal conflict because it addresses root causes and fosters mutual agreement. Option (a) is incorrect because escalating immediately bypasses the project manager's responsibility to manage team dynamics and may damage trust. Option (c) is incorrect because removing a team member is a drastic measure that does not resolve the underlying issue and may harm the project. Option (d) is incorrect because a conflict that is already affecting morale and timelines requires active management, not passive monitoring.$patch$, $patch$People$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.pmi.org/pmbok-guide-standards/foundational/pmbok","label":"PMI PMBOK Guide 7th Edition – Team Performance Domain"},{"url":"https://www.pmi.org/learning/library/conflict-management-project-performance-2203","label":"PMI – Conflict Management (PMI Practice Guide Reference)"},{"url":"https://www.pmi.org/certifications/project-management-pmp/earn-the-pmp/pmp-exam-preparation/pmp-examination-content-outline","label":"PMI Examination Content Outline (ECO) 2021 – People Domain"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'PMP-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A project manager is leading a cross-functional team that includes members from three different departments, each with its own reporting structure and cultural norms. Two senior team members from different departments have developed a persistent conflict over task ownership that is beginning to affect team morale and delivery timelines. The project sponsor has asked the project manager to resolve the situation quickly. Which approach should the project manager take FIRST?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A project manager is overseeing a large software implementation project using a hybrid approach. Midway through the project, the team discovers that a critical deliverable will be delayed due to an underestimated dependency between two work packages. The project schedule baseline has already been approved. What should the project manager do FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Immediately update the project schedule baseline to reflect the new delivery date and notify the project sponsor."},{"id":"b","text":"Perform integrated change control by analyzing the schedule impact, documenting a change request, and submitting it to the change control board."},{"id":"c","text":"Instruct the team to work overtime to recover the lost time and avoid raising a change request."},{"id":"d","text":"Escalate the issue directly to the project sponsor and wait for their decision before taking any corrective action."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$When a schedule deviation is identified against an approved baseline, the project manager must follow the Integrated Change Control process (PMBOK Guide Process Group: Monitoring and Controlling). This means performing an impact analysis, documenting a formal change request, and submitting it to the Change Control Board (CCB) for review and approval before any baseline is updated. Option (a) is incorrect because baselines cannot be changed without going through formal change control — unilaterally updating the baseline bypasses governance. Option (c) is incorrect because directing overtime without formal analysis or approval ignores the root cause (the dependency gap) and may introduce quality or resource risks. Option (d) is incorrect because escalation alone is not the first step; the project manager is responsible for preparing the analysis and change request before escalation, not simply waiting for direction.$patch$, $patch$Process$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.pmi.org/pmbok-guide-standards/foundational/pmbok","label":"PMBOK Guide 7th Edition – Project Work Performance Domain & Change Control"},{"url":"https://www.pmi.org/learning/library/integrated-change-control-7297","label":"PMI – Perform Integrated Change Control (PMBOK 6th Edition, Section 4.6)"},{"url":"https://www.pmi.org/certifications/project-management-pmp/earn-the-pmp/pmp-exam-preparation/pmp-exam-content-outline","label":"PMI PMP Examination Content Outline – Process Domain"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'PMP-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A project manager is overseeing a large software implementation project using a hybrid approach. Midway through the project, the team discovers that a critical deliverable will be delayed due to an underestimated dependency between two work packages. The project schedule baseline has already been approved. What should the project manager do FIRST?$patch$);

-- SAA-C03-P2: 2 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security engineer is designing an architecture where an EC2 instance in a private subnet must retrieve sensitive database credentials at runtime without storing them in the application code or environment variables. The credentials must be automatically rotated every 30 days. Which combination of AWS services best satisfies these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Store credentials in AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store (Standard tier) as plaintext parameters and retrieve them via the EC2 instance metadata service."},{"id":"b","text":"Store credentials in AWS Secrets Manager with automatic rotation enabled via a Lambda function, and grant the EC2 instance access through an IAM role attached to the instance."},{"id":"c","text":"Store credentials in an Amazon S3 bucket with SSE-S3 encryption, restrict access using a bucket policy, and have the EC2 instance download the credentials file at startup."},{"id":"d","text":"Hardcode the credentials in the EC2 user data script and encrypt the EBS root volume with an AWS KMS customer-managed key (CMK)."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that 'AWS Secrets Manager auto-rotates secrets via Lambda; integrates with RDS/Aurora/Redshift natively.' This directly satisfies the 30-day rotation requirement without manual intervention. Attaching an IAM role to the EC2 instance (per the 'IAM roles for EC2' principle and least-privilege guidance in the source) allows the instance to call Secrets Manager APIs using temporary credentials obtained via STS — no static credentials ever exist in code or environment variables.

Option A is incorrect: Parameter Store Standard tier does not natively support automatic secret rotation, and storing credentials as plaintext violates secure-credential handling.

Option C is incorrect: Downloading credentials from S3 at startup does not provide automatic rotation every 30 days, and the file would still be exposed in the instance's filesystem after download.

Option D is incorrect: Hardcoding credentials in user data is a critical security anti-pattern — user data is accessible in plaintext via the EC2 metadata service to any process running on the instance. Encrypting the EBS volume with a CMK does not mitigate this exposure, as the running OS decrypts the volume transparently.$patch$, $patch$Design Secure Architectures$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/secretsmanager/latest/userguide/rotating-secrets.html","label":"AWS Secrets Manager – Rotate secrets automatically"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/id_roles_use_switch-role-ec2.html","label":"AWS IAM – Using IAM roles for Amazon EC2"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/secretsmanager/latest/userguide/auth-and-access.html","label":"AWS Secrets Manager – How Secrets Manager works with IAM"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'SAA-C03-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security engineer is designing an architecture where an EC2 instance in a private subnet must retrieve sensitive database credentials at runtime without storing them in the application code or environment variables. The credentials must be automatically rotated every 30 days. Which combination of AWS services best satisfies these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A solutions architect is designing a multi-tier web application on AWS. The application consists of a public-facing Application Load Balancer (ALB), a fleet of EC2 instances in a private subnet running the application tier, and an Amazon RDS MySQL instance in a separate private subnet. The security team requires that the RDS instance only accept connections from the application tier EC2 instances, and that no direct internet access to the database is permitted. Which combination of configurations BEST enforces this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Attach a security group to the RDS instance that allows inbound traffic on port 3306 only from the CIDR range of the private subnet where the EC2 instances reside."},{"id":"b","text":"Attach a security group to the RDS instance that allows inbound traffic on port 3306 only from the security group ID assigned to the application tier EC2 instances."},{"id":"c","text":"Place the RDS instance in a public subnet and use a Network ACL to block all inbound traffic except from the application tier EC2 instance IP addresses."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable RDS encryption at rest and configure IAM database authentication, then allow all inbound traffic on port 3306 within the VPC CIDR."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option B is the most precise and secure approach. AWS security groups support referencing other security groups as the inbound source. By specifying the security group ID of the application tier EC2 instances as the allowed source on port 3306, only those instances (regardless of their private IP addresses changing due to scaling) can connect to the RDS instance. This is more robust than using a subnet CIDR (option A), because a CIDR-based rule would allow any resource in that subnet—not just the application EC2 instances—to reach the database. Option C is incorrect because placing RDS in a public subnet exposes it to internet routing paths, which violates the requirement, and NACLs based on individual IP addresses are fragile with Auto Scaling. Option D is incorrect because allowing all inbound traffic on port 3306 from the entire VPC CIDR is overly permissive and does not restrict access to only the application tier; encryption at rest and IAM authentication are valuable controls but do not replace network-layer restrictions.$patch$, $patch$Design Secure Architectures$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/vpc-security-groups.html","label":"AWS Documentation – Security Groups for Your VPC"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/UserGuide/Overview.RDSSecurityGroups.html","label":"AWS Documentation – Controlling Access with Security Groups (RDS)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/security-group-rules.html","label":"AWS Documentation – Security Group Rules"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'SAA-C03-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A solutions architect is designing a multi-tier web application on AWS. The application consists of a public-facing Application Load Balancer (ALB), a fleet of EC2 instances in a private subnet running the application tier, and an Amazon RDS MySQL instance in a separate private subnet. The security team requires that the RDS instance only accept connections from the application tier EC2 instances, and that no direct internet access to the database is permitted. Which combination of configurations BEST enforces this requirement?$patch$);

-- DOP-C02-P1: 1 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team maintains a multi-stage CI/CD pipeline using AWS CodePipeline with the following stages: Source (CodeCommit), Build (CodeBuild), Staging Deploy (CodeDeploy to EC2), Integration Tests (CodeBuild), and Production Deploy (CodeDeploy to EC2). The team wants to enforce a policy where any deployment to Production is automatically blocked if integration tests report more than 2% test failure rate, AND requires a manual approval from a senior engineer only during business hours (09:00–17:00 UTC, Monday–Friday). Outside business hours, the pipeline must halt and notify the on-call engineer via Amazon SNS before any manual approval token is issued. Which combination of pipeline modifications BEST satisfies these requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Add a Lambda invoke action after the Integration Tests stage that reads the CodeBuild test reports, evaluates the failure rate threshold, and either fails the pipeline or proceeds. Add a Manual Approval action after the Lambda action, configured with an SNS topic for notifications. Deploy a second Lambda function triggered by the pipeline approval action's SNS notification that checks the current UTC time and day; if outside business hours, it immediately rejects the approval token and publishes a separate SNS message to the on-call topic."},{"id":"b","text":"Configure a CodeBuild post-build phase script that exits with a non-zero code if failure rate exceeds 2%, which automatically fails the pipeline. Add a Manual Approval action with an SNS topic. Use an Amazon EventBridge rule to detect the approval pending state, trigger a Lambda function that checks business hours, and if outside them, calls CodePipeline PutApprovalResult with a 'Rejected' result and publishes to an on-call SNS topic."},{"id":"c","text":"Add a CodeBuild action after Integration Tests that publishes test metrics to CloudWatch. Create a CloudWatch Alarm that triggers an SNS notification to the team if failure rate exceeds 2%. Add a Manual Approval action that team members monitor manually and approve or deny based on alarm state. Use an AWS Config rule to audit deployments outside business hours."},{"id":"d","text":"Use CodePipeline variables to pass the test failure rate from the Integration Tests stage. Add a Manual Approval action with a Lambda function as the approver that checks the variable value and business hours logic, automatically approving or rejecting the token based on both conditions and sending SNS notifications as needed."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option B is the best answer because it uses native CodePipeline integration points with the least operational overhead. (1) Using a non-zero CodeBuild exit code to enforce the 2% threshold is the idiomatic, lowest-overhead way to gate pipeline progression—CodeBuild natively reports test results via CodeBuild Test Reports and a failed build automatically stops the pipeline without additional resources. (2) A Manual Approval action with an SNS topic is the standard pattern for human gates in CodePipeline. (3) An EventBridge rule targeting the 'STOPPED' or approval-pending pipeline state (source: 'aws.codepipeline', detail-type: 'CodePipeline Action Execution State Change' with state 'WAITING') cleanly decouples the business-hours logic from the pipeline itself. The Lambda function triggered by EventBridge calls codepipeline:PutApprovalResult to programmatically reject the token outside hours and notifies on-call via SNS—no human needs to manually reject it. Option A is close but introduces a redundant Lambda for threshold evaluation when CodeBuild exit codes already provide this natively; it also adds an extra action in the pipeline. Option C relies on manual human observation of a CloudWatch Alarm state before approving, which does not 'automatically block' deployments—it violates the automation requirement and introduces high operational overhead. Option D is incorrect because CodePipeline Manual Approval actions do not support Lambda functions as automated approvers directly within the approval action itself; approvals must be granted via the console, CLI, or API externally (e.g., from an EventBridge-triggered Lambda), not from within the approval action configuration.$patch$, $patch$SDLC Automation$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codepipeline/latest/userguide/approvals.html","label":"AWS CodePipeline – Add a Manual Approval Action"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codepipeline/latest/userguide/approvals-approve-or-reject.html","label":"AWS CodePipeline – Automate approvals with EventBridge and Lambda"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codebuild/latest/userguide/test-reporting.html","label":"AWS CodeBuild – Test Reporting"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codepipeline/latest/userguide/detect-state-changes-cloudwatch-events.html","label":"Amazon EventBridge – CodePipeline Event Patterns"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codepipeline/latest/APIReference/API_PutApprovalResult.html","label":"AWS CodePipeline PutApprovalResult API Reference"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team maintains a multi-stage CI/CD pipeline using AWS CodePipeline with the following stages: Source (CodeCommit), Build (CodeBuild), Staging Deploy (CodeDeploy to EC2), Integration Tests (CodeBuild), and Production Deploy (CodeDeploy to EC2). The team wants to enforce a policy where any deployment to Production is automatically blocked if integration tests report more than 2% test failure rate, AND requires a manual approval from a senior engineer only during business hours (09:00–17:00 UTC, Monday–Friday). Outside business hours, the pipeline must halt and notify the on-call engineer via Amazon SNS before any manual approval token is issued. Which combination of pipeline modifications BEST satisfies these requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$);

-- DOP-C02-P2: 1 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team maintains a microservices application deployed on Amazon ECS. They use AWS CodePipeline with the following stages: Source (CodeCommit) → Build (CodeBuild) → Staging Deploy (CodeDeploy) → Approval → Production Deploy (CodeDeploy). The team wants to enforce the following requirements:

1. Any feature branch push must trigger an isolated pipeline run that performs build and unit tests only — it must NOT deploy to any environment.
2. The main branch pipeline must run the full sequence including deployments.
3. Test reports from CodeBuild must be published and visible in the AWS Console so that the manual approver can review them before approving the production deployment.
4. If a CodeBuild unit test fails on the main branch, the pipeline must stop immediately and notify the on-call engineer via Amazon SNS.

Which combination of AWS-native configurations BEST satisfies ALL four requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create two separate CodePipeline pipelines: one triggered by feature branch changes (Source → Build only) and one triggered by the main branch (Source → Build → Staging Deploy → Approval → Production Deploy). In the main-branch CodeBuild project, configure a test report group using the `reports` section of the buildspec.yml and publish results to CodeBuild Test Reports. Add an Amazon EventBridge rule that matches the `codebuild-build-state-change` event with `buildStatus = FAILED` and targets an SNS topic to notify the on-call engineer."},{"id":"b","text":"Use a single CodePipeline with a branch condition at the Source stage. Add a Lambda invoke action after the Build stage that reads the source branch from the pipeline execution context and skips downstream stages for feature branches. Configure CodeBuild to write JUnit XML files to an S3 bucket, and create a separate Lambda function triggered on a schedule to poll S3 and send SNS notifications when a failed test report is found."},{"id":"c","text":"Create two separate CodePipeline pipelines differentiated by branch. In each CodeBuild project, use `aws codebuild start-build` inside the buildspec to recursively trigger downstream builds. Store test results in DynamoDB and create an AWS Step Functions state machine to evaluate test outcomes and send SNS notifications on failure."},{"id":"d","text":"Use a single CodePipeline with a manual gate at the beginning that requires an operator to specify the target environment. Configure CodeBuild to upload test result HTML to S3 with a pre-signed URL included in the CodePipeline approval notification email. Use Amazon CloudWatch Alarms on CodeBuild metrics to trigger SNS on failure."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option A is correct because it directly maps each requirement to a purpose-built AWS-native feature with minimal operational overhead:

1. **Feature branch isolation**: Two separate pipelines — one for feature branches (Build only) and one for main — is the recommended AWS pattern. CodePipeline natively supports per-branch pipeline triggers via CodeCommit branch filters on the Source action, avoiding the need for custom Lambda logic to conditionally skip stages.

2. **Full main branch pipeline**: The main pipeline includes all five stages as required without custom workarounds.

3. **Test report visibility**: CodeBuild Test Reports (configured via the `reports` block in buildspec.yml) natively publish JUnit/Cucumber/TestNG results directly into the CodeBuild console. Approvers can navigate to the CodeBuild run linked from the pipeline and review detailed pass/fail results — no S3 polling or external tooling needed.

4. **Immediate SNS notification on failure**: EventBridge natively captures `CodeBuild Build State Change` events. Filtering on `buildStatus = FAILED` and routing to SNS is a serverless, zero-maintenance pattern that fires in near real-time the moment a build fails.

**Why the other options are wrong:**
- **Option B** uses a single pipeline with a Lambda workaround to skip stages, which adds complexity and is not how CodePipeline natively handles multi-branch workflows. The scheduled Lambda polling S3 for test failures adds latency and operational overhead.
- **Option C** introduces recursive `start-build` calls (an anti-pattern creating hard-to-trace execution chains) and unnecessary use of DynamoDB + Step Functions for a problem solved natively by EventBridge + SNS.
- **Option D** relies on a manual operator gate at the start (violating automated pipeline triggering), pre-signed URL generation (brittle and time-limited), and CloudWatch Alarms on CodeBuild metrics — which are aggregate metrics and may not fire per-build-failure with the required immediacy or granularity.$patch$, $patch$SDLC Automation$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codepipeline/latest/userguide/pipelines-create.html","label":"AWS CodePipeline – Create a pipeline with multiple source actions"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codebuild/latest/userguide/test-reporting.html","label":"AWS CodeBuild – Working with test reporting"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codebuild/latest/userguide/sample-build-notifications.html","label":"AWS CodeBuild – Build notifications using Amazon EventBridge"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codebuild/latest/userguide/build-notifications.html#build-notifications-ref","label":"Amazon EventBridge – CodeBuild event types and patterns"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codepipeline/latest/userguide/best-practices.html","label":"AWS CodePipeline – Automating with pipelines and branches (best practices)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team maintains a microservices application deployed on Amazon ECS. They use AWS CodePipeline with the following stages: Source (CodeCommit) → Build (CodeBuild) → Staging Deploy (CodeDeploy) → Approval → Production Deploy (CodeDeploy). The team wants to enforce the following requirements:

1. Any feature branch push must trigger an isolated pipeline run that performs build and unit tests only — it must NOT deploy to any environment.
2. The main branch pipeline must run the full sequence including deployments.
3. Test reports from CodeBuild must be published and visible in the AWS Console so that the manual approver can review them before approving the production deployment.
4. If a CodeBuild unit test fails on the main branch, the pipeline must stop immediately and notify the on-call engineer via Amazon SNS.

Which combination of AWS-native configurations BEST satisfies ALL four requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$);

-- ACE-P1: 1 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Your organization has just been granted access to Google Cloud and you are tasked with setting up the initial environment. You need to create a new project, ensure that billing is enabled, and activate the Compute Engine API before deploying any virtual machines. After creating the project in the Google Cloud Console, which sequence of steps correctly completes the remaining prerequisites in the right order?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable the Compute Engine API first, then link a billing account to the project."},{"id":"b","text":"Link a billing account to the project first, then enable the Compute Engine API."},{"id":"c","text":"Create a service account first, link it to a billing account, then enable the Compute Engine API."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable the Compute Engine API first, then create an organization resource, then link a billing account."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Before enabling most Google Cloud APIs, a billing account must be linked to the project, because many services (including Compute Engine) require an active billing account to function. Once billing is linked, you can navigate to 'APIs & Services > Library' and enable the Compute Engine API. Option (a) is incorrect because attempting to enable Compute Engine without an attached billing account will either fail or result in an unusable state. Option (c) is incorrect because creating a service account is not a prerequisite for enabling an API; service accounts are used for authentication of workloads, not for API activation. Option (d) is incorrect because the organization resource is part of the resource hierarchy set up at the Google Workspace or Cloud Identity level and is not a step performed after project creation as a prerequisite for enabling APIs.$patch$, $patch$Setting up a cloud solution environment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/resource-manager/docs/creating-managing-projects","label":"Google Cloud – Creating and managing projects"},{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/billing/docs/how-to/modify-project","label":"Google Cloud – Enable billing for a project"},{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/apis/docs/getting-started#enabling_an_api","label":"Google Cloud – Enabling APIs"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'ACE-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Your organization has just been granted access to Google Cloud and you are tasked with setting up the initial environment. You need to create a new project, ensure that billing is enabled, and activate the Compute Engine API before deploying any virtual machines. After creating the project in the Google Cloud Console, which sequence of steps correctly completes the remaining prerequisites in the right order?$patch$);

-- SK0-005-P1: 1 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server administrator receives alerts that a Windows Server 2022 system is experiencing intermittent blue screen errors (BSODs) with the stop code MEMORY_MANAGEMENT. The server has four 16 GB DDR4 ECC RAM modules installed across all available DIMM slots. The errors appear most frequently during peak workload hours. Which sequence of troubleshooting steps is MOST appropriate to isolate the faulty component?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Immediately replace all four RAM modules with new ones, then monitor the server for 48 hours to confirm stability."},{"id":"b","text":"Run the Windows Memory Diagnostic tool, then if errors are found, test each DIMM individually by reseating one module at a time in a known-good slot and re-running the diagnostic after each swap."},{"id":"c","text":"Reinstall the operating system to eliminate software corruption as the root cause, then evaluate hardware only if BSODs persist."},{"id":"d","text":"Update the server firmware and BIOS to the latest version, then increase the virtual memory page file size to compensate for the failing RAM."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option B is correct because it follows a systematic, evidence-based troubleshooting methodology. Running the Windows Memory Diagnostic (or a tool like MemTest86) first confirms that RAM is the actual source of the MEMORY_MANAGEMENT BSOD, rather than a driver or OS issue. After confirming a memory fault, isolating each DIMM individually in a known-good slot narrows the failure to a specific module, minimizing unnecessary component replacement and downtime. Option A is incorrect because replacing all modules at once is wasteful and does not identify which module is faulty. Option C is incorrect because a MEMORY_MANAGEMENT stop code with ECC RAM strongly points to a hardware fault; reinstalling the OS addresses software-layer problems and wastes time without addressing the likely root cause. Option D is incorrect because expanding the page file does not fix faulty physical RAM and could mask the problem temporarily while leaving a dangerous instability in production.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/drivers/debugger/bug-check-0x1a--memory-management","label":"Microsoft Learn – MEMORY_MANAGEMENT Bug Check (0x0000001A)"},{"url":"https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/diagnosing-memory-problems-on-your-computer-6c58570f-9b0d-8f0e-0e5d-2c960e56e8e8","label":"Microsoft Support – Using Windows Memory Diagnostic Tool"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/server","label":"CompTIA Server+ SK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'SK0-005-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server administrator receives alerts that a Windows Server 2022 system is experiencing intermittent blue screen errors (BSODs) with the stop code MEMORY_MANAGEMENT. The server has four 16 GB DDR4 ECC RAM modules installed across all available DIMM slots. The errors appear most frequently during peak workload hours. Which sequence of troubleshooting steps is MOST appropriate to isolate the faulty component?$patch$);

-- XK0-005-P1: 1 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator needs to change the default runlevel so that the system boots into multi-user mode with networking but without a graphical interface. The system uses systemd as its init system. Which command should the administrator run to persistently set this target?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"systemctl set-default multi-user.target"},{"id":"b","text":"systemctl isolate multi-user.target"},{"id":"c","text":"systemctl enable multi-user.target"},{"id":"d","text":"ln -sf /lib/systemd/system/multi-user.target /etc/systemd/system/default.target"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The command 'systemctl set-default multi-user.target' persistently sets the default boot target by creating a symlink at /etc/systemd/system/default.target pointing to multi-user.target, which corresponds to runlevel 3 (multi-user with networking, no GUI). This change survives reboots. Option B ('systemctl isolate') switches to the target immediately for the current session only without persisting across reboots. Option C ('systemctl enable') enables individual units to start at boot but does not set the default target. Option D manually creates the symlink and would technically work, but it is not the recommended administrative method and bypasses systemd's management layer — 'systemctl set-default' is the correct and idiomatic approach.$patch$, $patch$System Management$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemd.target.html","label":"systemd.target — systemd documentation (freedesktop.org)"},{"url":"https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#set-default%20TARGET","label":"systemctl man page — set-default"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'XK0-005-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator needs to change the default runlevel so that the system boots into multi-user mode with networking but without a graphical interface. The system uses systemd as its init system. Which command should the administrator run to persistently set this target?$patch$);

-- XK0-005-P6: 1 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator needs to change the default target on a systemd-based server from graphical.target to multi-user.target so that the system boots into a non-graphical environment after the next reboot. Which command will accomplish this persistently?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"systemctl set-default multi-user.target"},{"id":"b","text":"systemctl isolate multi-user.target"},{"id":"c","text":"systemctl enable multi-user.target"},{"id":"d","text":"systemctl default multi-user.target"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The command 'systemctl set-default multi-user.target' persistently changes the default boot target by updating the symbolic link at /etc/systemd/system/default.target to point to multi-user.target. This change survives reboots. Option B ('systemctl isolate') switches the running system to that target immediately but does NOT persist across reboots — it is used for runtime-only transitions. Option C ('systemctl enable') is used to enable unit files to start at boot, but it is not the correct mechanism for setting the default target. Option D ('systemctl default') is not a valid systemctl subcommand and will produce an error.$patch$, $patch$System Management$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#set-default%20TARGET","label":"systemd Documentation – systemctl set-default"},{"url":"https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/configuring_basic_system_settings/assembly_working-with-systemd-targets_configuring-basic-system-settings#proc_setting-the-default-systemd-target_assembly_working-with-systemd-targets","label":"Red Hat – Changing the default systemd target"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'XK0-005-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator needs to change the default target on a systemd-based server from graphical.target to multi-user.target so that the system boots into a non-graphical environment after the next reboot. Which command will accomplish this persistently?$patch$);

-- DA0-001-P1: 1 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data analyst is working with a large retail organization that stores transactional records in a relational database, product images in an object storage system, and customer sentiment notes in flat text files. Which term BEST describes the combination of these three storage types?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Structured data"},{"id":"b","text":"Polyglot persistence"},{"id":"c","text":"Data lake"},{"id":"d","text":"Master data management"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Polyglot persistence refers to the practice of using multiple different data storage technologies — each chosen based on the nature of the data and how it is accessed — within a single system or organization. In this scenario, the organization uses a relational database (structured transactional data), object storage (unstructured binary data such as images), and flat text files (semi-structured or unstructured text), which is a classic example of polyglot persistence. Option A ('Structured data') is incorrect because not all three sources are structured; images and text files are unstructured. Option C ('Data lake') is a specific architecture that centralizes raw data in a single repository, which is not described here. Option D ('Master data management') refers to processes for ensuring consistency of critical shared data entities across an enterprise, not a storage-type combination.$patch$, $patch$Data Concepts and Environments$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/data","label":"CompTIA Data+ Exam Objectives (DA0-001) — Data Concepts and Environments"},{"url":"https://martinfowler.com/bliki/PolyglotPersistence.html","label":"Martin Fowler — Polyglot Persistence"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DA0-001-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data analyst is working with a large retail organization that stores transactional records in a relational database, product images in an object storage system, and customer sentiment notes in flat text files. Which term BEST describes the combination of these three storage types?$patch$);

-- DA0-001-P3: 1 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data analyst is working with a dataset stored in a relational database where each table represents a distinct entity and relationships between entities are enforced through foreign keys. The analyst needs to retrieve data that spans multiple tables. Which of the following concepts BEST describes the structural design principle being used in this database?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Normalization"},{"id":"b","text":"Data warehousing"},{"id":"c","text":"Data virtualization"},{"id":"d","text":"Columnar storage"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Normalization is the process of organizing a relational database to reduce data redundancy and improve data integrity by dividing data into related tables and enforcing relationships through primary and foreign keys. This is the structural design principle described in the scenario. Data warehousing refers to a system for analytical reporting and is not specifically about relational table design. Data virtualization abstracts data from its physical location to provide a unified view without moving data. Columnar storage is a physical storage method used in analytical databases where data is stored by column rather than by row, which is unrelated to the relational design principle described.$patch$, $patch$Data Concepts and Environments$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/training/resources/exam-objectives/comptia-data-da0-001-exam-objectives","label":"CompTIA Data+ Exam Objectives (DA0-001) – Data Concepts and Environments"},{"url":"https://www.ibm.com/topics/database-normalization","label":"IBM – What is Database Normalization?"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DA0-001-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data analyst is working with a dataset stored in a relational database where each table represents a distinct entity and relationships between entities are enforced through foreign keys. The analyst needs to retrieve data that spans multiple tables. Which of the following concepts BEST describes the structural design principle being used in this database?$patch$);

-- DA0-001-P5: 1 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data engineer is designing a new pipeline and must choose between a relational database and a document store for storing customer order records. The orders have a highly variable structure: some include digital-only items, others include physical shipments with nested address sub-objects, and future fields are expected to be added frequently without schema migrations. Which statement BEST describes why a document store would be more appropriate than a relational database for this use case?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Document stores enforce strict ACID transactions across all nodes, making them safer for financial order data than relational databases."},{"id":"b","text":"Document stores use a schema-on-read approach, allowing each record to contain different fields and nested structures without requiring predefined table schemas or costly migrations."},{"id":"c","text":"Document stores always provide faster query performance than relational databases because they do not use structured query language."},{"id":"d","text":"Document stores eliminate the need for any indexing strategy because all documents are stored in a flat key-value format."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Document stores (such as MongoDB or Couchbase) follow a schema-on-read model, meaning the structure of each document is interpreted at query time rather than enforced at write time. This makes them well-suited for data with variable or evolving structures—such as orders that contain different nested fields depending on order type—because new fields can be added to individual documents without altering a global schema or running migrations. Option A is incorrect: while some document stores offer ACID guarantees, this is not a universal characteristic and is not the primary reason to choose a document store over a relational database for variable-schema data. Option C is incorrect: document stores do not universally outperform relational databases in query speed; performance depends heavily on workload, indexing, and query patterns. Option D is incorrect: document stores absolutely support and benefit from indexing strategies; they do not store all data in a flat key-value format—that description applies to key-value stores, a different NoSQL category.$patch$, $patch$Data Concepts and Environments$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/data","label":"CompTIA Data+ Exam Objectives (DA0-001) – Data Concepts and Environments"},{"url":"https://www.mongodb.com/document-databases","label":"MongoDB Documentation – What is a Document Database?"},{"url":"https://www.ibm.com/topics/nosql-databases","label":"IBM – NoSQL Databases Explained"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DA0-001-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data engineer is designing a new pipeline and must choose between a relational database and a document store for storing customer order records. The orders have a highly variable structure: some include digital-only items, others include physical shipments with nested address sub-objects, and future fields are expected to be added frequently without schema migrations. Which statement BEST describes why a document store would be more appropriate than a relational database for this use case?$patch$);

-- DEA-C01-P1: 1 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data engineering team needs to ingest streaming clickstream data from a web application into Amazon S3 for downstream analytics. The data arrives at a rate of approximately 8,000 records per second, and the team requires that the raw data be partitioned in S3 by date and hour for efficient querying. They also need to automatically convert the incoming JSON records to Apache Parquet format before storing them. Which AWS service combination best satisfies these requirements with the least operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Use Amazon Kinesis Data Streams to capture the clickstream data, then configure an AWS Lambda function triggered by the stream to convert JSON to Parquet and write partitioned objects to Amazon S3."},{"id":"b","text":"Use Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose (Amazon Data Firehose) with dynamic partitioning enabled, configure the built-in record format conversion to Parquet using an AWS Glue Data Catalog table schema, and set the S3 prefix to include date and hour partition keys."},{"id":"c","text":"Use AWS Database Migration Service (DMS) to replicate the clickstream records into an Amazon RDS instance, then run a scheduled AWS Glue ETL job every hour to convert JSON to Parquet and export partitioned data to Amazon S3."},{"id":"d","text":"Use Amazon Managed Streaming for Apache Kafka (Amazon MSK) to ingest the data, then deploy a self-managed Apache Spark Structured Streaming application on Amazon EC2 to convert JSON to Parquet and write to Amazon S3."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Amazon Data Firehose (formerly Kinesis Data Firehose) is the correct choice because it is a fully managed, serverless service purpose-built for loading streaming data into destinations like Amazon S3 with minimal operational overhead. Its dynamic partitioning feature allows records to be automatically routed into S3 prefixes based on data attributes (e.g., year/month/day/hour extracted from the record), satisfying the partitioning requirement. The built-in record format conversion feature leverages an AWS Glue Data Catalog schema to transparently convert incoming JSON to Parquet or ORC before delivery—no custom code required. Option A (Kinesis Data Streams + Lambda) requires custom code for format conversion and partitioning logic, adding operational complexity. Option C (DMS + RDS + Glue) is designed for database migration, not streaming ingestion, and introduces unnecessary latency and cost. Option D (MSK + self-managed Spark on EC2) can achieve the goal but requires significant infrastructure management, contradicting the 'least operational overhead' requirement.$patch$, $patch$Data Ingestion and Transformation$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/firehose/latest/dev/dynamic-partitioning.html","label":"Amazon Data Firehose – Dynamic Partitioning"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/firehose/latest/dev/record-format-conversion.html","label":"Amazon Data Firehose – Record Format Conversion"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/firehose/latest/dev/what-is-this-service.html","label":"Amazon Data Firehose – What Is Amazon Data Firehose?"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DEA-C01-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data engineering team needs to ingest streaming clickstream data from a web application into Amazon S3 for downstream analytics. The data arrives at a rate of approximately 8,000 records per second, and the team requires that the raw data be partitioned in S3 by date and hour for efficient querying. They also need to automatically convert the incoming JSON records to Apache Parquet format before storing them. Which AWS service combination best satisfies these requirements with the least operational overhead?$patch$);

-- DP-100-P1: 1 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data scientist at Contoso Ltd. is planning a new machine learning project on Azure. The team needs to track experiments, manage datasets, register models, and collaborate across multiple workspaces in different Azure regions. Which Azure service should the data scientist provision FIRST to serve as the central hub for all these machine learning activities?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Azure Databricks workspace"},{"id":"b","text":"Azure Machine Learning workspace"},{"id":"c","text":"Azure Synapse Analytics workspace"},{"id":"d","text":"Azure AI Foundry hub"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$An Azure Machine Learning workspace is the foundational resource for all Azure ML activities. It provides a centralized place to track experiments, manage datasets and datastores, register models, create compute targets, and collaborate with team members. It integrates with Azure storage, container registry, key vault, and Application Insights automatically upon creation. Azure Databricks is a Spark-based analytics platform that can integrate with Azure ML but is not the central hub for ML lifecycle management. Azure Synapse Analytics is primarily a data integration and analytics service focused on big data and SQL workloads. Azure AI Foundry (formerly Azure AI Studio) is oriented toward generative AI and Azure AI Services rather than the traditional ML lifecycle tracked by DP-100 tooling.$patch$, $patch$Design and prepare a machine learning solution$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/machine-learning/concept-workspace","label":"What is an Azure Machine Learning workspace? – Microsoft Learn"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/machine-learning/how-to-manage-workspace","label":"Create and manage Azure Machine Learning workspaces – Microsoft Learn"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DP-100-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data scientist at Contoso Ltd. is planning a new machine learning project on Azure. The team needs to track experiments, manage datasets, register models, and collaborate across multiple workspaces in different Azure regions. Which Azure service should the data scientist provision FIRST to serve as the central hub for all these machine learning activities?$patch$);

-- DP-100-P2: 1 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data science team at a retail company is planning a new machine learning project on Azure. The team needs to select an Azure Machine Learning compute target that supports both interactive development in Jupyter notebooks and the ability to scale to multi-node distributed training jobs when required. The solution must minimize idle-time costs when no jobs are running. Which compute target best satisfies all of these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Azure Machine Learning Compute Instance"},{"id":"b","text":"Azure Machine Learning Compute Cluster"},{"id":"c","text":"Azure Kubernetes Service (AKS) cluster attached to Azure Machine Learning"},{"id":"d","text":"Azure Databricks cluster attached to Azure Machine Learning"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$An Azure Machine Learning Compute Cluster satisfies all three requirements. It supports interactive development through submitted jobs and notebook execution, scales automatically from 0 to a configured maximum number of nodes (multi-node distributed training), and scales back down to zero nodes when idle — eliminating compute costs between jobs. A Compute Instance (option A) is a single-node VM optimized for interactive notebook development but does not natively support multi-node distributed training or auto-scale to zero nodes (it must be manually stopped). An AKS cluster (option C) is primarily designed for model deployment/inference, not iterative training workloads, and does not scale to zero by default. An attached Azure Databricks cluster (option D) can run distributed training, but it requires a separate Databricks workspace, incurs additional costs, and is not the purpose-built Azure ML training compute — making it a less optimal choice compared to a native Compute Cluster.$patch$, $patch$Design and prepare a machine learning solution$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/machine-learning/concept-compute-target","label":"Azure Machine Learning compute targets overview"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/machine-learning/how-to-create-attach-compute-cluster","label":"Create an Azure Machine Learning compute cluster"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/machine-learning/concept-compute-instance","label":"Azure Machine Learning compute instance overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DP-100-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data science team at a retail company is planning a new machine learning project on Azure. The team needs to select an Azure Machine Learning compute target that supports both interactive development in Jupyter notebooks and the ability to scale to multi-node distributed training jobs when required. The solution must minimize idle-time costs when no jobs are running. Which compute target best satisfies all of these requirements?$patch$);

-- DP-300-P2: 1 questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Your organization is migrating an on-premises SQL Server 2019 workload to Azure. The database is 4 TB in size, requires support for in-memory OLTP tables, and must support read scale-out to offload reporting queries without additional licensing costs. The solution must minimize downtime during migration. Which Azure SQL deployment option and service tier combination best meets all of these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Azure SQL Database – Hyperscale service tier with one named replica"},{"id":"b","text":"Azure SQL Managed Instance – Business Critical service tier"},{"id":"c","text":"Azure SQL Managed Instance – General Purpose service tier"},{"id":"d","text":"Azure SQL Database – General Purpose service tier (vCore) with geo-replication"},{"id":"e","text":"SQL Server on Azure Virtual Machines – Enterprise Edition with Always On Availability Groups"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Azure SQL Managed Instance – Business Critical tier satisfies every stated requirement. (1) Full SQL Server engine compatibility means in-memory OLTP (memory-optimized tables and natively compiled stored procedures) is fully supported, whereas General Purpose tier does not support in-memory OLTP. (2) Business Critical automatically provisions a built-in Always On read-only replica that can serve reporting workloads at no extra license cost, fulfilling the read scale-out requirement. (3) A 4 TB database fits within the Business Critical maximum (up to 4 TB per database on current SKUs). (4) Azure Database Migration Service (DMS) supports online migrations to SQL Managed Instance, minimizing downtime. Option A (Hyperscale) supports large databases and read replicas but is a single-database PaaS offering and does not provide full Managed Instance compatibility for workloads that require instance-scoped features. Option C (Managed Instance – General Purpose) does not support in-memory OLTP tables. Option D (SQL Database – General Purpose) lacks in-memory OLTP support and geo-replication does not provide a no-cost read replica in the same region for scale-out. Option E (SQL Server on Azure VMs – Enterprise) could technically work but requires additional effort for HA configuration and does not represent the platform-as-a-service path that minimizes administrative overhead and migration downtime compared to Managed Instance with DMS.$patch$, $patch$Plan and implement data platform resources$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-sql/managed-instance/sql-managed-instance-paas-overview#service-tiers","label":"Azure SQL Managed Instance service tiers overview – Microsoft Learn"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-sql/in-memory-oltp-overview","label":"In-memory OLTP technologies for higher performance – Azure SQL Managed Instance"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-sql/database/read-scale-out","label":"Read scale-out with Business Critical tier – Microsoft Learn"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/dms/tutorial-sql-server-managed-instance-online-ads","label":"Migrate SQL Server to Azure SQL Managed Instance using DMS – Microsoft Learn"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DP-300-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Your organization is migrating an on-premises SQL Server 2019 workload to Azure. The database is 4 TB in size, requires support for in-memory OLTP tables, and must support read scale-out to offload reporting queries without additional licensing costs. The solution must minimize downtime during migration. Which Azure SQL deployment option and service tier combination best meets all of these requirements?$patch$);

